WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:10.840
[Amit Varma]: All of us are wired for empathy but we express it in different ways. When we see the suffering

00:00:10.840 --> 00:00:15.640
[Amit Varma]: of others, some of us stay silent and mind our own business. Some of us express our sympathy

00:00:15.640 --> 00:00:20.260
[Amit Varma]: or our outrage if there is cause for outrage. Talk is cheap and these days posturing is

00:00:20.260 --> 00:00:25.280
[Amit Varma]: easy, especially on social media. Some of us go a step further and take some kind of

00:00:25.280 --> 00:00:29.840
[Amit Varma]: initiative. Start an online petition, maybe donate to a good cause, share information

00:00:29.840 --> 00:00:34.920
[Amit Varma]: about how to help. Some of us even go out in the real world to try and make a difference.

00:00:34.920 --> 00:00:40.600
[Amit Varma]: Maybe we go to marches or protest rallies, maybe file a PIL or an RTI application. But

00:00:40.600 --> 00:00:45.840
[Amit Varma]: a few people decide to dedicate their lives to helping others. They fight to leave the

00:00:45.840 --> 00:00:50.720
[Amit Varma]: world a better place than it was when they got there. They don't know if they'll succeed.

00:00:50.720 --> 00:01:08.240
[Unknown]: They do it because they have to.

00:01:08.240 --> 00:01:12.600
[Amit Varma]: Welcome to The Scene and the Unseen. My guest for today is Kavita Krishnan, feminist, activist,

00:01:12.600 --> 00:01:17.680
[Amit Varma]: politician, communist. Kavita is on the Politburo of the CPIML, the Communist Party of India,

00:01:17.680 --> 00:01:23.160
[Amit Varma]: Marxist-Leninist, but is best known for her fearless feminism. She burst into national

00:01:23.160 --> 00:01:28.760
[Amit Varma]: attention when a powerful speech by her in the anti-rape protests of 2012 went viral.

00:01:28.760 --> 00:01:32.640
[Amit Varma]: She went on to write a fabulous book called Fearless Freedom, which lays out the sorry

00:01:32.640 --> 00:01:38.400
[Amit Varma]: state of women in India, but also articulates a feminist manifesto of sorts, which has found

00:01:38.400 --> 00:01:43.440
[Amit Varma]: much resonance among young people. Now, Kavita is a card-carrying communist, but that does

00:01:43.440 --> 00:01:48.360
[Amit Varma]: not make her a dogmatic leftist, as the stereotype goes. Over the years that I have followed

00:01:48.360 --> 00:01:53.960
[Amit Varma]: her work, I have found that she is driven by empathy and outrage, and not by ideology

00:01:53.960 --> 00:01:59.480
[Amit Varma]: or dogma. She is always open to dialogue, and her loyalty is to her principles, and

00:01:59.480 --> 00:02:04.160
[Amit Varma]: not to any of the political tribes around us. She was an outspoken critic of the acquittals

00:02:04.160 --> 00:02:08.860
[Amit Varma]: of Mahmud Faruqi and Tarun Tejpal, who had more or less confessed to rape, but were let

00:02:08.860 --> 00:02:13.980
[Amit Varma]: off by the courts. Many hypocritical Delhi elites, who call themselves liberal, supported

00:02:13.980 --> 00:02:19.000
[Amit Varma]: Faruqi and Tejpal, and attacked Krishnan for her views. But I share those views, and I

00:02:19.000 --> 00:02:24.120
[Amit Varma]: admire how Kavita takes no prisoners. I was delighted when she agreed to come on the show,

00:02:24.120 --> 00:02:28.480
[Amit Varma]: because I wanted to understand these feminist struggles a little better, not just in terms

00:02:28.480 --> 00:02:33.480
[Amit Varma]: of theories and ideas, because we can all read books and signal virtue on social media,

00:02:33.480 --> 00:02:38.400
[Amit Varma]: but in terms of the struggles on the ground. Our conversation lasted more than four hours,

00:02:38.400 --> 00:02:42.720
[Amit Varma]: and it felt way too short. I didn't cover a lot of the ground I wanted to, and yet I

00:02:42.720 --> 00:02:48.160
[Amit Varma]: got so much food for thought. I also made a conscious decision before this episode that

00:02:48.160 --> 00:02:53.760
[Amit Varma]: I would not get into arguments about Marx or communism or the Soviet Union or Cuba under

00:02:53.760 --> 00:02:59.520
[Amit Varma]: Castro, all of whom Kavita admires, and I absolutely don't. I didn't want to get combative

00:02:59.520 --> 00:03:05.240
[Amit Varma]: about ideology in this conversation. I wanted to focus on learning from her remarkable personal

00:03:05.240 --> 00:03:11.080
[Amit Varma]: journey as well as her powerful work as a feminist. This was such a rewarding conversation

00:03:11.080 --> 00:03:15.440
[Amit Varma]: for me. But before we get to it, let's take a quick commercial break.

