00:04:51.800 --> 00:04:54.720
[Amit Varma]: It's a pleasure.

00:04:54.720 --> 00:04:59.400
[Amit Varma]: So you know, before we start talking about our subject for the day and so on, tell me

00:04:59.400 --> 00:05:03.320
[Amit Varma]: a little bit about how the last few months have been for you. Like it's kind of been

00:05:03.320 --> 00:05:07.960
[Amit Varma]: tough for all of us. And you know, how's it been for you? How are you doing?

00:05:07.960 --> 00:05:12.800
[Guest]: It's actually been very, very, very difficult. You know, we all went through such a terrible

00:05:12.800 --> 00:05:18.560
[Guest]: time with the second wave of the pandemic. And I think it came really close home for

00:05:18.560 --> 00:05:23.680
[Guest]: everybody, you know, it didn't remain something abstract and remote. So of course, one of

00:05:23.680 --> 00:05:30.080
[Guest]: the things was that I actually did get COVID. So it was reasonably mild and happened about

00:05:30.080 --> 00:05:36.080
[Guest]: a couple of weeks after my first dose of the vaccine. So maybe that kept it mild. But still,

00:05:36.080 --> 00:05:42.280
[Guest]: it was, you know, stressful, of course, because you worry. And I still have some of the after

00:05:42.280 --> 00:05:47.440
[Guest]: effects as in, you know, insomnia and all of that. But I think beyond that, I think

00:05:47.440 --> 00:05:56.720
[Guest]: the losses of people, I think in such a short time, we lost people, I lost people who were

00:05:56.720 --> 00:06:02.520
[Guest]: very close comrades, absolutely, you know, indispensable people who I could not have

00:06:02.520 --> 00:06:10.500
[Guest]: imagined losing at this point. Very good friends, very, very young people, colleagues of my

00:06:10.500 --> 00:06:15.800
[Guest]: partner, as well as, you know, other young teachers whom I have known in Delhi University

00:06:15.800 --> 00:06:21.840
[Guest]: and all work about my age. So all of those were very, very difficult to deal with. And

00:06:21.840 --> 00:06:28.040
[Guest]: I think for me, the most challenging thing was that because I got COVID, I was not able

00:06:28.040 --> 00:06:34.640
[Guest]: to really step out and be in the middle of any of the relief work physically. And I think

00:06:34.640 --> 00:06:41.380
[Guest]: that was the only thing which may have actually prevented, might prevent one from feeling

00:06:41.380 --> 00:06:45.920
[Guest]: as helpless and as bad, you know, because you are at least able to. Last year, during

00:06:45.920 --> 00:06:50.560
[Guest]: the lockdown, I know that that's how we got through it, because this terrible scene of

00:06:50.560 --> 00:06:55.480
[Guest]: the migrant workers, you know, walking and dying. The only thing which we did night and

00:06:55.480 --> 00:06:59.200
[Guest]: day at that time was just trying to keep in touch with as many as we could and getting

00:06:59.200 --> 00:07:03.960
[Guest]: relief out. So this time, not personally not being able to do that, and there were others

00:07:03.960 --> 00:07:12.520
[Guest]: doing it, but that was that made it even harder. But I mean, we picked ourselves up now.

00:07:12.520 --> 00:07:17.320
[Amit Varma]: Yeah, it's interesting, you know, you use the word helpless, because what struck me

00:07:17.320 --> 00:07:22.640
[Amit Varma]: was that early last year, it was probably a time of a certain kind of hope, like even

00:07:22.640 --> 00:07:25.960
[Amit Varma]: though the economy was doing really badly, things were bleak, but there was hope because

00:07:25.960 --> 00:07:31.840
[Amit Varma]: in the CAA protest, we saw a lot of people kind of come together, you know, we saw young

00:07:31.840 --> 00:07:36.760
[Amit Varma]: people throughout the country protesting, waving the constitution over a thunk and all

00:07:36.760 --> 00:07:41.040
[Amit Varma]: of that happening and suddenly boom, you know, COVID happens and, and then there's nothing

00:07:41.040 --> 00:07:46.480
[Amit Varma]: you can do, like, you know, where do you protest? What do you do? It was just so strikingly

00:07:46.480 --> 00:07:50.840
[Amit Varma]: tough, and it's still sort of going on. Let's, let's sort of move back to...

00:07:50.840 --> 00:07:54.800
[Guest]: You also had the farmers movement, actually, you also had the farmers movement in between,

00:07:54.800 --> 00:08:00.400
[Guest]: which was also a, you know, a restoration of hope and all of that. But I think the second

00:08:00.400 --> 00:08:05.800
[Guest]: wave of the pandemic and the manner in which it has, it came, in a way, I think what made

00:08:05.800 --> 00:08:11.960
[Guest]: it worse, at least for me was that in a way I could see it coming. So since January, I

00:08:11.960 --> 00:08:18.520
[Guest]: had friends of mine who got COVID in December, in January. So at that time, also, we were

00:08:18.520 --> 00:08:24.880
[Guest]: trying to, you know, say to people that please don't hold panchayat elections in UP in this,

00:08:24.880 --> 00:08:30.520
[Guest]: in the next few months, and maybe don't hold assembly elections now, and all of that, because

00:08:30.520 --> 00:08:35.400
[Guest]: it looked like it was getting worse. And, you know, anyone following this knew that

00:08:35.400 --> 00:08:40.800
[Guest]: a second wave was coming. That made it much, much harder to, you know, feel that your voice

00:08:40.800 --> 00:08:46.040
[Guest]: is just counting for nothing. It's like doubting Cassandra, you know, that you know what's

00:08:46.040 --> 00:08:50.120
[Guest]: going to happen. And everybody is going to say, you're doubting and look, kitna changa

00:08:50.120 --> 00:08:54.960
[Guest]: hai, kitna positive hai. That was horrible.

00:08:54.960 --> 00:08:58.720
[Amit Varma]: You mentioned the UP panchayat elections and my thought went to the, you know, the 1600,

00:08:58.720 --> 00:09:02.160
[Amit Varma]: I think the last count was the teachers who died because they were forced to go on duty,

00:09:02.160 --> 00:09:08.200
[Amit Varma]: which is basically a murder. And it's not, it's not that you were the only sort of doubting

00:09:08.200 --> 00:09:13.440
[Amit Varma]: Cassandra. They're used to ignoring the activists, but they ignored the scientists, they ignored

00:09:13.440 --> 00:09:16.200
[Amit Varma]: the experts. So that's kind of bizarre.

00:09:16.200 --> 00:09:21.720
[Guest]: They even ignored a chief minister. Apparently, the Uttarakhand chief minister was, you know,

00:09:21.720 --> 00:09:25.960
[Guest]: replaced by Tirath Singh Rawat, who's now the chief minister, because he was trying

00:09:25.960 --> 00:09:31.640
[Guest]: to say, look, it might not be a good idea to hold the Kumbh Mela at this time, you know,

00:09:31.640 --> 00:09:36.800
[Guest]: it might not be a good idea to advance it a year and hold it in 2021 in April. So they

00:09:36.800 --> 00:09:40.720
[Guest]: told him, all right, we'll send you packing and, you know, get somebody who's okay with

00:09:40.720 --> 00:09:45.240
[Guest]: this package, with the agenda. It's terrible.

00:09:45.240 --> 00:09:51.640
[Amit Varma]: Yeah, lots happening. Let's get back to the subject at hand. And now that you're finally

00:09:51.640 --> 00:09:56.220
[Amit Varma]: on the show, you know, take me back to your early life, because we actually share the

00:09:56.220 --> 00:10:02.620
[Amit Varma]: same year of birth. I think I'm a few months younger. And so I'm curious about your childhood.

00:10:02.620 --> 00:10:07.040
[Amit Varma]: You know, tell me about it. I know, I know from the biographical details that you grew

00:10:07.040 --> 00:10:11.340
[Amit Varma]: up in Bhilai and all of that. But tell me a bit about your childhood, what was growing

00:10:11.340 --> 00:10:13.440
[Amit Varma]: up like and so on.

00:10:13.440 --> 00:10:21.240
[Guest]: I think that I had a bit of an idyllic childhood, because I did not really face any difficulties

00:10:21.240 --> 00:10:29.360
[Guest]: in childhood. It was a very happy time in a sense. And my because my parents were actually,

00:10:29.360 --> 00:10:37.120
[Guest]: you know, pretty great. And the strange thing is that I think they were greater after I

00:10:37.120 --> 00:10:41.280
[Guest]: was born. So my dad used to tell me that, you know, theirs was an arranged marriage.

00:10:41.280 --> 00:10:47.340
[Guest]: So they probably came from very different backgrounds. My dad was quite conservative

00:10:47.340 --> 00:10:53.880
[Guest]: in his thinking, he had not had much exposure to, you know, young women. And suddenly, he

00:10:53.880 --> 00:11:05.480
[Guest]: was married to this extremely smart, khub bolne wali, bilkul matlab bebak, besharam ladki.

00:11:05.480 --> 00:11:11.800
[Guest]: So he suddenly didn't really know what hit him. And, but, you know, so they kind of made

00:11:11.800 --> 00:11:18.080
[Guest]: a go of it. But he told me that, you know, it was after I was born that they really had,

00:11:18.080 --> 00:11:22.200
[Guest]: he said, you know, we didn't have our honeymoon period when we should have, but we had it

00:11:22.200 --> 00:11:27.880
[Guest]: after you were born, because that's when we really fell more in love with each other and

00:11:27.880 --> 00:11:32.640
[Guest]: all of that. So I think that's probably true, because my father also kind of relaxed, I

00:11:32.640 --> 00:11:37.240
[Guest]: think, and, you know, forgot about what kind of things he had been taught about how to

00:11:37.240 --> 00:11:43.120
[Guest]: be a man. And he just enjoyed being a dad so much. And he didn't think of himself as

00:11:43.120 --> 00:11:47.520
[Guest]: being the dad of a daughter. You know, so it was more of, you know, he was a very relaxed

00:11:47.520 --> 00:11:54.000
[Guest]: dad. And my mother was a natural feminist. She didn't use the word feminism very much

00:11:54.000 --> 00:12:00.000
[Guest]: as we were growing up. But her natural instinct, you know, instinctual response to almost everything

00:12:00.000 --> 00:12:11.040
[Guest]: was very, very principled, and very feminist, and also very, as in she would keep saying,

00:12:11.040 --> 00:12:16.160
[Guest]: in circumstances, we would see her doing this. So in circumstances where she would be alone,

00:12:16.160 --> 00:12:21.280
[Guest]: and there would be a social kind of consensus that something should be done, but she felt

00:12:21.280 --> 00:12:27.340
[Guest]: that was wrong, she would kind of just step in. So I did see her do this kind of thing.

00:12:27.340 --> 00:12:31.120
[Guest]: And we kind of grew up thinking this was the thing to do, say, if somebody is saying that

00:12:31.120 --> 00:12:36.400
[Guest]: a thief has been caught, and now he should be beaten up. So she would kind of, you know,

00:12:36.400 --> 00:12:41.440
[Guest]: step in and say, what on earth, why, you know, he's just some pocket money, he's just, you

00:12:41.440 --> 00:12:45.560
[Guest]: know, stolen some little thing, and he's a kid and what on earth. So you'd find her in

00:12:45.560 --> 00:12:49.800
[Guest]: this confrontation, you'd find a confronting people who would be trying to beat a dog to

00:12:49.800 --> 00:12:56.600
[Guest]: death or something. So that kind of thing also sort of came with the package of being

00:12:56.600 --> 00:13:03.280
[Guest]: my parents' daughter. And then there was my sister also. So we grew up very, and we grew

00:13:03.280 --> 00:13:10.040
[Guest]: up without anybody really looking over our shoulders much. Bhilai was initially a little

00:13:10.040 --> 00:13:14.600
[Guest]: bit of a safer place. Gradually, it became pretty unsafe for girls. But when we were

00:13:14.600 --> 00:13:20.080
[Guest]: very young, as until I was about 10 or so, we wandered around everywhere. We had a stray

00:13:20.080 --> 00:13:24.960
[Guest]: dog who used to be our guardian. So me and several other girls my age would just get

00:13:24.960 --> 00:13:29.880
[Guest]: up early in the morning and wander and have these adventures and pretend we were Famous

00:13:29.880 --> 00:13:35.120
[Guest]: Five and this and that with just that dog and his dog friends on hand. And my parents

00:13:35.120 --> 00:13:39.400
[Guest]: didn't worry. And my mother also had grown up that way because she said her parents also

00:13:39.400 --> 00:13:46.080
[Guest]: kind of, she would wander around Delhi with a fruit and a book in her hand and go to ruins

00:13:46.080 --> 00:13:50.640
[Guest]: in Delhi and just spend the whole day there just reading and so on. I said, my God, if

00:13:50.640 --> 00:13:57.160
[Guest]: you do that now, her parents would have heart attacks because of how unsafe it's become.

00:13:57.160 --> 00:14:04.200
[Guest]: But when she was a child, it was possible. So that was what it was like. I mean, I wasn't

00:14:04.200 --> 00:14:09.680
[Guest]: exposed to activism as a child, not at all. There was activism in Bhilai at that time,

00:14:09.680 --> 00:14:16.360
[Guest]: but I was unaware of it. I was an officer's daughter in the steel plant. We had friends

00:14:16.360 --> 00:14:22.480
[Guest]: who were workers who would, but they were not trade union activists as such. So I did

00:14:22.480 --> 00:14:27.880
[Guest]: not really know them very well. You know, the only trade union person I knew as a child

00:14:27.880 --> 00:14:34.000
[Guest]: was a somebody who was used to run the Bata shop, you know, the shoe shop. So he was a

00:14:34.000 --> 00:14:38.560
[Guest]: Bengali person and he was very much leftist and he was part of trade unions and also he

00:14:38.560 --> 00:14:43.740
[Guest]: would chatter on about trade union. And my mother used to enjoy these chats, I knew.

00:14:43.740 --> 00:14:48.620
[Guest]: So it would kind of pass over me. My dad was completely bored by politics, least interested.

00:14:48.620 --> 00:14:53.240
[Guest]: My mother was the journalist's daughter and very interested in politics and also she would

00:14:53.240 --> 00:14:58.160
[Guest]: follow the news and all. So it's like that.

00:14:58.160 --> 00:15:02.840
[Amit Varma]: Many stands to explore here, but I'll take a quick digression. And you pointed out that,

00:15:02.840 --> 00:15:05.880
[Amit Varma]: you know, your mother used to walk around Delhi with a fruit and a book and sit in the

00:15:05.880 --> 00:15:11.280
[Amit Varma]: ruins and read and that was no longer possible. And of course, today we know how things are.

00:15:11.280 --> 00:15:15.520
[Amit Varma]: Why do you think that things have become so much worse?

00:15:15.520 --> 00:15:20.000
[Guest]: I don't know, actually. I mean, it's not just Delhi, of course, even, I mean, she's done

00:15:20.000 --> 00:15:24.080
[Guest]: the same thing in Chennai. She said she used to, she and her sister used to just wander

00:15:24.080 --> 00:15:29.760
[Guest]: around barefoot here and there. And, you know, her parents didn't have to worry so much about

00:15:29.760 --> 00:15:36.960
[Guest]: safety. So I'm not sure what has changed. But I think that what I can imagine, at least

00:15:36.960 --> 00:15:42.280
[Guest]: about Delhi, is that at that time, it was largely a rural area. You know, she said that

00:15:42.280 --> 00:15:47.560
[Guest]: her school was, which was Frank Antony Public School. So she said, you know, walking from

00:15:47.560 --> 00:15:52.400
[Guest]: Defence Colony to Frank Antony Public School meant she would be walking through fields.

00:15:52.400 --> 00:15:56.440
[Guest]: There would actually be fields there. There would actually be green fields there. So I

00:15:56.440 --> 00:16:03.760
[Guest]: think that the change in Delhi, which was social change and not just a demographic change

00:16:03.760 --> 00:16:09.840
[Guest]: and it's becoming a more urban capital city, and these, you know, the villages of Delhi

00:16:09.840 --> 00:16:14.880
[Guest]: becoming, they're still villages in name, you know, it's still Munir Ka Gaon, but it's

00:16:14.880 --> 00:16:20.960
[Guest]: become a real estate kind of based, it's not a agriculture based society, it's a real estate

00:16:20.960 --> 00:16:28.480
[Guest]: based society. And I think that somehow that transition has not been very organic. I would

00:16:28.480 --> 00:16:31.920
[Guest]: say, you know, Bombay is becoming a city has been much more organic, because there's been

00:16:31.920 --> 00:16:36.200
[Guest]: a large working class and that has shaped the culture of the city. But in Delhi, it

00:16:36.200 --> 00:16:43.080
[Guest]: isn't, that's the rentier class that has shaped it. And somehow, I mean, that has not led

00:16:43.080 --> 00:16:49.120
[Guest]: to a change in how Delhi looks at women. So that change, I see happening a little bit

00:16:49.120 --> 00:16:54.400
[Guest]: more now, in fact, you know, with, but I know that in the 90s, when I came to Delhi first

00:16:54.400 --> 00:17:00.000
[Guest]: from Bombay, it was a terrible culture shock. A friend and I came from Bombay to Delhi,

00:17:00.000 --> 00:17:04.520
[Guest]: and I'd done my BA in Bombay. When I came to Delhi, we would walk around wearing the

00:17:04.520 --> 00:17:10.080
[Guest]: same stuff that we'd worn in Bombay, which was fairly, you know, raggedy stuff and ordinary

00:17:10.080 --> 00:17:16.080
[Guest]: stuff, nothing to, and we would wonder, why is everyone staring at us? What is the thing

00:17:16.080 --> 00:17:23.240
[Guest]: exactly? So then we realized that to get stared at in Delhi by men, and by not one man, it's

00:17:23.240 --> 00:17:27.200
[Guest]: not like, it's like if you're at a bus stop, suddenly you're getting stared at by several

00:17:27.200 --> 00:17:32.200
[Guest]: sets of men. And you realize that it was because you're a woman, it's because you're female,

00:17:32.200 --> 00:17:37.960
[Guest]: that's it. So the idea that if you're female and out on the road, and you, you know, they're

00:17:37.960 --> 00:17:42.840
[Guest]: speculating about what you're doing there, you're not expected to be there. And I know

00:17:42.840 --> 00:17:47.320
[Guest]: that for men, they didn't realize this at all, you know, because when my partner and

00:17:47.320 --> 00:17:52.920
[Guest]: I first, you know, got, we were colleagues together, comrades together. So we would have

00:17:52.920 --> 00:17:59.480
[Guest]: to, you know, travel here and there. So we'd be at a bus stop, say around 9 at night, right

00:17:59.480 --> 00:18:05.640
[Guest]: near the ISBT bus stand or something. And he would get increasingly uncomfortable because

00:18:05.640 --> 00:18:10.880
[Guest]: he'd realized that somebody's staring, somebody else is staring, somebody else is staring.

00:18:10.880 --> 00:18:16.440
[Guest]: And you know, he asked me what to do. I said, look, what's the point? If I confront one

00:18:16.440 --> 00:18:19.600
[Guest]: guy, there are all the other guys, I don't want to confront so many and have so much

00:18:19.600 --> 00:18:25.680
[Guest]: chodo, ignore. So then he's like, why exactly do you think they're looking like that? I

00:18:25.680 --> 00:18:31.120
[Guest]: said, they're looking because I fit their box of female, that's it. Look at the bus

00:18:31.120 --> 00:18:35.880
[Guest]: stop, how few women there are. I'm one of the only women sitting there. And so they

00:18:35.880 --> 00:18:40.360
[Guest]: think this is weird. This is strange. They're not able to put me in whatever box of, you

00:18:40.360 --> 00:18:45.800
[Guest]: know, I'm a young woman and a young woman student. So they can't put me in the box of

00:18:45.800 --> 00:18:50.160
[Guest]: oh, she looks like someone's wife. She looks like someone's, you know, whatever. So, and

00:18:50.160 --> 00:18:55.000
[Guest]: she's out here at night. So, you know, and then police people would come. If the bus

00:18:55.000 --> 00:18:59.920
[Guest]: stop didn't have too many people on it, then you'd have a police guy come up and say to

00:18:59.920 --> 00:19:04.800
[Guest]: him, aap kya kar rahe hain inke saath? Basically suspecting, are you a prostitute? What are

00:19:04.800 --> 00:19:09.240
[Guest]: you? You know, because otherwise, why would you be out at night? The idea that you might

00:19:09.240 --> 00:19:13.280
[Guest]: be a student, you might be an activist, you may be visiting Delhi University, and then

00:19:13.280 --> 00:19:18.880
[Guest]: going back to JNU, taking a bus from the ISBT bus adda, this was incomprehensible, even

00:19:18.880 --> 00:19:19.880
[Guest]: to the cops.

00:19:19.880 --> 00:19:24.120
[Amit Varma]: Yeah, the story really speaks to me, because I think, you know, what your partner kind

00:19:24.120 --> 00:19:27.600
[Amit Varma]: of figured out at that bus stop is something I've gone through as well, in the sense that

00:19:27.600 --> 00:19:31.800
[Amit Varma]: there are things we take for granted, which is this extra layer of awareness, which women

00:19:31.800 --> 00:19:38.720
[Amit Varma]: have, which is normal to them. And most men are unaware of it, like you said, and men

00:19:38.720 --> 00:19:42.920
[Amit Varma]: are fortunate enough that we can go out on the night and not have to worry about who's

00:19:42.920 --> 00:19:47.560
[Amit Varma]: looking at us or whatever, we can enter a lift and not have to worry about who's there.

00:19:47.560 --> 00:19:52.560
[Amit Varma]: And that extra layer is something that at some point, I guess, you begin to become aware

00:19:52.560 --> 00:19:57.400
[Amit Varma]: of till then you just take it for granted. When did you become aware of that extra layer?

00:19:57.400 --> 00:20:03.080
[Guest]: In Bhilai itself, in Bhilai, as I grew up, you know, as I entered my teens, I think Bhilai

00:20:03.080 --> 00:20:08.200
[Guest]: also probably underwent a little bit of change, or maybe as little children, we didn't really

00:20:08.200 --> 00:20:13.360
[Guest]: realize it. But gradually, I became aware of it. I'll tell you when, actually, I was

00:20:13.360 --> 00:20:21.120
[Guest]: quite young, even then, I was still a child. But my mother had started going out to work.

00:20:21.120 --> 00:20:26.920
[Guest]: So initially, she had not found a job. But then she did find a job, she started teaching.

00:20:26.920 --> 00:20:31.400
[Guest]: So she used to take a cycle and head out. And she used to leave us alone at, we were

00:20:31.400 --> 00:20:35.360
[Guest]: latchkey kids, my sister and I, so we'd go to school, come back, you know, feed ourselves

00:20:35.360 --> 00:20:44.040
[Guest]: and she'd be out. But then she got a stalker. So somebody in a car, whom she later realized

00:20:44.040 --> 00:20:49.080
[Guest]: was the son of a big industrialist there. So he was, you know, this quite, quite well

00:20:49.080 --> 00:20:53.920
[Guest]: known industrialist in that area. In fact, even now, I'm stopping myself from naming

00:20:53.920 --> 00:21:00.880
[Guest]: him and from saying even his car number, which we all remember by heart, because that family,

00:21:00.880 --> 00:21:05.400
[Guest]: my mother still lives in Billai and that family is still, I mean, it is an influential family

00:21:05.400 --> 00:21:10.120
[Guest]: still. So she got the stalker, this man in a car who would, she suddenly realized he's

00:21:10.120 --> 00:21:14.880
[Guest]: hanging out, he's following her wherever she goes. So initially, she ignored it, then she

00:21:14.880 --> 00:21:21.840
[Guest]: started getting scared, then she really got freaked out. Because one day, okay, he would

00:21:21.840 --> 00:21:26.200
[Guest]: make blank calls to the house all the time. So, you know, there were the phones, you know,

00:21:26.200 --> 00:21:31.360
[Guest]: the old sort of black phones, but also these were steel plant phones, Billai Steel Plant,

00:21:31.360 --> 00:21:36.400
[Guest]: right? So they were basically, you know, you could connect to a steel plant operator also

00:21:36.400 --> 00:21:41.000
[Guest]: if you wanted and all of that. You know, so he must have found it easy to figure out the

00:21:41.000 --> 00:21:47.280
[Guest]: number and he would keep making calls. And my mother was worried that the children, we

00:21:47.280 --> 00:21:50.840
[Guest]: would pick it up, her daughters would pick it up. For herself, she was, you know, kind

00:21:50.840 --> 00:21:55.480
[Guest]: of confident that she'd deal with it. But then she really lost her nerve when one day

00:21:55.480 --> 00:21:59.000
[Guest]: she just, you know, the doorbell rang, she opened the door and this man was standing

00:21:59.000 --> 00:22:05.800
[Guest]: in front. And she totally freaked out because she felt that if we were alone at home. So

00:22:05.800 --> 00:22:10.200
[Guest]: I think that that point I remember as a change. I don't remember exactly how old I was, maybe

00:22:10.200 --> 00:22:17.280
[Guest]: 13 or so. But she, I remember that that was a time when she felt that her fear communicated

00:22:17.280 --> 00:22:23.760
[Guest]: to us. So her, you know, so we then she would start telling us that you can't open the door.

00:22:23.760 --> 00:22:27.760
[Guest]: Even if someone says, I'm your father's friend, I'm your mother's friend, tell them, uncle,

00:22:27.760 --> 00:22:32.640
[Guest]: auntie, we are very sorry, but we have been told not to open the door. So I'm sorry, we're

00:22:32.640 --> 00:22:36.960
[Guest]: being rude, but we can't open the door to anyone. And that was the first time in Bilai

00:22:36.960 --> 00:22:40.360
[Guest]: that we had thought of that because we used to leave the door unlatched and stuff and

00:22:40.360 --> 00:22:48.520
[Guest]: not really think twice. Then that guy actually ran her into a sort of concrete gutter once

00:22:48.520 --> 00:22:53.400
[Guest]: near our house. So she was coming back on the cycle. And since he came so close to her

00:22:53.400 --> 00:22:58.520
[Guest]: on the cycle, she panicked and had to get off the road and she fell. So she came back

00:22:58.520 --> 00:23:07.640
[Guest]: to the house all, you know, scraped, bruised, not badly hurt, but really, really badly mentally

00:23:07.640 --> 00:23:12.480
[Guest]: freaked out. So she was in tears and she was shaking. And I remember my father looking

00:23:12.480 --> 00:23:18.200
[Guest]: very horrified and helpless and not knowing what to say what to do. And then our cat came

00:23:18.200 --> 00:23:23.360
[Guest]: and sat in her lap and, you know, she started crying even more. And we didn't know what

00:23:23.360 --> 00:23:28.800
[Guest]: to say. Then I then I remember hearing my parents talk about this. My sister was very

00:23:28.800 --> 00:23:33.280
[Guest]: young at that time, but I could understand what was being. So I remember my parents talking

00:23:33.280 --> 00:23:38.120
[Guest]: and finally deciding, no, we cannot complain. We cannot do anything because the police won't

00:23:38.120 --> 00:23:44.560
[Guest]: act against this guy. And how will we prove anything? And what if he gets more vindictive

00:23:44.560 --> 00:23:50.760
[Guest]: towards the children? So then they just became more protective. They started having a very

00:23:50.760 --> 00:23:56.320
[Guest]: lovely neighbor of mine. Sort of we were told not to go to our place, but to go to her place.

00:23:56.320 --> 00:24:00.120
[Guest]: So we would have lunch there when we came back from school. And then my mother would

00:24:00.120 --> 00:24:04.080
[Guest]: collect us, things like that. I think that was the time probably when I realized that

00:24:04.080 --> 00:24:08.600
[Guest]: this is, you know, the world we live in is not safe. After that, of course, there were

00:24:08.600 --> 00:24:15.320
[Guest]: any number of such instances in Bhilai where we realized that to be female and out on the

00:24:15.320 --> 00:24:23.320
[Guest]: road is something and not just in terms of safety. I think also in terms of the way you

00:24:23.320 --> 00:24:30.160
[Guest]: hold yourself right in public. So I think for a long time, my mother, quite remarkably

00:24:30.160 --> 00:24:37.440
[Guest]: actually to think about it, held herself and encouraged us to hold ourselves without really

00:24:37.440 --> 00:24:42.040
[Guest]: remembering that we are female. So we didn't, you know, we weren't, you know, how we hold

00:24:42.040 --> 00:24:46.840
[Guest]: ourselves, how we sit, how we laugh, what we do. We didn't really think much about it.

00:24:46.840 --> 00:24:51.680
[Guest]: And my parents, I think, had a very big role to play in that because I, in retrospect,

00:24:51.680 --> 00:24:57.160
[Guest]: now I look at society and I realize that maybe other girls were not as, even in Bhilai, were

00:24:57.160 --> 00:25:06.200
[Guest]: certainly not as lucky as I was. I knew that my women, my girl friends, as in school friends,

00:25:06.200 --> 00:25:11.720
[Guest]: they, and my sister's friends, they all thought of my mother as one of their friends. So they

00:25:11.720 --> 00:25:16.640
[Guest]: would keep telling me that, you know, they'd keep talking about, you know, secret plans

00:25:16.640 --> 00:25:20.960
[Guest]: we'd be making. And they'd say, aur kisi ko nahi bata sakte hain, aunty ko bata sakte

00:25:20.960 --> 00:25:27.040
[Guest]: hain, Lakshmi aunty ko bata sakte hain, because they knew that this one is at heart, you know,

00:25:27.040 --> 00:25:32.800
[Guest]: she's not going to chugli karo to their parents. So they didn't think of her as part of the,

00:25:32.800 --> 00:25:38.920
[Guest]: you know, authority figures. And I never realized how lucky I was in that, actually. I realized

00:25:38.920 --> 00:25:44.200
[Guest]: that later, because it was only probably when I came to Delhi that I began to fully realize

00:25:44.200 --> 00:25:49.880
[Guest]: that being a woman, it's not just about physical safety. It's about the fact that you are seen

00:25:49.880 --> 00:25:54.960
[Guest]: as though you have no business out in public. Kar kya rahe ho yahan pe? Mane you are not

00:25:54.960 --> 00:25:59.360
[Guest]: supposed to, you're supposed to account for yourself in public. You have to show that

00:25:59.360 --> 00:26:06.480
[Guest]: I have a good purpose, that I'm not immoral or whatever it is, you know. And even if it

00:26:06.480 --> 00:26:10.680
[Guest]: is unsafe, I'll have to explain, oh, it's unsafe, why are you out here? So the fact

00:26:10.680 --> 00:26:15.800
[Guest]: that I'll keep on having to explain my presence, I think I never had to do that much to my

00:26:15.800 --> 00:26:21.320
[Guest]: parents, you know. The only instance I remember, there was one instance when my mother lost

00:26:21.320 --> 00:26:26.040
[Guest]: her nerve a bit vis-a-vis me. That was one time when I had joined some karate class or

00:26:26.040 --> 00:26:31.400
[Guest]: something. So I used to do it just for exercise, kicks. So once, I usually used to get a lift

00:26:31.400 --> 00:26:36.360
[Guest]: back home with one person who would drop me on his cycle. That day, somehow he didn't

00:26:36.360 --> 00:26:40.800
[Guest]: turn up and I decided to have a leisurely walk home. So I walked home, and it's quite

00:26:40.800 --> 00:26:47.360
[Guest]: away from my home, but I walked. And it was evening, so around 7.30, it was dark. And

00:26:47.360 --> 00:26:53.680
[Guest]: as I, about halfway home, I realized I spotted my parents on the scooter going in the opposite

00:26:53.680 --> 00:26:57.800
[Guest]: direction. So I tried to call out to them, but they didn't see. So I thought, oh, well,

00:26:57.800 --> 00:27:02.040
[Guest]: and I walked home. As soon as I got home, my grandmother was at home then, and she came

00:27:02.040 --> 00:27:06.240
[Guest]: out looking very horrified and came and hugged me and said, come, come, come. So I said,

00:27:06.240 --> 00:27:10.440
[Guest]: what happened? So then she realized and she said, no, no, sit, sit, sit. And when your

00:27:10.440 --> 00:27:16.520
[Guest]: parents come, if your mother gets angry, don't react immediately. You know, she told me,

00:27:16.520 --> 00:27:22.780
[Guest]: don't be angry. So then my parents came home. The minute they opened the gate, my mother

00:27:22.780 --> 00:27:26.640
[Guest]: saw me and freaked out. She said, you're not going anywhere ever again and this and that

00:27:26.640 --> 00:27:31.720
[Guest]: and that and what. And that was so unlike her because she thought I was late and something

00:27:31.720 --> 00:27:35.440
[Guest]: had happened to me and they'd gone to look for me. So I said, but I saw you people and

00:27:35.440 --> 00:27:39.680
[Guest]: I was walking back and it was fine and we always walk and come on and all of that. But

00:27:39.680 --> 00:27:46.520
[Guest]: somewhere in her brain, she had gotten a fear, right? So she did. She suddenly became the,

00:27:46.520 --> 00:27:52.120
[Guest]: you know, the authority figure mother saying, kuch nahi kal se, sab bandh and all of that.

00:27:52.120 --> 00:27:57.040
[Guest]: So I was getting angry. Then my dad also came and told me, he said, don't say a word right

00:27:57.040 --> 00:28:01.560
[Guest]: now. Just relax now. We are very happy that nothing happened and you were not scared.

00:28:01.560 --> 00:28:05.960
[Guest]: We were scared. No, that's okay. You were not scared. You were enjoying your walk home.

00:28:05.960 --> 00:28:10.440
[Guest]: So now let your mother get over her fear. You know, she's had a very bad shock. So let

00:28:10.440 --> 00:28:16.400
[Guest]: her get over it. And of course, she never repeated that ever again. I happily went next

00:28:16.400 --> 00:28:22.880
[Guest]: evening also, no problem. But yeah. Yeah, your parents sound so remarkable. A couple

00:28:22.880 --> 00:28:26.720
[Amit Varma]: of threads to untangle there. But before that, a quick question. I'm just curious that when

00:28:26.720 --> 00:28:30.360
[Amit Varma]: the bell rang and she opened the door and it was that guy, what happened then? What

00:28:30.360 --> 00:28:36.600
[Guest]: did he say? What happened? She says he just stood there and said nothing. And she, you

00:28:36.600 --> 00:28:42.280
[Guest]: know, she was terrified, absolutely. But she just sort of shut the door and bolted it,

00:28:42.280 --> 00:28:47.280
[Guest]: locked it and just sat inside. And after a while, she looked out of the window and he

00:28:47.280 --> 00:28:52.240
[Guest]: was gone. But she just freaked out. I mean, she didn't say or do anything. And she did

00:28:52.240 --> 00:28:56.440
[Guest]: think, she said, should I make a call? Should I call the police? Who should I call? And

00:28:56.440 --> 00:29:02.680
[Guest]: she then decided not to. And I see that, you know, all the time now, when I think about

00:29:02.680 --> 00:29:08.400
[Guest]: women weighing in, whether they want to complain about something, especially stalking. I wrote

00:29:08.400 --> 00:29:14.560
[Guest]: about this sometime in 2013, when one woman had come to one of the meetings we were having

00:29:14.560 --> 00:29:19.640
[Guest]: during the Nirbhaya wala movement. I don't like calling it that, but it was the anti-rape

00:29:19.640 --> 00:29:25.080
[Guest]: movement. So this woman had come from quite a way. I think she was in Mangolpuri or someplace

00:29:25.080 --> 00:29:28.920
[Guest]: quite far away from central Delhi. She'd come all the way to the meeting because she'd heard

00:29:28.920 --> 00:29:34.760
[Guest]: about it from someone who worked with her. And the person who worked with her was a comrade

00:29:34.760 --> 00:29:39.800
[Guest]: of ours, a trade union member. So he mentioned it and she came. Then she took me aside after

00:29:39.800 --> 00:29:44.520
[Guest]: the meeting and told me she was being stalked. So I told her what do you want to do? And

00:29:44.520 --> 00:29:50.520
[Guest]: she said, main itne din mujhe dar lag raha tha ki mere bachon ke kuch karega. So I didn't

00:29:50.520 --> 00:29:56.240
[Guest]: want to complain. But now he's actually started following my kids around. And now I feel like

00:29:56.240 --> 00:30:00.880
[Guest]: then what do I have to lose? I have to have to complain because I cannot risk something

00:30:00.880 --> 00:30:05.360
[Guest]: happening to my children. And that kind of brought it alive again. And I remembered all

00:30:05.360 --> 00:30:09.360
[Guest]: of this. And then I wrote about it and I realized that a lot of other women have gone through

00:30:09.360 --> 00:30:15.760
[Guest]: this. And this fear of the consequences of your complaining, that other people, that

00:30:15.760 --> 00:30:21.680
[Guest]: your family members might have to bear it, is a huge burden. A lot of people do not want

00:30:21.680 --> 00:30:26.360
[Guest]: to take that burden. Look at what happened to the singer complainant. Her family members,

00:30:26.360 --> 00:30:32.360
[Guest]: so many of them were killed as a result. Or look at Ruchira, I think her name was Ruchira

00:30:32.360 --> 00:30:40.840
[Guest]: Girotra, right? The child in, you know, the tennis player in, I think it was Gurgaon or

00:30:40.840 --> 00:30:46.360
[Guest]: something. Some years ago, she complained against a police officer who had been sexually

00:30:46.360 --> 00:30:53.120
[Guest]: harassing her at the tennis club or something. And they made her life and her brother's life

00:30:53.120 --> 00:30:58.560
[Guest]: and her parents' life a living hell. So at the end of it, she committed suicide, Ruchira

00:30:58.560 --> 00:30:59.560
[Guest]: Girotra.

00:30:59.560 --> 00:31:06.040
[Amit Varma]: Yeah, I remember that now comes to mind. Yeah. Yeah. I was struck by something you said and

00:31:06.040 --> 00:31:11.360
[Amit Varma]: this is leading on to my next question. You know, I teach a writing class, an online writing

00:31:11.360 --> 00:31:15.840
[Amit Varma]: course and there one of the things that I tell the participants is that always look

00:31:15.840 --> 00:31:20.560
[Amit Varma]: for concrete details, which can make whatever you're writing about vivid. And you just did

00:31:20.560 --> 00:31:23.640
[Amit Varma]: that when you were talking about your mother and how she's come home and she's upset and

00:31:23.640 --> 00:31:29.160
[Amit Varma]: you said, the cat crawled onto her lap and she started crying, which is so concrete and

00:31:29.160 --> 00:31:33.520
[Amit Varma]: just makes it so real. So my question here is your mother, of course, taught literature.

00:31:33.520 --> 00:31:37.640
[Amit Varma]: You've spoken in the past about how you were surrounded by books at home and they were

00:31:37.640 --> 00:31:42.120
[Amit Varma]: in a sense a window to the world like at, you know, in some other interview of yours,

00:31:42.120 --> 00:31:46.760
[Amit Varma]: you've written about how, you know, even though those were homophobic times, that didn't affect

00:31:46.760 --> 00:31:50.880
[Amit Varma]: your attitude, because you had those books, that was your kind of window to the world

00:31:50.880 --> 00:31:54.280
[Amit Varma]: and you could sort of get a lot from there. Tell me a little bit about you know, the kind

00:31:54.280 --> 00:31:58.360
[Amit Varma]: of stuff you read, the writers you really liked, the writers who stayed with you and

00:31:58.360 --> 00:32:04.080
[Amit Varma]: other books that kind of shaped you in that period and even later, which had a profound

00:32:04.080 --> 00:32:05.080
[Amit Varma]: influence on you.

00:32:05.080 --> 00:32:11.760
[Guest]: Yeah, I mean, I've, I like to think about it because I read so indiscriminately. In

00:32:11.760 --> 00:32:16.960
[Guest]: my house, you know, children's books and adult books were not really distinguished. Even

00:32:16.960 --> 00:32:21.840
[Guest]: my mother and her sister and her brothers were not brought up that way. So apparently

00:32:21.840 --> 00:32:26.200
[Guest]: they never really had children's books, you know, brought for them and all of that. Books

00:32:26.200 --> 00:32:32.120
[Guest]: were there, all kinds of books and people just read them. So it was like that for me.

00:32:32.120 --> 00:32:36.920
[Guest]: So I knew that we read a lot of Enid Blyton, for instance. Okay, so that's something everyone

00:32:36.920 --> 00:32:42.600
[Guest]: reads, we also read. But I think about it now when I think about what you take away

00:32:42.600 --> 00:32:48.400
[Guest]: from there, right? So the thing is, there's a lot of now in the UK and other places that

00:32:48.400 --> 00:32:54.960
[Guest]: are even moved to say ban Enid Blyton or do a sanitizing of her books because she uses

00:32:54.960 --> 00:33:01.080
[Guest]: very racist language here and there. Okay, extremely racist language and racist portrayal

00:33:01.080 --> 00:33:05.760
[Guest]: of some characters. Definitely colonial, you know, if you look at any Indian character

00:33:05.760 --> 00:33:08.960
[Guest]: in her books, they are a ridiculous kind of thing, you know, somebody, it's not even an

00:33:08.960 --> 00:33:13.640
[Guest]: Indian character, but somebody acting as an Indian student or something, it's ridiculous.

00:33:13.640 --> 00:33:20.200
[Guest]: But and of course, it's, you know, it's obsessed by the idea of gender rules, right? Because

00:33:20.200 --> 00:33:24.200
[Guest]: it's always about, oh, you know, this girl can't do anything because she's a girl and

00:33:24.200 --> 00:33:29.680
[Guest]: who's girlish and who's boyish and all of that. The thing is that I think about what

00:33:29.680 --> 00:33:34.840
[Guest]: I was getting when I read that stuff. To me, the most interesting character was not the

00:33:34.840 --> 00:33:41.320
[Guest]: ones who were, you know, obeying the rules. The one whom the writer made most interesting

00:33:41.320 --> 00:33:46.160
[Guest]: was the one who was breaking the rules. So you always, you know, the tomboy character

00:33:46.160 --> 00:33:51.520
[Guest]: was the interesting one. You know, even in, you know, Little Women, you know, Louisa May

00:33:51.520 --> 00:33:56.640
[Guest]: Alcott's. It is Jo who's your heroine because she's the one who's actually not the little

00:33:56.640 --> 00:34:03.240
[Guest]: woman as such. She's not in the mold of women as they were meant to be. So I am not really,

00:34:03.240 --> 00:34:06.920
[Guest]: I have, you know, when I look back now, I feel like saying, don't tell your children,

00:34:06.920 --> 00:34:11.880
[Guest]: you don't read this, don't read that. Let them read everything. I read a lot of Reader's

00:34:11.880 --> 00:34:17.960
[Guest]: Digest for lack of anything, because I was so voracious. So I wanted a continuous supply

00:34:17.960 --> 00:34:22.920
[Guest]: of stuff to read. I read a lot of Reader's Digest. Well, here I'm sitting in front of

00:34:22.920 --> 00:34:28.840
[Guest]: you card carrying communists. The whole Reader's Digest was a propaganda against communism.

00:34:28.840 --> 00:34:38.120
[Guest]: Okay. They had such, it was a very, very propagandist magazine. Okay. But what do I remember from

00:34:38.120 --> 00:34:42.440
[Guest]: what I read of it? I remember that they used to carry these books. They would carry full

00:34:42.440 --> 00:34:47.680
[Guest]: book length stories, maybe slightly abridged. So they had stuff from the Second World War

00:34:47.680 --> 00:34:53.200
[Guest]: about people kind of escaping from the Nazis and, you know, what the Nazis did and all

00:34:53.200 --> 00:34:58.960
[Guest]: of that. Now, I remember all of that. All of that gave a very vivid memory to me. And

00:34:58.960 --> 00:35:05.200
[Guest]: so when I started looking around my own reality and figuring out, oh, these guys are behaving

00:35:05.200 --> 00:35:11.560
[Guest]: exactly like those Nazis. So that was an easy thing for me. I didn't get the anti-American,

00:35:11.560 --> 00:35:19.480
[Guest]: anti-Russia propaganda and anti-Soviet propaganda and anti-communist propaganda didn't really

00:35:19.480 --> 00:35:24.680
[Guest]: penetrate that much, you know. Of course, there was a lot of Russian, anti-US propaganda,

00:35:24.680 --> 00:35:30.200
[Guest]: which I also read because they were the People's, was it the People's Publishing House? Basically

00:35:30.200 --> 00:35:36.160
[Guest]: the Soviet literature. So they would have these camps and lovely books of all kinds,

00:35:36.160 --> 00:35:40.360
[Guest]: especially for children and especially science books and all, which were great. And so my

00:35:40.360 --> 00:35:45.680
[Guest]: parents actually learned Russian. So they were many Russians in Bilay. So they would

00:35:45.680 --> 00:35:50.240
[Guest]: learn Russian and interact a lot with Russians. They had several good friends. But they would

00:35:50.240 --> 00:35:54.480
[Guest]: laugh at the stories they were being taught because they were being taught stories about

00:35:54.480 --> 00:36:01.040
[Guest]: people escaping from the U.S. to go to the Soviet Union and say, oh, we are in paradise.

00:36:01.040 --> 00:36:05.980
[Guest]: And the Reader's Digest would have stories which were the opposite, right? People escaping

00:36:05.980 --> 00:36:11.280
[Guest]: from, you know, Soviet Russia or East Germany or whatever it is and finding freedom in the

00:36:11.280 --> 00:36:15.900
[Guest]: West and all of that. So my parents would make a lot of jokes about this, you know.

00:36:15.900 --> 00:36:22.120
[Guest]: So I think it was their treatment of literature that it's, or any reading, that this is not

00:36:22.120 --> 00:36:27.140
[Guest]: something that you're not just swallowing and believing, that you're actually engaging

00:36:27.140 --> 00:36:31.240
[Guest]: with it. You can laugh at it. You can argue about it. You can think about it. That was

00:36:31.240 --> 00:36:37.420
[Guest]: more of the approach. So in terms of books, I think one book which I accidentally picked

00:36:37.420 --> 00:36:42.720
[Guest]: up and read was actually the, you know, I read and re-read and re-read it so often.

00:36:42.720 --> 00:36:46.600
[Guest]: And I was very young when I first picked it up. The front page was missing. So I didn't

00:36:46.600 --> 00:36:51.120
[Guest]: know what book it was. I just started reading. It turned out to be To Kill a Mockingbird.

00:36:51.120 --> 00:36:59.160
[Guest]: I had no idea. I must have been about 10 maybe or 11, not more than that. So I began reading

00:36:59.160 --> 00:37:05.200
[Guest]: and I had no idea, you know, when they were discussing rape, I had no idea what they meant

00:37:05.200 --> 00:37:09.200
[Guest]: exactly because I didn't quite know the dynamics of what was going on. So I wasn't much better

00:37:09.200 --> 00:37:13.640
[Guest]: off than Scout when she's asking, you know, what exactly is happening here? What's rape?

00:37:13.640 --> 00:37:18.720
[Guest]: You know, so carnal knowledge of a woman without her consent. What, what, what is carnal? I

00:37:18.720 --> 00:37:25.280
[Guest]: didn't know, but I couldn't put the book down. And I felt the sense of a tremendous injustice

00:37:25.280 --> 00:37:32.600
[Guest]: of various kinds and felt very, very moved by it. And then I figured out later, I remember

00:37:32.600 --> 00:37:37.840
[Guest]: I picked this up at my grandparents' house in Coonoor. So I, I figured out that it was

00:37:37.840 --> 00:37:41.680
[Guest]: called To Kill a Mockingbird because then I asked my mother and all of that. And then

00:37:41.680 --> 00:37:47.920
[Guest]: she said, yes, I think this is that one. So that I went back to several times. And I think

00:37:47.920 --> 00:37:53.800
[Guest]: that in a sense, you know, making the connection with biases in our society and, you know,

00:37:53.800 --> 00:38:00.680
[Guest]: communal biases, caste biases. I think that was a very, very formative kind of book, which

00:38:00.680 --> 00:38:07.040
[Guest]: made a big difference. And then a lot of, you know, short stories and things like, like

00:38:07.040 --> 00:38:13.480
[Guest]: Kate Chopin. So her writing. So this was also stuff I just discovered accidentally, you

00:38:13.480 --> 00:38:18.440
[Guest]: know, I would find it lying in the, at the back shelf in Coonoor or in Vilai, somewhere

00:38:18.440 --> 00:38:23.080
[Guest]: at the back and just pull it out and say, okay, book I haven't read yet. So I'd read

00:38:23.080 --> 00:38:28.880
[Guest]: it. And I realized that it's a book about a, you know, I was reading The Awakening where

00:38:28.880 --> 00:38:34.280
[Guest]: it's this woman who eventually, you know, leaves her marriage. So I was reading stuff

00:38:34.280 --> 00:38:40.680
[Guest]: like that without, you know, without a censor and really feeling moved. You know, I would

00:38:40.680 --> 00:38:46.000
[Guest]: live with these characters for a long time. And I was, as I said, I read anything and

00:38:46.000 --> 00:38:53.440
[Guest]: everything. So I was reading Max Birbaum and James Thurber in Coonoor. Again, just finding

00:38:53.440 --> 00:38:59.000
[Guest]: the books, reading them. And then in my school in Vilai, when I went to class, you know,

00:38:59.000 --> 00:39:04.560
[Guest]: ninth and 10th, I realized that my classes are boring me. Okay. I had to somehow pass

00:39:04.560 --> 00:39:09.480
[Guest]: mathematics, which have terrified me and maths and science had become a burden and found

00:39:09.480 --> 00:39:14.880
[Guest]: it very hard. But my English classes and, you know, social science classes had become

00:39:14.880 --> 00:39:19.080
[Guest]: boring because, you know, I could make out the mistakes that the, you know, teacher is

00:39:19.080 --> 00:39:24.600
[Guest]: making and I couldn't bear what they were doing with poetry and reading in class. So

00:39:24.600 --> 00:39:30.160
[Guest]: I realized that what I would instead do was to go to the school library on time, pick

00:39:30.160 --> 00:39:35.320
[Guest]: up something to read and read it under my desk in my book so they will know what I'm

00:39:35.320 --> 00:39:41.880
[Guest]: reading. So I read a lot of Dostoevsky because they had these old Soviet publications of

00:39:41.880 --> 00:39:45.480
[Guest]: crime and punishment there. So I read Crime and Punishment as though it was a detective

00:39:45.480 --> 00:39:50.320
[Guest]: novel. Okay. So here I am waiting with bated breath. Oh, my God, poor guy. And then I'd

00:39:50.320 --> 00:39:54.240
[Guest]: imagine, my God, suppose I end up killing somebody one day, then what will I live with?

00:39:54.240 --> 00:39:58.440
[Guest]: I'll keep on thinking. Even if no one catches me, I'll be feeling guilty. I'll be feeling

00:39:58.440 --> 00:40:04.800
[Guest]: guilty. So I really felt it. Then I found a book by very irrelevant, Leaves in the Forest.

00:40:04.800 --> 00:40:09.880
[Guest]: So that I read. I had no idea who's very irrelevant. I just found the book, read it and I was fascinated

00:40:09.880 --> 00:40:22.440
[Guest]: by it because they meet Gandhi. So he mentions meeting Gandhi and he meets C.F. Andrews.

00:40:22.440 --> 00:40:27.560
[Guest]: So C.F. Andrews talks about Gandhi. So, and it's very funny because they are cocking a

00:40:27.560 --> 00:40:33.280
[Guest]: snook at the priesthood, you know, because the priesthood doesn't want them joining,

00:40:33.280 --> 00:40:38.460
[Guest]: you know, the British priests don't want these guys joining, supporting the freedom movement

00:40:38.460 --> 00:40:45.720
[Guest]: or supporting Adivasis, you know, Goan Adivasis living their lives in their own way. And,

00:40:45.720 --> 00:40:52.160
[Guest]: you know, that I found was fascinating to me. So I had a sort of weird, eclectic kind

00:40:52.160 --> 00:40:54.240
[Guest]: of exposure of this kind.

00:40:54.240 --> 00:40:59.040
[Amit Varma]: Yeah, no, this is this is kind of nuts, because like when I was a kid, first of all, a lot

00:40:59.040 --> 00:41:03.640
[Amit Varma]: of the books you're naming are sort of familiar to me, the books and authors, because obviously,

00:41:03.640 --> 00:41:07.000
[Amit Varma]: in India, you only got so much back in the day. So it was pretty much a staple, you're

00:41:07.000 --> 00:41:11.320
[Amit Varma]: going to read your Ennard Blyton and Hardy Boys and all of that. And I like the Mallory

00:41:11.320 --> 00:41:15.640
[Unknown]: Towers series a lot back when I was a kid, I remember, especially the Tomboys. So we

00:41:15.640 --> 00:41:23.000
[Amit Varma]: have something in common there. And what kind of gave me, somewhat startled me was that,

00:41:23.000 --> 00:41:27.040
[Amit Varma]: you know, my sort of gateway into serious literature was when I picked up Dostoevsky's

00:41:27.040 --> 00:41:30.680
[Amit Varma]: House of the Dead, because I thought, oh, it's going to be a thriller kind of thing.

00:41:30.680 --> 00:41:36.120
[Amit Varma]: And I was 10. And I absolutely just fell into it and just read everything by him. Now, on

00:41:36.120 --> 00:41:41.200
[Amit Varma]: the one hand, it seems to me that, you know, we can complain that there were so few books

00:41:41.200 --> 00:41:44.520
[Amit Varma]: available. So which is why, you know, you and I basically read the same kind of things.

00:41:44.520 --> 00:41:48.240
[Amit Varma]: And of course, we were indiscriminate, because you got hold of whatever you could, and today

00:41:48.240 --> 00:41:52.520
[Amit Varma]: everything is available. But on the other hand, we were enormously lucky and privileged,

00:41:52.520 --> 00:41:59.080
[Amit Varma]: because we did read a lot. And I say this in the context of seeing a little bit outside

00:41:59.080 --> 00:42:04.320
[Amit Varma]: the world that we are in, like, you know, I'm sort of struck by in one of your interviews,

00:42:04.320 --> 00:42:09.360
[Amit Varma]: you spoke about how you went to Shaheen Bagh, when that happened. And a question that you

00:42:09.360 --> 00:42:14.200
[Amit Varma]: like to ask all the women gathered there was that, quote, you're afraid of many things,

00:42:14.200 --> 00:42:18.720
[Amit Varma]: but tell me, are you having fun? Stop quote. And the reason this is significant is that

00:42:18.720 --> 00:42:25.040
[Amit Varma]: because they'd have this newfound sense of solidarity from being part of a women's movement.

00:42:25.040 --> 00:42:29.760
[Amit Varma]: And what is happening here, it seems to me is that, you know, some of them at least are

00:42:29.760 --> 00:42:35.880
[Amit Varma]: getting a glimpse of a world that they didn't really know existed or could never have experienced.

00:42:35.880 --> 00:42:39.640
[Amit Varma]: There's a sociologist called Timur Kuran, who wrote this book called Private Truths

00:42:39.640 --> 00:42:46.480
[Amit Varma]: Public Lies in 1999, where he essentially spoke about how many of us will often put

00:42:46.480 --> 00:42:52.120
[Amit Varma]: on a face, which is a lie, because we think that that's what everyone else around us thinks.

00:42:52.120 --> 00:42:56.960
[Amit Varma]: For example, before the Soviet Union collapse, the example he gave was that nobody would

00:42:56.960 --> 00:43:00.160
[Amit Varma]: express anything against the Soviet Union, because my God, and they thought they were

00:43:00.160 --> 00:43:04.440
[Amit Varma]: the only rebellious people. And then suddenly, one day, they realized that there are other

00:43:04.440 --> 00:43:08.480
[Amit Varma]: people like them. And that leads to what he calls a preference cascade, when they see

00:43:08.480 --> 00:43:13.360
[Amit Varma]: that there are others like them. And boom, it seems it feels like it happened overnight,

00:43:13.360 --> 00:43:18.200
[Amit Varma]: but they all felt that way secretly all the way through. Now, I think for us, that kind

00:43:18.200 --> 00:43:23.080
[Amit Varma]: of that awareness can happen through reading that awareness can happen through, you know,

00:43:23.080 --> 00:43:28.120
[Amit Varma]: all the privileges that we have. But for most people, that simply isn't there. Like it isn't

00:43:28.120 --> 00:43:33.400
[Amit Varma]: the case, I would imagine that most women in India are happy with the patriarchy, and

00:43:33.400 --> 00:43:37.600
[Amit Varma]: yet they are not speaking out against it, you would imagine. So now do you think that

00:43:37.600 --> 00:43:43.600
[Amit Varma]: in this kind of modern age, where you are sort of surrounded by different kinds of social

00:43:43.600 --> 00:43:48.400
[Amit Varma]: media, where you know, people like you have much more of a voice than you would have,

00:43:48.400 --> 00:43:53.240
[Amit Varma]: say, maybe in in the year 2000? You know, that there is a chance of a preference cascade

00:43:53.240 --> 00:43:58.640
[Amit Varma]: in this direction also happening, that could then lead to sort of an acceleration of the

00:43:58.640 --> 00:44:01.080
[Amit Varma]: kind of change we'd all want to see?

00:44:01.080 --> 00:44:06.600
[Guest]: Yes, and no both. I think that yes, in the sense that yes, you can see it happening among

00:44:06.600 --> 00:44:11.960
[Guest]: young women, right? So even this whole pinjra tod phenomenon. So it's a it's a movement

00:44:11.960 --> 00:44:18.240
[Guest]: on the ground. But it also has a way of communication and spreading through social media. People

00:44:18.240 --> 00:44:23.280
[Guest]: get to know about it, and then they want to do their own unit of it and all of that, right?

00:44:23.280 --> 00:44:28.960
[Guest]: So I think that it is something which has helped, of course, the internet has helped.

00:44:28.960 --> 00:44:36.120
[Guest]: And people get more, you know, they're exposed to a whole range of books or ideas or through

00:44:36.120 --> 00:44:41.320
[Guest]: other means, you know, it's not just through reading, it's also talking, listening, whatever,

00:44:41.320 --> 00:44:46.120
[Guest]: you know, they're hearing talks, they're hearing whatever. But at the same time, I think that

00:44:46.120 --> 00:44:52.160
[Guest]: there's a lot of there's a big digital divide also. So I see that there is a change happening

00:44:52.160 --> 00:44:58.680
[Guest]: in young women in rural India, or semi-rural India. I can see that happening when I visit,

00:44:58.680 --> 00:45:03.400
[Guest]: I can see it happening when, you know, there are young women there who are studying, so

00:45:03.400 --> 00:45:10.720
[Guest]: they're craving for new experiences. They are full of ideas. And it's not just young

00:45:10.720 --> 00:45:16.200
[Guest]: women, for that matter, even young boys, okay, they are full of questions. And if you just

00:45:16.200 --> 00:45:20.320
[Guest]: happen to be visiting their home, it's like they won't let you sleep at night because

00:45:20.320 --> 00:45:25.360
[Guest]: they want to surround you and keep asking you stuff because they are not getting the

00:45:25.360 --> 00:45:29.760
[Guest]: answers they want. And they are looking for answers beyond the town or the village in

00:45:29.760 --> 00:45:35.200
[Guest]: which they live, right? And I would ask them, if they're asking a lot of questions about

00:45:35.200 --> 00:45:37.360
[Guest]: Indian society, and so I would ask them,

00:45:37.360 --> 00:45:42.920
[Guest]: Aap log TV pe kya dekhte hain? Ravish ko nahi sunte kya? Because I would tell them, Ravish

00:45:42.920 --> 00:45:48.000
[Guest]: addresses this issue on that show. They wouldn't have heard of him. This was some years back,

00:45:48.000 --> 00:45:51.720
[Guest]: I remember, in Bihar. They hadn't heard of him, although Ravish is from Bihar. So I'd

00:45:51.720 --> 00:45:55.880
[Guest]: say, so what do you get on TV? What are you watching? They said, arre jo free mein channel

00:45:55.880 --> 00:45:59.320
[Guest]: aata hai, wohi toh dekhte hain. Aur free mein channel jo aata hai, woh Deepak Chaurasia,

00:45:59.320 --> 00:46:05.440
[Guest]: woh ye. So ye cheezein toh aati nahi, humaar dimaag mein ye baatein aati hain. And we don't

00:46:05.440 --> 00:46:11.200
[Guest]: know where to get the answer for it. And I realised that they are not that keen on reading,

00:46:11.200 --> 00:46:16.880
[Guest]: okay? Especially reading stuff which is written in the usual sort of, you know, political

00:46:16.880 --> 00:46:23.120
[Guest]: patrika style. They're not really readers of that kind now. They are willing to read

00:46:23.120 --> 00:46:27.800
[Guest]: literature, they're willing to read poetry, but in terms of a political polemic, they

00:46:27.800 --> 00:46:33.640
[Guest]: may or may not. Whereas they really want to listen, they want to interact, you know, they

00:46:33.640 --> 00:46:37.560
[Guest]: want to get the sense that they are asking something and able to argue and all of that.

00:46:37.560 --> 00:46:44.120
[Guest]: And I think those experiences are, we still don't realise how precious they are and how

00:46:44.120 --> 00:46:50.540
[Guest]: little we are able to create of that for most, for the large majority of our youngsters.

00:46:50.540 --> 00:46:54.520
[Guest]: And that's why when they manage to come from rural, if they manage to make it through school

00:46:54.520 --> 00:47:01.040
[Guest]: and come to university or college, that is the point at which the world is opening up.

00:47:01.040 --> 00:47:08.600
[Guest]: And that is the point at which they feel alright, now, you know, this is where suddenly, I have

00:47:08.600 --> 00:47:13.720
[Guest]: the chance to listen to so much more, know so much more and all of that.

00:47:13.720 --> 00:47:17.720
[Amit Varma]: Yeah, and this kind of tells you that there are, you know, people use phrases like malnourished,

00:47:17.720 --> 00:47:22.400
[Amit Varma]: there are multiple kinds of malnourishment that not having information, not knowing about

00:47:22.400 --> 00:47:27.980
[Amit Varma]: the world is itself one such thing. And were you ever into TikTok by any chance?

00:47:27.980 --> 00:47:32.600
[Guest]: Not at all. In fact, I'm very old fashioned that way. I was dragged kicking and screaming

00:47:32.600 --> 00:47:39.520
[Guest]: onto Facebook and Twitter later. But even now, I look even at something like Spaces

00:47:39.520 --> 00:47:42.800
[Guest]: and say, I haven't been there yet. I have no idea what it is.

00:47:42.800 --> 00:47:47.440
[Amit Varma]: No, no, I wish before it was banned, you'd check TikTok out because I just fell in love

00:47:47.440 --> 00:47:51.720
[Amit Varma]: with it. And in fact, I taught a very brief online course on TikTok and Indian society

00:47:51.720 --> 00:47:55.880
[Amit Varma]: before it got banned. And I thought that it getting banned was tragic. Because what you're

00:47:55.880 --> 00:48:00.720
[Amit Varma]: speaking of, you would see glimpses of it there like TikTok was a one app, which was

00:48:00.720 --> 00:48:05.040
[Amit Varma]: for rural India, which was for people left untouched by this. I mean, of course, city

00:48:05.040 --> 00:48:11.000
[Amit Varma]: kids also used it and all of that. But there was such an explosion of new and different

00:48:11.000 --> 00:48:16.440
[Amit Varma]: kinds of creativity with people using TikTok in all our villages and towns, especially,

00:48:16.440 --> 00:48:21.360
[Amit Varma]: I mean, I especially noticed this among people of alternate sexualities, for whom suddenly

00:48:21.360 --> 00:48:26.800
[Amit Varma]: you have all these creators of alternate sexualities creating incredible content. And, you know,

00:48:26.800 --> 00:48:31.960
[Amit Varma]: and then that was leading to some kind of a cascade where more and more creators like

00:48:31.960 --> 00:48:36.680
[Amit Varma]: that were coming up because they had new role models, which is very far away from the nonsense

00:48:36.680 --> 00:48:41.440
[Amit Varma]: that you see in our, you know, mainstream film industries. And another of the things

00:48:41.440 --> 00:48:45.040
[Amit Varma]: I noticed is that in many of those, you know, when it comes to romance, you see the woman

00:48:45.040 --> 00:48:48.440
[Amit Varma]: making the first move. And there was just this whole new kind of language happening

00:48:48.440 --> 00:48:55.840
[Guest]: and that's fantastic. Yeah, yeah. So I really wish that you had seen it, but and that the

00:48:55.840 --> 00:49:01.840
[Guest]: bandit is just, I've heard people speaking about it, but yeah, I didn't see much of it

00:49:01.840 --> 00:49:05.880
[Guest]: myself. I've seen bits of it shared here and there. And I did think that, you know, people

00:49:05.880 --> 00:49:11.200
[Guest]: are getting some control over their own, you know, some kind of space of their own to express

00:49:11.200 --> 00:49:15.120
[Guest]: and all of that. So it's very sad. Yeah, that that is shut down.

00:49:15.120 --> 00:49:21.320
[Amit Varma]: And it was evolving, you had very interesting kinds of descent also, which, you know, in

00:49:21.320 --> 00:49:27.040
[Amit Varma]: art in, in creative ways, which you wouldn't really see in any other media. So it is what

00:49:27.040 --> 00:49:32.120
[Amit Varma]: it is. Let's let's kind of go back to sort of growing up process. You're a kid in Bhilai.

00:49:32.120 --> 00:49:36.600
[Amit Varma]: And eventually you landed up in Mumbai at St. Xavier's. And then you went and did your

00:49:36.600 --> 00:49:43.320
[Amit Varma]: MPhil in JNU. Tell me about your sort of evolving conception of yourself in these times. Like,

00:49:43.320 --> 00:49:47.680
[Amit Varma]: what did you see yourself as? What did you see yourself doing? How were your interests

00:49:47.680 --> 00:49:53.640
[Amit Varma]: kind of developing and growing? And are there other directions that you could possibly have

00:49:53.640 --> 00:49:58.480
[Amit Varma]: taken? Had you not taken this one? Like, how big a role does happenstance play in where

00:49:58.480 --> 00:50:00.360
[Amit Varma]: we land up?

00:50:00.360 --> 00:50:06.200
[Guest]: I think a very big role happenstance is what I would I think, what I am today is sort of

00:50:06.200 --> 00:50:12.760
[Guest]: in spite of myself, I say that it's not, it's not only happenstance, it's about my overcoming

00:50:12.760 --> 00:50:20.160
[Guest]: my own self, my own resistance. Because I, I had thought that I would study literature,

00:50:20.160 --> 00:50:26.080
[Guest]: I might teach literature, I might be a journalist, these were possibilities that had occurred

00:50:26.080 --> 00:50:31.280
[Guest]: to me and that I had thought about and felt comfortable with. In Bhilai, anybody who didn't

00:50:31.280 --> 00:50:38.520
[Guest]: study science or who didn't do either the IIT ki tayyari or MBBS ki tayyari, basically

00:50:38.520 --> 00:50:45.080
[Guest]: were considered dropouts. So everyone in, teachers were shocked that, teachers who didn't

00:50:45.080 --> 00:50:50.480
[Guest]: know me well, there were a couple of teachers who knew what I really was. And they had told

00:50:50.480 --> 00:50:56.120
[Guest]: my parents when I was in the eighth standard, don't force her into these directions. That

00:50:56.120 --> 00:51:01.240
[Guest]: is not what she wants to do. So the thing was that then, you know, the arts wale jo

00:51:01.240 --> 00:51:05.040
[Guest]: bachche the, they were considered to be, oh, you know, so everybody's shocked, you know,

00:51:05.040 --> 00:51:10.060
[Guest]: why are you opting for that? And then there was a pressure that, okay, if you're opting

00:51:10.060 --> 00:51:15.400
[Guest]: for that, you must be wanting to prepare for the IAS. So then my mother also would tell

00:51:15.400 --> 00:51:19.360
[Guest]: me, do you think you want to, everybody's saying it, what is it about? So once when

00:51:19.360 --> 00:51:24.520
[Guest]: I visited Delhi, my aunt who lived in Delhi at that time, she was a very wonderful woman,

00:51:24.520 --> 00:51:30.760
[Guest]: she's no more. So she was a very gregarious, very social person, not me. I was a very private

00:51:30.760 --> 00:51:36.720
[Guest]: person, very private, always with a few select friends, not interested in meeting everyone,

00:51:36.720 --> 00:51:42.760
[Guest]: talking to everyone. And she was the opposite. And she told me that, I don't think you're

00:51:42.760 --> 00:51:47.920
[Guest]: going to like this. So she said, look, if you want, I have a friend who's an IAS officer,

00:51:47.920 --> 00:51:53.600
[Guest]: and I will take you and you can sit outside her door, watch what she does in the day and

00:51:53.600 --> 00:51:58.840
[Guest]: tell me, do you really see yourself doing that? And I didn't do that eventually, I didn't

00:51:58.840 --> 00:52:06.880
[Guest]: go and observe. But in talking to her, I realized that no, I wasn't really at all interested

00:52:06.880 --> 00:52:12.400
[Guest]: in that. So I said, I don't think that's me at all. I'm not a very good organizer, certainly

00:52:12.400 --> 00:52:18.640
[Guest]: not an administrator, not that kind of an authority figure. That's not my thing. Plus,

00:52:18.640 --> 00:52:25.540
[Guest]: you know, people dealing is not my best strength is what I thought at that time. So I remained

00:52:25.540 --> 00:52:31.240
[Guest]: my private little self with a few very good friends in Bombay, but very few and, you know,

00:52:31.240 --> 00:52:39.240
[Guest]: very, very close, but very few. But in, I was very, very concerned in Bombay by the

00:52:39.240 --> 00:52:47.040
[Guest]: communal violence that happened in 92, 93. So that I was in Bombay when the Babri Masjid

00:52:47.040 --> 00:52:53.680
[Guest]: came down, I was in Bombay when the riots happened, and when the blasts happened. And

00:52:53.680 --> 00:53:02.440
[Guest]: that stuff did leave a big, big impact on me, because I had friends, older friends,

00:53:02.440 --> 00:53:06.560
[Guest]: who were journalists. So they would drop in in the college. So they were formerly from

00:53:06.560 --> 00:53:11.040
[Guest]: the college. So they would drop in, talk to, there was a group of us. So there was teachers,

00:53:11.040 --> 00:53:16.520
[Guest]: students, and there was a place called the Social Science Center, the Social Science

00:53:16.520 --> 00:53:20.040
[Guest]: Center. And we used to hang out in the San Xavier Social Science Center, where I used

00:53:20.040 --> 00:53:26.880
[Guest]: to help out as a librarian with the books and stuff there, me and my friend. So there

00:53:26.880 --> 00:53:31.240
[Guest]: people would come and describe that we are journalists, and we've seen police killing

00:53:31.240 --> 00:53:35.720
[Guest]: Muslims running away. And, you know, these are not all stories that we are being allowed

00:53:35.720 --> 00:53:40.560
[Guest]: to print even. So these were journalists with publications, good publications, like the

00:53:40.560 --> 00:53:45.200
[Guest]: Times of India and all, very deeply disturbed by what they were seeing, not able to report

00:53:45.200 --> 00:53:51.680
[Guest]: on all of that. So I knew that this was an anti-Muslim pogrom that was happening. I knew

00:53:51.680 --> 00:53:58.480
[Guest]: that one of my closest friends, who's still my best friend now, so I would visit her house

00:53:58.480 --> 00:54:04.000
[Guest]: all the time in Bombay. She was a Bombaywali. And her parents, her mother, I would meet

00:54:04.000 --> 00:54:08.640
[Guest]: her mother, and her mother would tell me, you know, stuff she had heard, which was all

00:54:08.640 --> 00:54:14.000
[Guest]: myths, okay, that, oh, Matunga, there's this big sari store, and it's been burned down

00:54:14.000 --> 00:54:20.160
[Guest]: by the Muslims. So I would store this information away, my friend and I would store it away,

00:54:20.160 --> 00:54:25.760
[Guest]: then actually ask someone to check, and then come back, you know, do our own fact check,

00:54:25.760 --> 00:54:30.520
[Guest]: basically, and come back and say, no, it's standing. Ask so and so. They're telling you

00:54:30.520 --> 00:54:34.840
[Guest]: the damn thing is standing. This is a lie. Okay. So you're being told these lies by the

00:54:34.840 --> 00:54:41.880
[Guest]: local Shiv Senics and the local RSS people. So the thing was, you could see this happening

00:54:41.880 --> 00:54:46.520
[Guest]: and it was deeply disturbing. I think most disturbing also because of the stuff that

00:54:46.520 --> 00:54:51.640
[Guest]: was being said at that time, by these groups about women, right? So I could, I had no trouble

00:54:51.640 --> 00:54:57.080
[Guest]: at all connecting it with all the stuff I'd read about Nazis. It was instant. So because,

00:54:57.080 --> 00:55:02.080
[Guest]: and I would feel totally indignant because it was totally smothering to think about these

00:55:02.080 --> 00:55:07.240
[Guest]: people marching on the streets, sort of owning the streets. And immediately you realize that,

00:55:07.240 --> 00:55:12.880
[Guest]: you know, as somebody who was so comfortable in Bombay, but when your rioters are in possession

00:55:12.880 --> 00:55:18.480
[Guest]: of the streets, it becomes a very different thing because then you are seen as someone

00:55:18.480 --> 00:55:24.800
[Guest]: who could be a target if they didn't like what you said or did or wore or whatever,

00:55:24.800 --> 00:55:25.800
[Guest]: right?

00:55:25.800 --> 00:55:30.320
[Guest]: Another very formative thing I should mention actually is that was Xavier's itself. I mean,

00:55:30.320 --> 00:55:35.880
[Guest]: that was a big point, not in terms of activism. I think the people I knew who later became

00:55:35.880 --> 00:55:41.320
[Guest]: activists there didn't think of me as being a potential activist. Okay. So even people

00:55:41.320 --> 00:55:47.840
[Guest]: like Arun Ferreira, who's now in prison, Bhima Koregaon, he and several others at that time,

00:55:47.840 --> 00:55:52.600
[Guest]: they were activists. And I don't think they, you know, I'd hang out with them all the time,

00:55:52.600 --> 00:56:00.920
[Guest]: but I don't think they really saw me as activist material as such. But in college, my English

00:56:00.920 --> 00:56:05.960
[Guest]: literature classes, so there was this teacher called Eunice de Souza, who was absolutely

00:56:05.960 --> 00:56:11.200
[Guest]: the most remarkable teacher and poet. You've heard of her, I'm sure. So her classes and

00:56:11.200 --> 00:56:16.840
[Guest]: her, especially when she taught us, I remember the awakening I had when she taught the war

00:56:16.840 --> 00:56:23.320
[Guest]: poets, basically the First World War British poets. So that was anti-war poetry, basically.

00:56:23.320 --> 00:56:28.560
[Guest]: Or even if it wasn't anti-war, it was by people who were fighting the war, who were soldiers,

00:56:28.560 --> 00:56:33.560
[Guest]: who thought they were good British soldiers. So they were not, you know, they were not

00:56:33.560 --> 00:56:39.120
[Guest]: dropping out as soldiers. They were not deserting the army. But they were writing about what

00:56:39.120 --> 00:56:47.000
[Guest]: they saw, and they were expressing their loss of illusions about what war was, and their

00:56:47.000 --> 00:56:53.800
[Guest]: extreme discomfort with the patriotic jingoism about soldiers and giving themselves up for

00:56:53.800 --> 00:56:59.080
[Guest]: the nation and all of that. And I know that that was the point at which I sort of stopped.

00:56:59.080 --> 00:57:03.760
[Guest]: As a child, I always used to stand up for the national anthem. If it played on TV or

00:57:03.760 --> 00:57:08.320
[Guest]: radio, you know, there I was. But at that point, I started wondering whether I wanted

00:57:08.320 --> 00:57:14.560
[Guest]: to do that every time or not. I remember thinking that I need to be thinking about this, what

00:57:14.560 --> 00:57:19.920
[Guest]: this means. And definitely the ideas about war and nation and all of that were very badly

00:57:19.920 --> 00:57:24.560
[Guest]: shaken up once. So that was, I mean, that was also formative in ways which I didn't

00:57:24.560 --> 00:57:30.240
[Guest]: realize at that time, probably. But they were formative in the sense that when I saw army

00:57:30.240 --> 00:57:36.800
[Guest]: out on the streets in Bombay, so they came to very belatedly to control the riots. The

00:57:36.800 --> 00:57:44.520
[Guest]: riots, I'd already seen curfews, curfew-ridden streets. I knew, I'd seen VT station full

00:57:44.520 --> 00:57:49.920
[Guest]: of Muslims who were fleeing. So I knew that stuff was happening. And then there was the

00:57:49.920 --> 00:57:55.480
[Guest]: army. And I remember, you know, walking out on the streets when the army was doing a,

00:57:55.480 --> 00:58:00.640
[Guest]: you know, basically the army vehicles were moving. And you would have thought that the

00:58:00.640 --> 00:58:07.480
[Guest]: army has come to bring order, right? And in a way they did. But the men in the army, you

00:58:07.480 --> 00:58:14.640
[Guest]: know, the ones who were in that, in those vehicles, young men in uniform, their presence

00:58:14.640 --> 00:58:19.000
[Guest]: on the street was quite frightening to me as a woman, I remember. Because they would

00:58:19.000 --> 00:58:26.640
[Guest]: be shouting from those, you know, their vehicles, they would be shouting, you know, lewd abuse

00:58:26.640 --> 00:58:32.200
[Guest]: and stuff like that. And it was not something you were particularly used to in Bombay, I

00:58:32.200 --> 00:58:37.800
[Guest]: can tell you that, you know, because, and it didn't feel, and to my mind, I mean, I

00:58:37.800 --> 00:58:43.200
[Guest]: was not at all comfortable with what that represented either. Because it felt as though

00:58:43.200 --> 00:58:48.760
[Guest]: the city had become a very alien kind of place, you know. So the city which I, I still love

00:58:48.760 --> 00:58:52.600
[Guest]: Bombay. I still, I cannot, it's a love that doesn't go away because it's the place where

00:58:52.600 --> 00:59:00.200
[Guest]: I first became an adult. And I love that place. But I know that that sense of discomfort,

00:59:00.200 --> 00:59:05.080
[Guest]: you know, Anand Patwardhan's film Ram Ke Naam. So Ram Ke Naam has a scene right at the end

00:59:05.080 --> 00:59:12.080
[Guest]: where he's filming a march that is for secularism. And that reaches near Flora Fountain, I think

00:59:12.080 --> 00:59:19.240
[Guest]: it is some such place near, I think it's Churchgate or Flora Fountain, somewhere there. And there's

00:59:19.240 --> 00:59:27.760
[Guest]: a stone pelting by the, by the Shiv Senex and Hindutva right wing people. So I, my friend

00:59:27.760 --> 00:59:32.040
[Guest]: and I were in college. So our college was Xavier's. We walked down from there. And we

00:59:32.040 --> 00:59:36.640
[Guest]: had another older friend with us who was a former student of the college and former student

00:59:36.640 --> 00:59:41.960
[Guest]: of JNU also. So he had gone in a very big brotherly fashion with us, basically a little

00:59:41.960 --> 00:59:47.400
[Guest]: protective. So we went and when this stone pelting started, this guy who had gone with

00:59:47.400 --> 00:59:53.760
[Guest]: us started saying, I want you guys back. So he kind of persuaded us to, you know, turn

00:59:53.760 --> 00:59:57.840
[Guest]: back. We didn't want to, but after hanging out for about 15 minutes in the middle of

00:59:57.840 --> 01:00:03.840
[Guest]: the pelting stones, he said, no, if you're, and he looks at me and he said, tumhara saar

01:00:03.840 --> 01:00:07.960
[Guest]: fatega toh you don't even have, like your parents aren't here or whatever. You're in

01:00:07.960 --> 01:00:12.840
[Guest]: a hostel. Just, just come out of this now, you know, you've done your protesting now,

01:00:12.840 --> 01:00:18.040
[Guest]: just come right back. So he became very parental and took us back very sweetly. But whenever

01:00:18.040 --> 01:00:23.280
[Guest]: I see Ram Ke Naam and I see that, I think to myself, yes, I was there. That's good.

01:00:23.280 --> 01:00:26.560
[Guest]: But that's all. I didn't do anything more in the name of activism. The rest happened

01:00:26.560 --> 01:00:30.560
[Guest]: when I came to JNU for my MA.

01:00:30.560 --> 01:00:35.240
[Amit Varma]: Yeah, that's, that's actually very evocative. And it's very interesting. You know, I'm reminded

01:00:35.240 --> 01:00:39.440
[Amit Varma]: of this book by Chyna Meeville called The City and the City, which is of, you know,

01:00:39.440 --> 01:00:43.760
[Amit Varma]: one city that is also, you know, there are two sort of simultaneous overlapping cities.

01:00:43.760 --> 01:00:48.280
[Amit Varma]: And it seems to me that that's also the case with Bombay, that it is actually so many different

01:00:48.280 --> 01:00:52.600
[Amit Varma]: cities. I mean, the Bombay by night is so different from the Bombay by day. And these

01:00:52.600 --> 01:00:56.560
[Amit Varma]: different versions also include alternate realities, like when that lady, you know,

01:00:56.560 --> 01:01:01.080
[Amit Varma]: your friend's mom tells you that XYZ store has been burned down, and you find that XYZ

01:01:01.080 --> 01:01:05.520
[Amit Varma]: store is still standing. It's like in a parallel universe, it's like the city divides into

01:01:05.520 --> 01:01:09.360
[Amit Varma]: two, right? And one version of the city has XYZ store and in the other version of the

01:01:09.360 --> 01:01:14.760
[Amit Varma]: story, it's ruined. And you have that alternate reality just coming through the ages and just

01:01:14.760 --> 01:01:19.480
[Amit Varma]: shaping so many people who live in a city that we don't see and we live in a city that

01:01:19.480 --> 01:01:24.040
[Amit Varma]: they don't see, which is, you know, kind of poignant in a sense. So, how did you then

01:01:24.040 --> 01:01:28.920
[Amit Varma]: eventually, after all this, get into activism and then get into politics?

01:01:28.920 --> 01:01:34.760
[Guest]: Yes, that is the part where the in spite of myself comes in because I came to JNU. So,

01:01:34.760 --> 01:01:40.840
[Guest]: my same friend from Bombay, she and I got into JNU together, she in the German Studies

01:01:40.840 --> 01:01:48.240
[Guest]: Center and me in English literature. So, we were very excited. We liked JNU. We didn't

01:01:48.240 --> 01:01:54.560
[Guest]: like Delhi much, but we did like JNU. And we liked classes, teaching, all of that. But

01:01:54.560 --> 01:02:00.080
[Guest]: JNU also has a lot of politics. And we were immediately interested as soon as we came.

01:02:00.080 --> 01:02:04.200
[Guest]: So, we were immediately interested in figuring out who would we like to vote for. So, you

01:02:04.200 --> 01:02:10.560
[Guest]: basically come to JNU in June, July, and elections happen. You basically come in July and your

01:02:10.560 --> 01:02:14.800
[Guest]: elections happen in October. So, you don't have very long, you know, two, three months

01:02:14.800 --> 01:02:20.120
[Guest]: to basically figure out your mind. It's you get a very short kind of crash course in what's

01:02:20.120 --> 01:02:26.320
[Guest]: happening. And we found that interesting without being involved, right? So, we saw that, you

01:02:26.320 --> 01:02:32.880
[Guest]: know, in 93, when we joined, then there was this new student, relatively new student organization

01:02:32.880 --> 01:02:37.400
[Guest]: called ISA. We didn't know it was new. By the way, the first student organization which

01:02:37.400 --> 01:02:43.240
[Guest]: contacted us was the ABVP. How? Because in the, actually, the letter we got from the

01:02:43.240 --> 01:02:49.480
[Guest]: university telling us that you have got admission to JNU, so that in the official envelope,

01:02:49.480 --> 01:02:57.720
[Guest]: there was a card by the ABVP signed by a woman who was an ABVP office bearer. Okay. And I

01:02:57.720 --> 01:03:01.840
[Guest]: remember that when that, when I got that in Bhilai, and my friend got it in Bombay, both

01:03:01.840 --> 01:03:07.000
[Guest]: of us had spoken on phone and said, what on earth? Because we knew that if we didn't know

01:03:07.000 --> 01:03:11.680
[Guest]: anything else about politics, but we knew that the ABVP represented these right wing

01:03:11.680 --> 01:03:16.680
[Guest]: fellows and we were like, what is this? Is this what is going to happen in JNU? These

01:03:16.680 --> 01:03:21.400
[Guest]: guys are sending letters with the administration. But then we came and realized that they had

01:03:21.400 --> 01:03:25.520
[Guest]: basically managed to find someone in the admin who had agreed to put this letter in for them

01:03:25.520 --> 01:03:30.760
[Guest]: and it had become quite an issue and people had protested it and all. But then the main

01:03:30.760 --> 01:03:34.880
[Guest]: jagda then was, of course, ABVP was there. And then there was the SFI, which was the

01:03:34.880 --> 01:03:41.000
[Guest]: established large left organization and there was ISA. So, we eventually became very close

01:03:41.000 --> 01:03:46.600
[Guest]: friends with some ISA women. And ISA had a lot of very strong women. And what clinched

01:03:46.600 --> 01:03:52.440
[Guest]: it for us was that whether it was the ABVP or whether it was the more conservative left,

01:03:52.440 --> 01:03:58.040
[Guest]: which was coming to us, they would both try to scare us off from the ISA feminists. Okay.

01:03:58.040 --> 01:04:02.440
[Guest]: So they would both try to tell us that these women are. So that was an immediate clincher

01:04:02.440 --> 01:04:07.520
[Guest]: for us. They were like, oh, really? There are these fallen women? Okay, where are they?

01:04:07.520 --> 01:04:13.640
[Guest]: That sounds interesting. Let's go befriend them. So, we kind of really hit it off with

01:04:13.640 --> 01:04:18.640
[Guest]: them because it was so clear that they were feminists and they were their lifelong friends

01:04:18.640 --> 01:04:27.000
[Guest]: now. But I never thought of getting active with them at all. So, 94 happens and 94, I

01:04:27.000 --> 01:04:34.520
[Guest]: voted for ISA. But 94 happens and in 94, you know, the ISA really tried to get me and my

01:04:34.520 --> 01:04:40.640
[Guest]: friend and some other friends of mine to contest elections. And I resisted it like the dickens.

01:04:40.640 --> 01:04:47.560
[Guest]: Okay. I really, I, because I could feel the pull. I could feel that I can do this, but

01:04:47.560 --> 01:04:53.440
[Guest]: I felt tremendous fear because I felt like it'll just sweep me away. And everyone knew

01:04:53.440 --> 01:04:58.080
[Guest]: that I'm the one who's kind of holding the others also back. Okay. Because we would go

01:04:58.080 --> 01:05:02.740
[Guest]: file our nominations and then the next morning come and take them back. And the person who's

01:05:02.740 --> 01:05:08.160
[Guest]: my partner, he was the secretary then. Very thrilled when suddenly five women have filed

01:05:08.160 --> 01:05:13.000
[Guest]: nominations and next day, you know, four of them are taking it back. Very irritated he

01:05:13.000 --> 01:05:17.360
[Guest]: was. Okay. And he's like, what on earth? And I hadn't taken membership of ISA either. And

01:05:17.360 --> 01:05:21.280
[Guest]: I'm like, nahi, nahi, nahi, apni individuality rakhni hai aur sangathan ka part ho jaoge

01:05:21.280 --> 01:05:26.160
[Guest]: toh. It's a pleasure. Mine, my ideas won't be mine. No, no, no, no, no, no, no. So, I

01:05:26.160 --> 01:05:32.400
[Guest]: didn't contest. But I didn't contest. But in return, I promised to campaign for ISA.

01:05:32.400 --> 01:05:38.200
[Guest]: And that was the first sense of a little shame. Because I was, in my school of languages,

01:05:38.200 --> 01:05:43.520
[Guest]: I was taking around this group of the ISA candidates. So there are five councillor posts.

01:05:43.520 --> 01:05:49.560
[Guest]: Had we contested, it would have been at least three women, if not four, and one guy. Okay.

01:05:49.560 --> 01:05:54.920
[Guest]: This way it turned out to be all five guys. So every time, and the campaigners were all

01:05:54.920 --> 01:06:01.500
[Guest]: women, articulate women, me, my friends, all were extremely. So we'd walk into a classroom

01:06:01.500 --> 01:06:05.860
[Guest]: and these guys would introduce themselves. And some of us would also do the talking.

01:06:05.860 --> 01:06:11.160
[Guest]: And in every class, there would be people asking, why is there no woman on the panel?

01:06:11.160 --> 01:06:16.320
[Guest]: And what's wrong with ISA? And here you guys are. And these boys would give us the dirts.

01:06:16.320 --> 01:06:22.440
[Guest]: Okay. Like saying, look, they're thinking it's our fault. And you people should have

01:06:22.440 --> 01:06:28.280
[Guest]: been the candidates and you guys have made us contest. So we would really be like, kya

01:06:28.280 --> 01:06:32.640
[Guest]: aap bataayen? Toh pehli baar thoda sharam laga. But uske baad bhi after that election

01:06:32.640 --> 01:06:38.280
[Guest]: also. So in that election, this Shiv Sena guy was a candidate, Bharti Vidyarthi Sena.

01:06:38.280 --> 01:06:44.040
[Guest]: So he made some horrible anti-Muslim speech. And then he came to our Ganga hostel mess

01:06:44.040 --> 01:06:50.480
[Guest]: and made a very terrible, a long speech about how, about the Hindu Rashtra. So we had gone

01:06:50.480 --> 01:06:55.800
[Guest]: in there and started sort of heckling him, asking him, what will you do with us? You

01:06:55.800 --> 01:07:00.480
[Guest]: know, who don't think of ourselves as being Indian first or religion first. He said, you

01:07:00.480 --> 01:07:05.760
[Guest]: have to be Hindu first, then you can be Indian and then you have to be whatever sect you

01:07:05.760 --> 01:07:10.760
[Guest]: are and all of that. So we had said, we are women first. What do you do with us? We don't

01:07:10.760 --> 01:07:15.680
[Guest]: really care which country we belong to. We are Indians and so theek hai, we are Indians,

01:07:15.680 --> 01:07:19.160
[Guest]: but we are women. Wherever we live in the world, we are going to be treated a certain

01:07:19.160 --> 01:07:24.440
[Guest]: way. What do you make of us? So he said, bahot se jail hain and all of that in a very dramatic

01:07:24.440 --> 01:07:29.600
[Guest]: way. He was a very good looking guy. So Ravi Dvivedi, his name was, he died later in a

01:07:29.600 --> 01:07:34.680
[Guest]: pretty tragic accident sometime later. I heard about that. Bhopal ka ladka tha, lekin bahot

01:07:34.680 --> 01:07:43.200
[Guest]: good looking tha aur bahot bade ada se kaha usne yeh baat. We, of course, totally freaked

01:07:43.200 --> 01:07:48.320
[Guest]: out and also because we could see our own women friends who were Maharashtrian girls

01:07:48.320 --> 01:07:54.160
[Guest]: and they were supporting this guy. So they were in that mess with him. So then we rushed

01:07:54.160 --> 01:07:57.840
[Guest]: to the ISA public meeting and got really, we threw ourselves night and day into the

01:07:57.840 --> 01:08:05.320
[Guest]: ISA campaign because we wanted them to win and we wanted these guys to get to lose, ABVP

01:08:05.320 --> 01:08:10.080
[Guest]: to lose and all of that. So after that also, but after the elections also, I wanted to

01:08:10.080 --> 01:08:16.160
[Guest]: again retreat. I didn't want to be involved. But again, it was a feminist thing. ISA and

01:08:16.160 --> 01:08:22.040
[Guest]: SFI won the election. So ISA won the president's post that year and SFI won other posts. In

01:08:22.040 --> 01:08:27.160
[Guest]: 2003, ISA had won all the top three posts and the last post was went to SFI. So it remained

01:08:27.160 --> 01:08:32.800
[Guest]: with the left. But there was also a lot of quarreling on the left. So a lot of arguments

01:08:32.800 --> 01:08:39.440
[Guest]: on the left. But we did have some very good friends in the SFI also who were basically,

01:08:39.440 --> 01:08:45.520
[Guest]: again, the feminists were our friends. So there were feminists in the SFI some who were

01:08:45.520 --> 01:08:52.840
[Guest]: good friends. And it was again, a feminist outrage that led me to get active in ISA finally,

01:08:52.840 --> 01:08:58.040
[Guest]: the last barrier basically. So the last barrier was that, you know, there was an ISA conference

01:08:58.040 --> 01:09:06.080
[Guest]: happening to select leadership. And there's factions and stuff about, you know, so I didn't

01:09:06.080 --> 01:09:10.680
[Guest]: know any of this. And I decided my woman friend who was the leader there, she had decided,

01:09:10.680 --> 01:09:15.240
[Guest]: she nominated all our names, you know, three or four of us. So we had all prepared to say

01:09:15.240 --> 01:09:20.120
[Guest]: no, no, no, we don't want to be in the leadership and all. Leave us, leave our names out. In

01:09:20.120 --> 01:09:26.320
[Guest]: the meantime, there was this hapless guy who stood up, and he spoke. And he said, jab ek

01:09:26.320 --> 01:09:31.360
[Guest]: hai humare paas mein, ek Tithi Bhattacharya hai, one woman we have, no, in the leadership.

01:09:31.360 --> 01:09:37.020
[Guest]: So why do we need four or five more? And then my shyest friend, the one who'd never spoken

01:09:37.020 --> 01:09:42.400
[Guest]: in public, okay, she went huffing and puffing to the stage and suddenly burst out into an

01:09:42.400 --> 01:09:47.560
[Guest]: angry speech, okay, saying that, what is it? Are we all, you know, just body parts over

01:09:47.560 --> 01:09:51.920
[Guest]: there? Irreplaceable one by the other, we are all separate people. You have so many

01:09:51.920 --> 01:09:56.360
[Guest]: men, nobody's saying you have one man, why do you need more? What is this and all? And

01:09:56.360 --> 01:10:00.200
[Guest]: all of us then went and gave speeches and all and immediately went into the methrutval

01:10:00.200 --> 01:10:04.680
[Guest]: leadership. And my friend was so happy, the one who was already, the two friends we had

01:10:04.680 --> 01:10:09.960
[Guest]: who were already in the, you know, leadership there, they felt like that guy had done their

01:10:09.960 --> 01:10:18.040
[Guest]: job, okay. They were very, very grateful to him. They were like, oh, so they said we couldn't,

01:10:18.040 --> 01:10:24.400
[Guest]: he couldn't have done better had we paid him, you know. And then of course, the last barrier

01:10:24.400 --> 01:10:29.960
[Guest]: was when I contested elections. Again, I didn't want to contest. I was very reluctant to contest.

01:10:29.960 --> 01:10:35.840
[Guest]: But then, yeah, I was kind of persuaded by Chandrashekhar ki laddo chupchap and all of

01:10:35.840 --> 01:10:41.800
[Guest]: that. So then I contested and won to my shock and surprise. So yeah, after that, I didn't

01:10:41.800 --> 01:10:46.200
[Guest]: hesitate anymore. I took on a lot of responsibilities after that.

01:10:46.200 --> 01:10:53.240
[Amit Varma]: And Chandrashekhar, you're referring to Chandrashekhar Prasad, who was killed tragically, right?

01:10:53.240 --> 01:10:57.520
[Amit Varma]: The way you've told the story, it can totally be a web series, you know, pivotal scene guy

01:10:57.520 --> 01:11:02.240
[Amit Varma]: goes and says these things, shy girl gets up. So tell me something earlier, you've spoken

01:11:02.240 --> 01:11:06.480
[Amit Varma]: about how you were also, I mean, you didn't use the term shy, but you were kind of happy

01:11:06.480 --> 01:11:12.000
[Amit Varma]: spending time with yourself, not a very outgoing, gregarious person, as such. But then when

01:11:12.000 --> 01:11:15.960
[Amit Varma]: you get into politics, when you get into activism, you're making speeches, you kind of have to

01:11:15.960 --> 01:11:21.440
[Amit Varma]: come out of yourself. What was that sort of process like that learning to do all of those

01:11:21.440 --> 01:11:24.560
[Amit Varma]: things? Tell me about that.

01:11:24.560 --> 01:11:29.600
[Guest]: That was the biggest challenge for me. And that continues to be a challenge, I'd say.

01:11:29.600 --> 01:11:36.480
[Guest]: Because I was and am, you know, basically a very private person who, you know, it's

01:11:36.480 --> 01:11:41.880
[Guest]: the kind of person, if the world was an ideal place, then I would just like to be teaching

01:11:41.880 --> 01:11:47.000
[Guest]: and reading and writing and living on a mountainside with a dog or something like that, you know,

01:11:47.000 --> 01:11:51.680
[Guest]: dog and cat. So that's me. That's my ideal life. And I sometimes, you know, daydream

01:11:51.680 --> 01:11:57.080
[Guest]: and think, kash, you know, kisi din revolution ke baad, but I know ki revolution ho bhi jaye

01:11:57.080 --> 01:12:02.600
[Guest]: toh revolution ke baad kaam badh jayega, ghatega nahi. So anyway, the thing is that I used

01:12:02.600 --> 01:12:08.760
[Guest]: to resist, you know, so I know that when I contested elections, suddenly I, you know,

01:12:08.760 --> 01:12:14.680
[Guest]: I was giving all my time to campaigning, right? So the day the elections ended and we won,

01:12:14.680 --> 01:12:18.680
[Guest]: so Chandrashekhar and I had won, the other two people on our panel didn't win. So he

01:12:18.680 --> 01:12:23.800
[Guest]: won president, I was joint secretary. So the same evening, he came to my hostel, called

01:12:23.800 --> 01:12:29.360
[Guest]: me down and said, chalo chalna hai. Maine kaha ho gaya na, elections. Now kaha chalna

01:12:29.360 --> 01:12:33.840
[Guest]: hai? So he's like, what do you think? People have voted for you. Come with me. We have

01:12:33.840 --> 01:12:39.000
[Guest]: to go say thanks to people and all of that. So I went reluctantly. And on the way, you

01:12:39.000 --> 01:12:42.600
[Guest]: know, and I realized how he's meeting people, people are chatting, people are talking and

01:12:42.600 --> 01:12:48.760
[Guest]: he's just, people are telling him all kinds of things about their family members, this,

01:12:48.760 --> 01:12:53.520
[Guest]: that. So at the end of it, I was like, when will I get time to study if I'm going to be

01:12:53.520 --> 01:12:59.000
[Guest]: doing this? So he gave me one look and tried to talk to me and persuade me ki nahi, you

01:12:59.000 --> 01:13:03.600
[Guest]: know, and I realized that my worst nightmares have come true. My time is no longer my own

01:13:03.600 --> 01:13:09.240
[Guest]: and I was really panicking. But I think that that basically started it, that gradually,

01:13:09.240 --> 01:13:15.320
[Guest]: you know, and he played a very big part in that. He and my partner also, who was also,

01:13:15.320 --> 01:13:19.840
[Guest]: who still, I mean, he doesn't really, he is in a sense, he's private in the sense he doesn't

01:13:19.840 --> 01:13:24.760
[Guest]: like social media. He doesn't want his name out anywhere. He, you know, mostly it's all

01:13:24.760 --> 01:13:32.120
[Guest]: behind the scenes work. But he was not someone who considered his time and his space to be

01:13:32.120 --> 01:13:38.000
[Guest]: his own. So he had, you know, his room would always be open. So Chandu's also and my partner's

01:13:38.000 --> 01:13:42.640
[Guest]: also. So these were people who lived their lives very much in the public, you know, and

01:13:42.640 --> 01:13:48.400
[Guest]: so they, you know, seeing them and figuring out that there seems to be a reason for this.

01:13:48.400 --> 01:13:55.360
[Guest]: It's not just because you want people's votes, you know, it's actually because this is a

01:13:55.360 --> 01:14:00.280
[Guest]: job, just listening to people, just someone coming and telling them how worried they are

01:14:00.280 --> 01:14:04.680
[Guest]: about their mother who's sick back in a village. Just someone who's coming and telling them

01:14:04.680 --> 01:14:09.440
[Guest]: about their love life and, you know, how they are suffering because they think they're feeling

01:14:09.440 --> 01:14:14.480
[Guest]: rejected or something. All kinds of things they would come in. So not all of them are

01:14:14.480 --> 01:14:18.280
[Guest]: things which you're going to go and deal with as a neta, you know. But the point is that

01:14:18.280 --> 01:14:27.160
[Guest]: being a neta meant that you are actually available to people for a lot of things. And that, you

01:14:27.160 --> 01:14:34.200
[Guest]: know, gradually I did adjust to it, but I still find it a challenge. So I still need

01:14:34.200 --> 01:14:41.160
[Guest]: to and I accept it about myself. I'm like, OK, I am like that. So I need to recharge

01:14:41.160 --> 01:14:47.160
[Guest]: sometimes. I need to switch off sometimes. I do need to take off and have some private

01:14:47.160 --> 01:14:52.680
[Guest]: time myself. So I do that sometimes when it's possible to do it, you know. And then I feel

01:14:52.680 --> 01:14:58.320
[Guest]: like, OK, now, you know, I feel restored and I can again be at beck and call of anybody

01:14:58.320 --> 01:15:03.320
[Guest]: and everybody all times of day and night.

01:15:03.320 --> 01:15:08.760
[Amit Varma]: So now, you know, most of us in our journeys, the things we do are instrumental. So if I'm

01:15:08.760 --> 01:15:12.480
[Amit Varma]: studying this, it's because I want to become this. Or if I'm, you know, doing this work

01:15:12.480 --> 01:15:16.200
[Amit Varma]: experience is because I want to do that next. This is what it will do for my career, so

01:15:16.200 --> 01:15:20.280
[Amit Varma]: on and so forth. But it seems to me that with a certain kind of people, you know, whether

01:15:20.280 --> 01:15:25.000
[Amit Varma]: it's an artist or whether it's a politician or whether it's a whatever, at some point,

01:15:25.000 --> 01:15:29.400
[Amit Varma]: that becomes a calling, you know, in the way that you mentioned Chandrasekhar and your

01:15:29.400 --> 01:15:33.560
[Amit Varma]: partner, that at some point the doors are open and people can come in and talk and that

01:15:33.560 --> 01:15:38.160
[Amit Varma]: becomes a calling and that becomes your life. So, you know, and from what it seems to me,

01:15:38.160 --> 01:15:41.560
[Amit Varma]: the day after you win the election, you're not there yet, because you're like, hey, how

01:15:41.560 --> 01:15:46.160
[Amit Varma]: will I study? Why do I have to go now? But then you become that, right? So what is that

01:15:46.160 --> 01:15:51.640
[Amit Varma]: shift like? What is the transition like? Is there a moment where you step back and say,

01:15:51.640 --> 01:15:56.880
[Amit Varma]: okay, this is me, this is me for the rest of my life. This is what I do. Is there something

01:15:56.880 --> 01:15:57.880
[Amit Varma]: like that?

01:15:57.880 --> 01:16:04.560
[Guest]: There wasn't a moment. I think it happened over some time. And I didn't really, it wasn't

01:16:04.560 --> 01:16:10.480
[Guest]: a moment at all. So I think it was a negotiation throughout and it took time. So I know that

01:16:10.480 --> 01:16:19.320
[Guest]: in April of 94, was it? No, April of 95, it must have been. Yeah. So that time, you know,

01:16:19.320 --> 01:16:24.120
[Guest]: you had your end semester exams coming and assignments to write and so much work, you

01:16:24.120 --> 01:16:28.440
[Guest]: know, you didn't type in those days. So my hands and my handwriting is very bad. So it

01:16:28.440 --> 01:16:33.680
[Guest]: was really difficult to, you know, write and took me time and all of that. So at that time,

01:16:33.680 --> 01:16:38.520
[Guest]: you know, that was time when you only studied. But at that time, you know, there was supposed

01:16:38.520 --> 01:16:43.880
[Guest]: to be an important sort of meeting in the university, which was supposed to take decisions

01:16:43.880 --> 01:16:48.400
[Guest]: about fee hikes and stuff. So the idea was that there was to be a march to the HRD ministry

01:16:48.400 --> 01:16:54.080
[Guest]: also to say, no, don't hike college fees and university fees and all. And I was like, okay,

01:16:54.080 --> 01:16:59.120
[Guest]: thoda kaam kar denge, parcha-parcha aayega toh hum bandh denge, type ka. But basically

01:16:59.120 --> 01:17:04.560
[Guest]: I realized that no, it can't happen like that. We all have to take responsibility. Otherwise

01:17:04.560 --> 01:17:08.800
[Guest]: the burden falls only on two, three people. How are they supposed to spare the time? So

01:17:08.800 --> 01:17:14.000
[Guest]: gradually after a lot of arguments, this, you know, I came to realize this. Again, you

01:17:14.000 --> 01:17:19.160
[Guest]: know, my partner is a very, very big part in realizing that because he, and he made

01:17:19.160 --> 01:17:23.800
[Guest]: a whole lot of us realize it, you know, that this is something serious, that this is not

01:17:23.800 --> 01:17:28.600
[Guest]: just a hobby. It doesn't matter if you're going to teach later. If you may have a job,

01:17:28.600 --> 01:17:32.640
[Guest]: you may do other things. He has a job now. But the point is that if these things that

01:17:32.640 --> 01:17:37.560
[Guest]: you're doing, these things are not optional, they're not less important than others. They're

01:17:37.560 --> 01:17:42.080
[Guest]: not a hobby. They are things that need to be done. So you find a way to do them. So

01:17:42.080 --> 01:17:46.840
[Guest]: I realized that yes, if I pushed myself, I did finish all my assignments. Well, I got

01:17:46.840 --> 01:17:52.640
[Guest]: good grades and I also managed to do all the work that was necessary to make those protest

01:17:52.640 --> 01:17:58.680
[Guest]: events a success, you know, you know, so that was a, that happened. And then came the time

01:17:58.680 --> 01:18:04.280
[Guest]: when Chandu's death was a turning point in a way I didn't realize. I had still thought

01:18:04.280 --> 01:18:08.400
[Guest]: I'd be teaching and all of that after that. And that was the year I was submitting my

01:18:08.400 --> 01:18:13.240
[Guest]: MPhil dissertation. So I had again, you know, I'd taken off and I told all my comrades that

01:18:13.240 --> 01:18:18.720
[Guest]: look, I'm studying and unless it's an absolute emergency, do not call me. I'm on the third

01:18:18.720 --> 01:18:25.600
[Guest]: floor in my hostel and writing. So there was no mobile phones, right? So there was a call

01:18:25.600 --> 01:18:32.240
[Guest]: in the, there was a phone in the guards room. So you people got calls there. So someone

01:18:32.240 --> 01:18:38.440
[Guest]: called there. So a phone call. So I was wondering now, who can it be? And why are they calling

01:18:38.440 --> 01:18:43.040
[Guest]: me? They all know that this one month, one and a half months I need to write my dissertation.

01:18:43.040 --> 01:18:47.840
[Guest]: I can't spare. So anyway, I went down grumbling, took the call and it was someone from my party

01:18:47.840 --> 01:18:53.960
[Guest]: office in Delhi. And they said, Chandu ki hathya ho gayi. I didn't recognize the voice

01:18:53.960 --> 01:18:58.120
[Guest]: because it wasn't someone I knew well. So I immediately said, you're lying. Who is this?

01:18:58.120 --> 01:19:02.400
[Guest]: So then he gave the phone to someone whom I knew very well. And I could make out his

01:19:02.400 --> 01:19:07.800
[Guest]: crying and he said, yes, it's true. Just now. It was literally minutes after it had happened.

01:19:07.800 --> 01:19:13.040
[Guest]: Minutes after four o'clock. So then I just freaked out. And then I had to go and tell

01:19:13.040 --> 01:19:17.360
[Guest]: a lot of people and all of that. And then we had this whole movement. So my writing,

01:19:17.360 --> 01:19:22.380
[Guest]: my MPhil became quite difficult, you know, because literally everyone was on the streets.

01:19:22.380 --> 01:19:26.800
[Guest]: So when I finally got back to writing, I think I didn't do a very good job. And my guide

01:19:26.800 --> 01:19:31.400
[Guest]: was very upset with me. And among other things, she said, you know, what is this? You know,

01:19:31.400 --> 01:19:35.000
[Guest]: where were you and how could you not write? And you have to, you have to make a choice.

01:19:35.000 --> 01:19:41.440
[Guest]: You know, you can't do both and all of that. So I remember thinking, feeling very angry

01:19:41.440 --> 01:19:47.560
[Guest]: at that in a sense, because I felt like she should have understood that it wasn't physically

01:19:47.560 --> 01:19:53.120
[Guest]: possible for me to not be out on the streets in those weeks and think that I can actually

01:19:53.120 --> 01:19:58.240
[Guest]: how could I, you know, how could I possibly, you know, one of our closest friends has been

01:19:58.240 --> 01:20:04.160
[Guest]: killed in this manner. So I, with the help of other friends who helped edit, my guide

01:20:04.160 --> 01:20:07.840
[Guest]: was right in the sense that she was right about one thing. She read what I had written

01:20:07.840 --> 01:20:12.600
[Guest]: in terms of my chapters. And she said, it reads like an MCD, whatever, drain inspectors

01:20:12.600 --> 01:20:18.120
[Guest]: report. Okay, it was very boringly written, very badly written. So then I had a friend

01:20:18.120 --> 01:20:24.920
[Guest]: who helped edit it. And she was wonderful in the time she gave me editing it and making

01:20:24.920 --> 01:20:29.920
[Guest]: it actually read like something. So without that I could never have got through. But because

01:20:29.920 --> 01:20:35.880
[Guest]: of all that extra editing work I did, I missed out on going to Cuba, something which I will

01:20:35.880 --> 01:20:42.320
[Guest]: always regret. Two people had gotten a chance to go from our organization to Cuba for a

01:20:42.320 --> 01:20:48.640
[Guest]: youth conference. And I was one of them. And I couldn't go because of my MPhil. I really,

01:20:48.640 --> 01:20:54.560
[Guest]: really regretted that because yeah, it was sad. But after that, that was a turning point.

01:20:54.560 --> 01:20:58.880
[Guest]: Somehow after that, I found myself, I did apply, went for a couple of interviews for

01:20:58.880 --> 01:21:04.920
[Guest]: jobs, didn't get them and wasn't really interested. But I was hesitant in the sense I wasn't sure

01:21:04.920 --> 01:21:09.680
[Guest]: my party needed me. I thought of myself at that time as a party member rather than just

01:21:09.680 --> 01:21:17.040
[Guest]: ISA, not a student. So then I went and spoke to one of our party leaders. He didn't push

01:21:17.040 --> 01:21:20.120
[Guest]: me. He said, I said, do you think I should take up a job? He said, if you want a job,

01:21:20.120 --> 01:21:24.880
[Guest]: you should take it up. You can always do party work with it. I took that to mean, oh, maybe

01:21:24.880 --> 01:21:29.940
[Guest]: they don't really have anything worth that I can do. Then there were others who spoke

01:21:29.940 --> 01:21:35.280
[Guest]: to me and said, tumhe jaruat hai kya abhi? Paise ki jaruat hai kya hai? What's the problem?

01:21:35.280 --> 01:21:41.320
[Guest]: I said, no, I'm OK, actually, and I don't have to take up a job right now. So they said,

01:21:41.320 --> 01:21:45.480
[Guest]: in that case, please, there's lots of work for you to do. So then, of course, the jobs

01:21:45.480 --> 01:21:49.720
[Guest]: they were giving me again, every job that I've been given, I've been scared of initially.

01:21:49.720 --> 01:21:56.020
[Guest]: I've wanted to say no to. So they wanted to give me the ISA president's job and I wanted

01:21:56.020 --> 01:22:01.320
[Guest]: to say no. But then I went to the meeting saying I'm going to say no. But then I went

01:22:01.320 --> 01:22:06.240
[Guest]: there and I said yes, eventually, because I realized, oh, it's the call of duty, basically.

01:22:06.240 --> 01:22:14.200
[Guest]: So I said yes. And then, yeah, I learned of the job and found I could do it.

01:22:14.200 --> 01:22:21.040
[Amit Varma]: So by party, you mean CPIML, right? CPIML. Yeah. So what does politics really mean after

01:22:21.040 --> 01:22:24.800
[Amit Varma]: this? Because none of the communist parties, from what I remember, and you'll have to forgive

01:22:24.800 --> 01:22:30.080
[Amit Varma]: me if my knowledge of this is very rudimentary, but from what I remember, none of the communist

01:22:30.080 --> 01:22:35.080
[Amit Varma]: parties were really winning too many seats, certainly not in the north of India. So what

01:22:35.080 --> 01:22:39.360
[Amit Varma]: did politics really mean in that sense? Was it activism? Because again, it's not instrumental

01:22:39.360 --> 01:22:43.720
[Amit Varma]: in terms of there's practically no chance for your coming to power. So are you trying

01:22:43.720 --> 01:22:49.000
[Amit Varma]: to maybe shape the culture in little ways, making small impacts on the margins? What's

01:22:49.000 --> 01:22:51.000
[Amit Varma]: the end goal?

01:22:51.000 --> 01:22:57.320
[Guest]: No, not really. I don't. I see the job as all of it, including the elections and all

01:22:57.320 --> 01:23:02.200
[Guest]: of that. I see electoral wins also as important and necessary, as well as all kinds of other

01:23:02.200 --> 01:23:07.840
[Guest]: changes which are equally important and necessary. But it's more in terms of I don't see the

01:23:07.840 --> 01:23:15.840
[Guest]: win as a win for a particular brand name or a win for particular persons. I think that

01:23:15.840 --> 01:23:21.800
[Guest]: every win which is hard won, very difficult to win, but those wins for a left party are

01:23:21.800 --> 01:23:31.120
[Guest]: basically wins for a certain class of people who otherwise are always losing. In my party's

01:23:31.120 --> 01:23:36.880
[Guest]: case, for instance, I remember that when Chandu did give me a party membership, offer me a

01:23:36.880 --> 01:23:44.560
[Guest]: party membership, he took me on a long walk around JNU campus and he appealed to my feminism.

01:23:44.560 --> 01:23:50.520
[Guest]: And he said, what do you think? Wouldn't you want to know more about how women wage these

01:23:50.520 --> 01:23:58.040
[Guest]: struggles in terms of, for instance, laboring women, Dalit women in Bihar who faced a massacre

01:23:58.040 --> 01:24:04.280
[Guest]: by the Ranbir Sena. So they faced a massacre because they are in a certain struggle and

01:24:04.280 --> 01:24:10.520
[Guest]: it's not an armed struggle. So what do they do in that struggle? What are the forms? Aren't

01:24:10.520 --> 01:24:15.280
[Guest]: you interested in learning from them? Because otherwise you will only have this much experience

01:24:15.280 --> 01:24:24.000
[Guest]: and that's it. So I noticed that he wasn't telling me, you have a lot to give those women.

01:24:24.000 --> 01:24:29.400
[Guest]: He was telling me the opposite, that you are limiting yourself because you are not taking

01:24:29.400 --> 01:24:36.160
[Guest]: what they could give you. And so you should actually, you should be knowing a lot more.

01:24:36.160 --> 01:24:42.200
[Guest]: You don't know enough. So I realized that that was what I wanted to do. And I was doing

01:24:42.200 --> 01:24:47.880
[Guest]: that and their victories. So every election that they won, our party won an MP seat in

01:24:47.880 --> 01:24:58.120
[Guest]: 1989 and then MLA seats, they first won in the, in 1992, 1996, I think. Yes, 96. So that's

01:24:58.120 --> 01:25:02.320
[Guest]: when the Ranbir Sena massacre started happening and there was this whole pushback and then

01:25:02.320 --> 01:25:07.600
[Guest]: the Lalu phenomenon was also there. So our party's meteoric rise was suddenly halted

01:25:07.600 --> 01:25:14.880
[Guest]: because the social justice space was then divided between the Janata Dal and our party.

01:25:14.880 --> 01:25:20.000
[Guest]: So till then, the social justice space was mainly our party. But as the 90s, with the

01:25:20.000 --> 01:25:26.280
[Guest]: rise of Lalu, that became divided. There was a divide. But I wanted that these forces,

01:25:26.280 --> 01:25:31.040
[Guest]: these people who are fighting these battles for land and wages and dignity, their winning

01:25:31.040 --> 01:25:37.840
[Guest]: an election means it's their victory. Their victory. I wanted that. So basically, I was

01:25:37.840 --> 01:25:44.800
[Guest]: doing it for that. So it was, and I still am. So it doesn't matter so much. I mean,

01:25:44.800 --> 01:25:52.440
[Guest]: I want us to win more seats. I want us to do much better. I'm thrilled when we do. But

01:25:52.440 --> 01:26:00.280
[Guest]: I am not terribly crushed when we don't. Let's put it that way. It doesn't crush me when

01:26:00.280 --> 01:26:06.200
[Guest]: we don't because I realized that, well, that's where the movement is at now. That class of

01:26:06.200 --> 01:26:12.640
[Guest]: people is not anywhere close to winning right now what to do, you know.

01:26:12.640 --> 01:26:17.720
[Amit Varma]: So I have three follow up questions about your political journey. And one of them is

01:26:17.720 --> 01:26:23.760
[Amit Varma]: that when you join a party, and I think you mentioned earlier in 94, when you were sort

01:26:23.760 --> 01:26:27.680
[Amit Varma]: of being voted by different parties, and people said, hey, join IFA and you were like, no,

01:26:27.680 --> 01:26:31.240
[Amit Varma]: I don't want to, you know, I want to maintain my autonomy and think for myself and all of

01:26:31.240 --> 01:26:36.720
[Amit Varma]: that. And it strikes me that joining a party also carries a risk of pleasing allegiance

01:26:36.720 --> 01:26:41.680
[Amit Varma]: to a tribe, you know, in different subtle ways that you may not even realize yourself

01:26:41.680 --> 01:26:47.320
[Amit Varma]: that you become circumscribed by that. And that's especially so if it is a political

01:26:47.320 --> 01:26:51.880
[Amit Varma]: tribe in the sense that the fundamental thing about politics is you need to win. There is

01:26:51.880 --> 01:26:56.800
[Amit Varma]: that will to power, that will to power involves thinking in certain ways that you might not

01:26:56.800 --> 01:27:00.960
[Amit Varma]: otherwise do not just thinking in terms of principles and ideas, but thinking in terms

01:27:00.960 --> 01:27:05.600
[Amit Varma]: of vote banks positioning, like you said earlier that, you know, we never looked at our win

01:27:05.600 --> 01:27:10.080
[Amit Varma]: as a victory for a brand name or a person. But nevertheless, if you're in politics, and

01:27:10.080 --> 01:27:13.760
[Amit Varma]: you want to win and you want to follow the will to power to his logical conclusion, those

01:27:13.760 --> 01:27:19.760
[Amit Varma]: are sort of things that you are thinking of. So what was this something that you know,

01:27:19.760 --> 01:27:26.200
[Amit Varma]: was an issue like one thing that I often say, and I think is by and large, true across the

01:27:26.200 --> 01:27:30.080
[Amit Varma]: world and across politics is that politics corrodes character, because you might go in

01:27:30.080 --> 01:27:34.960
[Amit Varma]: there with certain principles. But then politics is the art of compromise. And it is the art

01:27:34.960 --> 01:27:40.160
[Amit Varma]: of finding a way to win. And then gradually you just, you know, you do things you may

01:27:40.160 --> 01:27:43.480
[Amit Varma]: think are necessary compromises, you don't really believe in them, but you change along

01:27:43.480 --> 01:27:48.680
[Amit Varma]: the way. So is that a journey that you were conscious of that you managed to avoid? Is

01:27:48.680 --> 01:27:53.760
[Amit Varma]: that a tussle that is always there? Or is your party different? Or, you know, what's

01:27:53.760 --> 01:27:58.840
[Guest]: your sort of? I love the question, Amit, because it was

01:27:58.840 --> 01:28:05.720
[Guest]: certainly in my mind, that was certainly a reason why I was hesitant. And I have a complete

01:28:05.720 --> 01:28:11.400
[Guest]: abhorrence of cults. So I won't even use the word tribe, okay, because tribe I can still

01:28:11.400 --> 01:28:17.720
[Guest]: see as different. I have a complete abhorrence of cults. And on the left, you have no dearth

01:28:17.720 --> 01:28:24.520
[Guest]: of cults. Okay, there are plenty. And I was not, you know, I cannot see myself as being

01:28:24.520 --> 01:28:32.440
[Guest]: a member of a cult ever. So I was worried about that. But two things that sort of made

01:28:32.440 --> 01:28:38.720
[Guest]: me understand things a little better. One was that I felt that the idea that I am this

01:28:38.720 --> 01:28:47.040
[Guest]: individual person, and standing alone on something, apart from everyone else makes my position

01:28:47.040 --> 01:28:52.640
[Guest]: more independent or more superior to others wasn't something true. It's not always because

01:28:52.640 --> 01:28:57.020
[Guest]: I realized that, you know, what are you changing, then at the end of the day, change comes when

01:28:57.020 --> 01:29:02.520
[Guest]: you are interacting with others. And it is always something that's collective. Somebody

01:29:02.520 --> 01:29:09.520
[Guest]: I admire, an artist recently wrote, I saw a social media post of theirs, won't name

01:29:09.520 --> 01:29:13.680
[Guest]: them. But I saw a social media post of theirs, where they had several posts about how an

01:29:13.680 --> 01:29:19.280
[Guest]: individual is the one who makes the chance you get, you know, you get insight and truth

01:29:19.280 --> 01:29:24.480
[Guest]: only as an individual, not as a mob, not as a crowd. I thought about that a lot. And I

01:29:24.480 --> 01:29:31.800
[Guest]: don't agree, because I think that truth is not something people get it. It's not just

01:29:31.800 --> 01:29:37.480
[Guest]: something that's given to you as an insight. It's not just a light bulb moment, always.

01:29:37.480 --> 01:29:42.860
[Guest]: It's often something that you realize you want, but it is possible to get it only by

01:29:42.860 --> 01:29:47.000
[Guest]: working with a whole lot of other people. And if there are people, there are going to

01:29:47.000 --> 01:29:51.840
[Guest]: be differences of opinion. So the issue is whether you're able to have a democratic way

01:29:51.840 --> 01:29:59.160
[Guest]: of functioning and decision making. And in ISA, very early on, I was very reassured by

01:29:59.160 --> 01:30:06.560
[Guest]: the fact that this was not a place where everyone agreed with everyone else, very far from it.

01:30:06.560 --> 01:30:13.080
[Guest]: Okay, so there would be these heated arguments without getting our personal relationships

01:30:13.080 --> 01:30:21.080
[Guest]: altered. Okay, so we were very close and loving and caring for each other, while being absolutely

01:30:21.080 --> 01:30:26.960
[Guest]: so I know that my feminism was something that a lot of men in my organization resisted for

01:30:26.960 --> 01:30:31.360
[Guest]: a bit in the sense that they said, no, no, you are very critical of Marxism, but you

01:30:31.360 --> 01:30:36.420
[Guest]: haven't read Marxism, right. And I realized that some of what they were saying was true.

01:30:36.420 --> 01:30:40.720
[Guest]: Because when we got arguing, I realized that the Marx which I had read was the Marx I had

01:30:40.720 --> 01:30:46.360
[Guest]: gotten from postmodernist critiques of Marxism. So then they would poke at me and I would

01:30:46.360 --> 01:30:52.160
[Guest]: go back and read, you know, what I had thought I had read before, and realize that, oh, it's

01:30:52.160 --> 01:30:57.320
[Guest]: actually saying something a little different. So I would also change my mind, but I realized

01:30:57.320 --> 01:31:02.720
[Guest]: that they do change their mind on many things. And those came out of these arguments. And

01:31:02.720 --> 01:31:06.960
[Guest]: the best thing was that even where their minds were not changed, I would write leaflets for

01:31:06.960 --> 01:31:12.120
[Guest]: the organization, and they would be signed by everyone, including those who had not agreed.

01:31:12.120 --> 01:31:17.240
[Guest]: So I realized that that was, you know, I felt very reassured in that, that a feminist thinking

01:31:17.240 --> 01:31:22.840
[Guest]: I wrote something called a feminized Marxism. And a lot of the Marxist, pakka Marxwadis

01:31:22.840 --> 01:31:27.480
[Guest]: looked quite horrified and asked several of our ISA national leaders, ki yeh kya paagal

01:31:27.480 --> 01:31:31.840
[Guest]: ho gaye ho kya? What is all this feminized Marxism? What does it mean? So they said,

01:31:31.840 --> 01:31:36.040
[Guest]: no, actually, she's written it and we are carrying it in our name and read it. It's

01:31:36.040 --> 01:31:41.240
[Guest]: not, you know, it's not so bad. Don't go beyond the title, read what she's written. So now

01:31:41.240 --> 01:31:46.040
[Guest]: when I read that title, I cringe a little bit, because it's not exactly the way I'd

01:31:46.040 --> 01:31:52.040
[Guest]: put it now. But yeah, I mean, I do realize that there was a germ of what I hold even

01:31:52.040 --> 01:31:57.000
[Guest]: now. And that happened over a time, over a journey. And collective decision making is

01:31:57.000 --> 01:32:03.120
[Guest]: still in my party. Even now, there's no, there's no, you know, cultishness at all, you know,

01:32:03.120 --> 01:32:06.960
[Guest]: so it's not like koi bada neta hai toh uski baat bas maan lena hai and all of that, not

01:32:06.960 --> 01:32:12.320
[Guest]: at all. But I do realize that it's a bit different, that there are, there is a chance of this

01:32:12.320 --> 01:32:17.240
[Guest]: happening in left parties. It has happened internationally. Okay, there was a cult around

01:32:17.240 --> 01:32:25.120
[Guest]: Stalin. There was, there have been cults around other leaders. And there have been cults in

01:32:25.120 --> 01:32:31.760
[Guest]: other ML groups. I see a very cultish behavior in some left supporters online, especially

01:32:31.760 --> 01:32:36.080
[Guest]: for instance, when they're defending their, you know, the CPM position in West Bengal

01:32:36.080 --> 01:32:43.800
[Guest]: right now. So it's this blind defense of the indefensible. You know, you are facing a reality,

01:32:43.800 --> 01:32:48.360
[Guest]: but you're saying, you know, the sun is shining, but you are saying no, it's midnight. And

01:32:48.360 --> 01:32:52.520
[Guest]: I believe it's midnight and you people are all liberal idiots who don't understand that

01:32:52.520 --> 01:32:58.880
[Guest]: it's midnight, you know, or when it comes to China, you know, so if I, if my party criticizes

01:32:58.880 --> 01:33:04.240
[Guest]: what China is doing with the Uyghurs, there are plenty of cultish fellows you meet who

01:33:04.240 --> 01:33:08.560
[Guest]: are, who will say, oh, this is, you know, CPM is a liberal, Kavita Krishnan toh liberal

01:33:08.560 --> 01:33:13.960
[Guest]: hai. Toh liberal hona bahut kharab cheez nahi hai na. The communist is supposed to be, the

01:33:13.960 --> 01:33:18.400
[Guest]: problem with liberalism is that they don't realize that those liberal values are not

01:33:18.400 --> 01:33:24.800
[Guest]: accessed by everybody. Not everyone can have the benefit of what liberal, the good that

01:33:24.800 --> 01:33:28.720
[Guest]: liberalism offers. That is the problem with liberalism. The problem with liberalism is

01:33:28.720 --> 01:33:36.000
[Guest]: not because it's liberal. The problem is because you don't realize how to make it available

01:33:36.000 --> 01:33:40.640
[Guest]: to everyone. And that can, so the communists have to be liberal for everybody. No, that's

01:33:40.640 --> 01:33:46.880
[Guest]: the whole point. The point is not that you become authoritarian for everyone instead,

01:33:46.880 --> 01:33:54.680
[Guest]: right? And so I am, I'm still very, very wary of cults, but I think that somehow in CPIML's

01:33:54.680 --> 01:33:59.760
[Guest]: own experience and the way it has developed as a party, that's for another conversation

01:33:59.760 --> 01:34:06.960
[Guest]: sometime. But I think that in its own experience of growing, it too has had to consciously

01:34:06.960 --> 01:34:12.000
[Guest]: avoid becoming a cult. So I remember just one small example of that. I know that, you

01:34:12.000 --> 01:34:16.200
[Guest]: know, my, the magazine I edit, which is the party organ is called Liberation. So my party

01:34:16.200 --> 01:34:22.360
[Guest]: is called CPIML Liberation. So initially it used to be called the Vinod Mishra group,

01:34:22.360 --> 01:34:26.760
[Guest]: because there were groups named after this person, that person, this person, that person.

01:34:26.760 --> 01:34:31.960
[Guest]: Vinod Mishra, he became the general secretary suddenly because several other people who

01:34:31.960 --> 01:34:36.440
[Guest]: were leaders died. They were killed by the police or they were killed in custody, police

01:34:36.440 --> 01:34:42.680
[Guest]: custody. So he found himself in the late twenties, a young man, suddenly the general secretary

01:34:42.680 --> 01:34:48.120
[Guest]: of a party, which was facing huge violence, facing a lot of depression, and that was scattered

01:34:48.120 --> 01:34:55.800
[Guest]: all around. And he turned that around. And I don't think of it as just being his remarkable

01:34:55.800 --> 01:35:00.560
[Guest]: abilities. At that time, I doubt whether anybody thought a 27, 28 year old had any remarkable

01:35:00.560 --> 01:35:05.640
[Guest]: abilities. It was just that it was his job. He had to do it, but he did turn it around

01:35:05.640 --> 01:35:10.760
[Guest]: and he did it by keeping a very straight head. And the first thing he did was to say, no,

01:35:10.760 --> 01:35:16.560
[Guest]: this stops. It's not Vinod Mishra group. It has to be a party. And the party means it's

01:35:16.560 --> 01:35:21.640
[Guest]: a collective. The collective means it's collective decision-making. What I say doesn't go. If

01:35:21.640 --> 01:35:27.240
[Guest]: I don't persuade you, it doesn't go. So he then managed to persuade a party that was

01:35:27.240 --> 01:35:35.640
[Guest]: underground to actually start contesting elections, start doing things differently, start realizing

01:35:35.640 --> 01:35:41.780
[Guest]: that class struggle takes many forms. Caste and gender became pretty central to the struggles

01:35:41.780 --> 01:35:48.120
[Guest]: that were launched in the 1980s by our party. All of that. And it happened also because

01:35:48.120 --> 01:35:52.360
[Guest]: there was this very conscious, this thing that, so there are jokes about ML parties,

01:35:52.360 --> 01:35:57.320
[Guest]: okay, which I'm the, you know, several jokes about ML parties and how cultish they can

01:35:57.320 --> 01:36:02.200
[Guest]: be. Okay. So my own comrades used to tell us those jokes in which they would be about,

01:36:02.200 --> 01:36:14.000
[Guest]: you know, how to address Charu Majumdar. So should he be addressed as comrade? So the

01:36:14.000 --> 01:36:19.080
[Guest]: point is that our party developed by laughing at this, by joking about this and saying,

01:36:19.080 --> 01:36:25.880
[Guest]: please, no, this is not what we want to be doing. Okay. By very far from it. So, yeah.

01:36:25.880 --> 01:36:29.880
[Amit Varma]: Yeah, it just strikes me that if Sri Sri Ravi Shankar joined your party, you could call

01:36:29.880 --> 01:36:36.200
[Amit Varma]: him comrade, comrade Ravi Shankar. But so I'd actually told you, I had, I'd actually

01:36:36.200 --> 01:36:40.440
[Amit Varma]: told you, I had three questions about your political journey. And I've asked one of them.

01:36:40.440 --> 01:36:44.480
[Amit Varma]: So you would imagine there are two left, but one more popped up from, you know, what you

01:36:44.480 --> 01:36:48.120
[Amit Varma]: mentioned about how within ISI, you would have all these heated arguments, but you'd

01:36:48.120 --> 01:36:52.120
[Amit Varma]: still love each other and be friends and all of that. And the arguments were just at an

01:36:52.120 --> 01:36:57.720
[Amit Varma]: intellectual level. And we don't see that in the modern discourse so much. And my theory

01:36:57.720 --> 01:37:04.760
[Amit Varma]: for why that is, is that what social media especially does is that one, it enables people

01:37:04.760 --> 01:37:10.640
[Amit Varma]: to form these sort of echo chambers, find a tribe or the cult as it were. And then the

01:37:10.640 --> 01:37:15.400
[Amit Varma]: incentive there is always to raise the status within that echo chamber. And the only way

01:37:15.400 --> 01:37:20.280
[Amit Varma]: of doing that is by moving to the extremes, and by getting increasingly shrill. So sometimes

01:37:20.280 --> 01:37:24.400
[Amit Varma]: you can, you know, attack people in other echo chambers and never actually talk to them

01:37:24.400 --> 01:37:28.080
[Amit Varma]: or address their arguments, but just attack them. And sometimes it becomes this quest

01:37:28.080 --> 01:37:33.000
[Amit Varma]: for purity within your little cult, where you attack someone from the same cult for

01:37:33.000 --> 01:37:39.320
[Amit Varma]: not being pure enough. So it seems to me that therefore, our politics in a sense, is necessarily

01:37:39.320 --> 01:37:45.480
[Amit Varma]: going to be driven to extremes in this manner. And, you know, I don't know if I am if this

01:37:45.480 --> 01:37:50.240
[Amit Varma]: is just the availability heuristic that because, you know, I'm on Twitter so much, because

01:37:50.240 --> 01:37:54.640
[Amit Varma]: I noticed this stuff, I'm noticing it. And maybe it was always like this. But my sense

01:37:54.640 --> 01:37:59.200
[Amit Varma]: is that the discourse has become degraded, where everyone is living in their alternate

01:37:59.200 --> 01:38:04.440
[Amit Varma]: realities. And we don't talk to each other anymore. What's what's your sense?

01:38:04.440 --> 01:38:09.120
[Guest]: What you say about social media? Absolutely. And I'll speak a little bit about that immediately

01:38:09.120 --> 01:38:16.240
[Guest]: after but I just wanted to correct one thing that our arguments in ISA were not just intellectual.

01:38:16.240 --> 01:38:23.000
[Guest]: I think we felt them very, very personally. So, you know, when they say personal is political,

01:38:23.000 --> 01:38:28.600
[Guest]: it's also that the political is very, very personal to us who are, you know, living politics.

01:38:28.600 --> 01:38:32.760
[Guest]: And I don't think it's only for activists. I think for a lot of people, if politics is

01:38:32.760 --> 01:38:39.040
[Guest]: at all about your values, then it is something deeply personal. It is something deeply personal.

01:38:39.040 --> 01:38:44.120
[Guest]: I felt this, you know, when I was reading Anja Lumba's, who was my guide, by the way,

01:38:44.120 --> 01:38:49.320
[Guest]: my MPhil. So Anja Lumba's very, very fine book called Revolutionary Desires. So she's

01:38:49.320 --> 01:38:54.720
[Guest]: written this book about the women in the first phase of the Indian communist movement. And,

01:38:54.720 --> 01:38:58.560
[Guest]: you know, that's one of the things which I felt while on reading that book. But these

01:38:58.560 --> 01:39:03.280
[Guest]: are women for whom it's not just that their personal is political, it's that the political

01:39:03.280 --> 01:39:08.160
[Guest]: is so deeply personal to them. So they can feel, you know, emotional ups and downs like

01:39:08.160 --> 01:39:14.000
[Guest]: you do in a love relationship. It's like that. So our arguments were deeply felt and

01:39:14.000 --> 01:39:19.640
[Guest]: they were personal and we had quarrels, we had arguments. I only say that it didn't mean

01:39:19.640 --> 01:39:26.960
[Guest]: that we wrote off people because of those arguments. Because in general, we cared for

01:39:26.960 --> 01:39:35.600
[Guest]: each other. We knew each other very well. And so we knew each other's quirks also. We

01:39:35.600 --> 01:39:42.160
[Guest]: knew each other's, you know, blind spots also. And so we were a very diverse set of people

01:39:42.160 --> 01:39:48.920
[Guest]: who were still very loving to each other in that sense. And I can't say more than I think

01:39:48.920 --> 01:39:54.520
[Guest]: I think most of all for that, I mean, I'm not saying it just because he's dead. But

01:39:54.520 --> 01:40:00.600
[Guest]: Chandu was really remarkable in that way. Because he was someone I realized whose politics

01:40:00.600 --> 01:40:05.960
[Guest]: came from a place of love, not from a place of intellect alone. I think for me, it was

01:40:05.960 --> 01:40:11.160
[Guest]: most of more of an intellectual sense and of ideas and duty and all of that. But for

01:40:11.160 --> 01:40:17.480
[Guest]: him, he really loved people. And then he wanted to make their lives better, that kind of thing.

01:40:17.480 --> 01:40:22.040
[Guest]: And he was that kind of person who would have these very, very loving relationships with

01:40:22.040 --> 01:40:28.640
[Guest]: people who were in rival organizations, people who were very critical of us. He'd argue bitterly

01:40:28.640 --> 01:40:36.480
[Guest]: with them. But at the end of it, they knew that if they needed help, or if they were,

01:40:36.480 --> 01:40:40.480
[Guest]: you know, they needed succor at some point, they knew they would find it with him. And

01:40:40.480 --> 01:40:44.240
[Guest]: that was something which really stayed with me for a long time. But what you're saying

01:40:44.240 --> 01:40:48.320
[Guest]: now about social media, I think the first problem which I see with social media, apart

01:40:48.320 --> 01:40:56.440
[Guest]: from the, as you say, the tendency to be more one dimensional, more, you know, you also

01:40:56.440 --> 01:41:03.560
[Guest]: get a I'm talking even about myself, that on if I'm on social media, and I see somebody

01:41:03.560 --> 01:41:11.840
[Guest]: has an argument, right? My whole body, okay, from my toes to my head, wants that dopamine

01:41:11.840 --> 01:41:18.080
[Guest]: hit of smashing it back with an answer, okay? I wouldn't be able to do that if I didn't

01:41:18.080 --> 01:41:25.520
[Guest]: have this at my fingertips. And I realized over time that I didn't like that feeling.

01:41:25.520 --> 01:41:30.840
[Guest]: I didn't like doing that anymore, because I realized that it is making me also react

01:41:30.840 --> 01:41:36.320
[Guest]: in ways which is unnecessary, even if it's an unfair attack. I'm not talking about trolls,

01:41:36.320 --> 01:41:40.200
[Guest]: I'm talking about maybe, you know, someone I know on social media, but they don't agree

01:41:40.200 --> 01:41:45.280
[Guest]: with me. I don't have to smash it out of the court, I don't have to smash it back in their

01:41:45.280 --> 01:41:52.280
[Guest]: faces. I can wait a little bit, think about it. And then, so I tell myself that it's like

01:41:52.280 --> 01:41:58.580
[Guest]: drunk driving. So I tell myself, don't drive while drunk. So don't tweet while angry. Okay.

01:41:58.580 --> 01:42:03.520
[Guest]: So I tell myself that if I'm in a particularly angry or volatile mood, maybe I shouldn't.

01:42:03.520 --> 01:42:06.960
[Guest]: It took me a very long time to come to this place, I can tell you, because I've done a

01:42:06.960 --> 01:42:13.480
[Guest]: lot of ill-advised tweeting and posting. And it is my comrades, in fact, who have persuaded

01:42:13.480 --> 01:42:18.480
[Guest]: me, who have gradually gotten me to see that this is not a particularly wise or good thing

01:42:18.480 --> 01:42:25.080
[Guest]: to be doing. But I think for me, the worst part of social media is that what it does

01:42:25.080 --> 01:42:31.760
[Guest]: is it teaches young people that you can become a, you know, you get recognition very fast

01:42:31.760 --> 01:42:37.160
[Guest]: on social media, by doing very little outside social media. Or if you're doing something

01:42:37.160 --> 01:42:43.440
[Guest]: outside social media, so showing it on social media becomes the main thing. And so the tendency

01:42:43.440 --> 01:42:47.580
[Guest]: is that you start thinking of yourself more as an individual. And I'm not saying this

01:42:47.580 --> 01:42:52.040
[Guest]: badly about the persons, I'm talking about the structure of the, you know, social media

01:42:52.040 --> 01:42:56.680
[Guest]: itself and media. And then media picks you up from there. It happened to me. But the

01:42:56.680 --> 01:43:02.200
[Guest]: point is, you know, since 2013 movement, before 2013 also, I was doing the same thing and

01:43:02.200 --> 01:43:07.080
[Guest]: had been doing it for more than a decade. Okay. But media didn't know who I was, they

01:43:07.080 --> 01:43:14.040
[Guest]: had no clue I existed. I gave a speech to about 25-30 people outside Shreela Dixit's

01:43:14.040 --> 01:43:19.280
[Guest]: house. And 25-30 because by that time, you know, water cannon chal chuka tha and a lot

01:43:19.280 --> 01:43:24.400
[Guest]: of people had been chased away. So I gave that speech and left. Okay. And that speech

01:43:24.400 --> 01:43:29.000
[Guest]: went viral. And so suddenly people realized that, oh, here's this articulate person and

01:43:29.000 --> 01:43:33.400
[Guest]: start calling me to every media channel. So initially, I had no discrimination, I just

01:43:33.400 --> 01:43:37.840
[Guest]: got yanked around and go everywhere. Then gradually, I started realizing cutting it

01:43:37.840 --> 01:43:44.240
[Guest]: down. But I and that recognition that came for me as an individual, I realized that I

01:43:44.240 --> 01:43:49.240
[Guest]: would have to fight to make them take my organization's name. And they would think that this is a

01:43:49.240 --> 01:43:54.680
[Guest]: business for political prachar. And I would tell them, no, the point is, I'm only representing.

01:43:54.680 --> 01:44:00.400
[Guest]: Otherwise, I would just be a talking head. No, I'm representing the wisdom, collective

01:44:00.400 --> 01:44:08.360
[Guest]: wisdom that an entire organization of lakhs of people is living every day. No. So how

01:44:08.360 --> 01:44:14.120
[Guest]: is it fair for just for me to just go as Kavita Krishnan Samajik Karekarta? Don't do that.

01:44:14.120 --> 01:44:19.840
[Guest]: You know, I'm going there because my organization does this work. Okay, so then I have to force

01:44:19.840 --> 01:44:25.200
[Guest]: them to do this. My mother used to watch me on TV and text me when she realized when when

01:44:25.200 --> 01:44:29.640
[Guest]: she'd tell me they aren't giving IPAS name. So when there would be a break in between,

01:44:29.640 --> 01:44:33.800
[Guest]: I'd call people and say, why isn't you know, because I couldn't see what they're showing.

01:44:33.800 --> 01:44:38.200
[Guest]: So that took a long while. But the point is that happened to me when I was in my 40s.

01:44:38.200 --> 01:44:44.280
[Guest]: Okay, I was it when it happens to people who are in their early 20s. I think they find

01:44:44.280 --> 01:44:50.360
[Guest]: it much harder to think collectively. So then it changes the dynamics within groups, it

01:44:50.360 --> 01:44:55.560
[Guest]: changes the dynamics of how you then they start thinking, okay, I'm this political figure.

01:44:55.560 --> 01:45:02.080
[Guest]: I have this politics. Where can I take this in my bag with me? I started out in this left

01:45:02.080 --> 01:45:05.880
[Guest]: organization. But if the left organization doesn't have much career opportunity, where

01:45:05.880 --> 01:45:10.400
[Guest]: will I win? So maybe I can just take all this progressive politics and go with it to Congress

01:45:10.400 --> 01:45:15.320
[Guest]: or to X, Y, Z. And I think they're, I'm not saying this in a bad way about any of the

01:45:15.320 --> 01:45:19.720
[Guest]: people who've done this. I understand how it's happening, but I feel bad about it. And

01:45:19.720 --> 01:45:25.000
[Guest]: I think that they have often had a very disillusioning experience after that, because they've realized

01:45:25.000 --> 01:45:30.520
[Guest]: they can't do that. You can't, you know, your left ideology and left politics comes with

01:45:30.520 --> 01:45:36.240
[Guest]: a certain kind of practice. You can't just pin it on your this thing like a badge and

01:45:36.240 --> 01:45:41.960
[Guest]: go carry it with you somewhere else, you know, you won't be able to do the same kind of politics.

01:45:41.960 --> 01:45:47.080
[Amit Varma]: So I'll just kind of think aloud. And it strikes me that the fundamental difference here is

01:45:47.080 --> 01:45:52.480
[Amit Varma]: that for the casual person who's not really into a cause, the cost of posturing has gone

01:45:52.480 --> 01:45:57.800
[Amit Varma]: down almost to zero. Like I imagine in 1990, let's say you care about cause X, or let's

01:45:57.800 --> 01:46:01.320
[Amit Varma]: say in 1990, you don't care about any cause, but you'd like to posture that, oh, I am on

01:46:01.320 --> 01:46:05.720
[Amit Varma]: this side, you can tell it to people in your drawing room at a party, and it has no impact.

01:46:05.720 --> 01:46:09.680
[Amit Varma]: But if you actually want to, you know, build that brand of yourself, you have to go to

01:46:09.680 --> 01:46:13.800
[Amit Varma]: rallies, you have to put in the hard yards, you have to do all of that. And whereas on

01:46:13.800 --> 01:46:18.720
[Amit Varma]: social media, the cost of posturing is for all practical purposes, zero, anybody can

01:46:18.720 --> 01:46:24.440
[Amit Varma]: just say anything and, you know, appropriate that label or tag for themselves and oh, look,

01:46:24.440 --> 01:46:28.360
[Amit Varma]: I'm so compassionate, I care about X or Y or Z, or I'm so sanskari, or I'm so nationalistic.

01:46:28.360 --> 01:46:33.400
[Amit Varma]: I think I mean, this applies to all the cults, of course. And then what happens is that the

01:46:33.400 --> 01:46:39.000
[Amit Varma]: genuine carers in a sense, and again, I'm thinking aloud, get sort of drowned out by

01:46:39.000 --> 01:46:44.200
[Amit Varma]: all the shallow posturers who are then competing with each other. And therefore, Twitter gets

01:46:44.200 --> 01:46:48.680
[Amit Varma]: or social media gets further and further away from the real world where people are actually

01:46:48.680 --> 01:46:55.360
[Amit Varma]: doing real things, but maybe shat on on Twitter for not being pure enough or whatever, any

01:46:55.360 --> 01:46:58.520
[Amit Varma]: kind of random thing.

01:46:58.520 --> 01:47:06.640
[Guest]: I very much agree with you. My only caveat to that would be that then it's not social

01:47:06.640 --> 01:47:14.200
[Guest]: media versus real life. It's more about movements that are there in real life, and are also

01:47:14.200 --> 01:47:19.640
[Guest]: on social media. So for me, something like Yloitor, or something like Pinjatod, which

01:47:19.640 --> 01:47:24.800
[Guest]: is even more so Pinjatod, to me, those are in a different category, you know, because

01:47:24.800 --> 01:47:30.880
[Guest]: they are not just about individuals who are, you know, saying something. It's not just

01:47:30.880 --> 01:47:37.040
[Guest]: a statement on social media. It's not just a discourse. They're actually trying to organize

01:47:37.040 --> 01:47:44.200
[Guest]: and social media is one of the organizing tools of it. Not the only one, but one of

01:47:44.200 --> 01:47:48.840
[Guest]: them. I think that as far as that's concerned, that's good. But my worry is that it's also

01:47:48.840 --> 01:47:53.280
[Guest]: the other way around. And I keep seeing that happening because it's also like if it didn't

01:47:53.280 --> 01:47:57.520
[Guest]: happen on social media, it didn't happen at all, right? But the point is, there's lots

01:47:57.520 --> 01:48:03.960
[Guest]: of movements, lots of interesting political developments that happen off social media,

01:48:03.960 --> 01:48:09.360
[Guest]: and not all of them can happen on social media. It's not just about social media space. See,

01:48:09.360 --> 01:48:14.240
[Guest]: it can be a remote andolan in a village, and you can find a way to get it on social media.

01:48:14.240 --> 01:48:18.800
[Guest]: I'm not talking about that. I'm talking about gender politics. I can tell you that much

01:48:18.800 --> 01:48:24.560
[Guest]: of the work which I do as a feminist activist, or which my organization does, cannot be ever

01:48:24.560 --> 01:48:30.800
[Guest]: shared on social media or on media, ever. Okay? I cannot do that. The reason is because

01:48:30.800 --> 01:48:38.440
[Guest]: so much of it is in the realm of private talking to survivors and victims of violence. I'll

01:48:38.440 --> 01:48:45.560
[Guest]: give you an example, and I'll tell you how insidious this is. Okay? So there's this comrade

01:48:45.560 --> 01:48:51.400
[Guest]: in our office here who is one of the most senior members of our party, and a very, very,

01:48:51.400 --> 01:48:57.160
[Guest]: again, somebody who wouldn't describe himself. He wouldn't use the word feminist to describe

01:48:57.160 --> 01:49:02.720
[Guest]: himself, but who is one of those whom I can generally count on to be the most supportive

01:49:02.720 --> 01:49:08.800
[Guest]: with, you know, any move that is feminist in spirit. Okay? And that is progressive in

01:49:08.800 --> 01:49:15.440
[Guest]: spirit and all of that. He's a very wonderful person. The thing is that newspapers one day

01:49:15.440 --> 01:49:23.840
[Guest]: were full of stories about a JNU student, a woman, who was raped by a Delhi University

01:49:23.840 --> 01:49:31.120
[Guest]: some student. Okay? So the papers were full of this rape. And, you know, the papers obviously

01:49:31.120 --> 01:49:37.680
[Guest]: did not report on any complaint being filed, any protest, any this, any that. Okay? So

01:49:37.680 --> 01:49:42.360
[Guest]: it so happened that a couple of days after this, the papers had been full of it, and

01:49:42.360 --> 01:49:49.760
[Guest]: I happened to visit our office. And this comrade, he sat me down, and no, he didn't sit me down.

01:49:49.760 --> 01:49:53.760
[Guest]: I realized that he'd been speaking to a whole lot of other people and had been telling

01:49:53.760 --> 01:49:57.920
[Guest]: them in the office, I think that ISA, you know, it's really become very problematic

01:49:57.920 --> 01:50:02.080
[Guest]: because look, they are not taking up this issue. And why are they not taking it up?

01:50:02.080 --> 01:50:08.200
[Guest]: It's because, you know, they must be thinking that, oh, this happened in a room. So somewhere,

01:50:08.200 --> 01:50:14.520
[Guest]: you know, there was a conservative bone that had gotten activated in him. So he thought

01:50:14.520 --> 01:50:20.720
[Guest]: that because we are sort of these feminists who think in terms of free interaction between

01:50:20.720 --> 01:50:25.560
[Guest]: the sexes, he thought that maybe that's why they think, okay, because this happened in

01:50:25.560 --> 01:50:29.360
[Guest]: a hostel room, they don't want to believe the girl or something like that. And how wrong

01:50:29.360 --> 01:50:34.560
[Guest]: is that? And all of that. So he filled his head with all of this and told several others.

01:50:34.560 --> 01:50:39.200
[Guest]: So those others told me. So I, of course, marched into him and I sat him down and I

01:50:39.200 --> 01:50:43.920
[Guest]: said, pehla toh yeh dar why didn't you ask me first? Okay? I wasn't a student then, but

01:50:43.920 --> 01:50:48.800
[Guest]: I'm a women's organization activist. You could have asked me, I'm in Delhi, or you could

01:50:48.800 --> 01:50:53.600
[Guest]: have asked some of the students. So I said, now I'll tell you what's been happening. So

01:50:53.600 --> 01:50:58.240
[Guest]: I told him that, look, the same night that it, the same evening it happened, a night

01:50:58.240 --> 01:51:04.720
[Guest]: people got to know. So I saw activists, one of whom is a, has had training in psychiatry,

01:51:04.720 --> 01:51:11.920
[Guest]: has had training in counseling. She and some others, they went to meet this survivor. They

01:51:11.920 --> 01:51:17.520
[Guest]: spent hours with her just sitting quietly until she was, or sitting around until she

01:51:17.520 --> 01:51:22.880
[Guest]: was in a position to talk to one of them. When she agreed to talk, she told them what

01:51:22.880 --> 01:51:30.080
[Guest]: happened, but she said that I'm a foreign student and I do not want a police complaint.

01:51:30.080 --> 01:51:35.440
[Guest]: I do not want an MLC done. And I do not want to complain to the university because if my

01:51:35.440 --> 01:51:39.760
[Guest]: parents get to know, that's the end of my education, they will pull me out of college.

01:51:39.760 --> 01:51:44.720
[Guest]: So a lot of attempts happened to persuade her, telling her that her privacy will be

01:51:44.720 --> 01:51:49.440
[Guest]: cared for, but, and to go for an MLC also because she was actually hurting. So they

01:51:49.440 --> 01:51:54.800
[Guest]: said, look, you need medical care, you know, so why don't we take you to a professional

01:51:54.800 --> 01:51:59.040
[Guest]: who will, both medical and psychiatric care? She said, no, because then they are obliged

01:51:59.040 --> 01:52:06.640
[Guest]: by law to report it to the police and I can't have that. So she didn't. And for two days

01:52:06.640 --> 01:52:13.520
[Guest]: after that, different people had been to try and talk to her and had not succeeded. And

01:52:13.520 --> 01:52:17.840
[Guest]: she didn't agree. Eventually, I think at the very end, I think she filed a complaint,

01:52:17.840 --> 01:52:21.920
[Guest]: not of rape, but of sexual harassment. And so that became grounds for the university

01:52:21.920 --> 01:52:26.080
[Guest]: to take some action against him. There could never be a police complaint because she was

01:52:26.080 --> 01:52:32.560
[Guest]: not willing for it. So I told him, why didn't you have faith? And you should have had the

01:52:32.560 --> 01:52:37.440
[Guest]: most faith in those who were most feminist, because it's precisely because they are in

01:52:37.440 --> 01:52:43.120
[Guest]: such strong support of consensual relationships that they understand what is non-consent.

01:52:44.160 --> 01:52:48.560
[Guest]: So they know to distinct, they're not, you know, you're wrong when they think that because

01:52:48.560 --> 01:52:54.480
[Guest]: they think it's okay for people to have sex in hostel rooms, that they think that they

01:52:54.480 --> 01:52:58.480
[Guest]: doubt the statement that this girl says, which is that, oh, I was in a hostel room with him,

01:52:58.480 --> 01:53:03.920
[Guest]: but he raped me. No, it's the opposite. They're believing her because they understand that

01:53:03.920 --> 01:53:09.680
[Guest]: you can have consent, non-consent, and this woman is talking about non-consent. But the

01:53:09.680 --> 01:53:14.640
[Guest]: point is that this takes time. And he said, but it didn't come in the newspaper. I said,

01:53:14.640 --> 01:53:20.880
[Guest]: it will never come in the newspaper. It can't come. You can't. And not, this is just one

01:53:20.880 --> 01:53:28.560
[Guest]: instance. I can, you know, the large, vast number of interventions that we make are of

01:53:28.560 --> 01:53:36.320
[Guest]: this nature where you will not be able to talk about it to anybody, you know? So it's hard,

01:53:36.320 --> 01:53:41.920
[Guest]: you know? I remember that that person was a speaker of a certain language. So one other

01:53:41.920 --> 01:53:47.520
[Guest]: girl contacted me and she had very angry saying, what is ISA doing and how come it's doing nothing?

01:53:48.080 --> 01:53:54.320
[Guest]: So I said, you speak that survivor's language. You yourself are a student. You know ISA well.

01:53:54.320 --> 01:54:01.760
[Guest]: Why don't you go and speak to her? She spoke to her, you know, very confidently. And after

01:54:01.760 --> 01:54:06.800
[Guest]: that, she was absolutely chastised because when she came to me, she had realized that

01:54:06.800 --> 01:54:14.400
[Guest]: this is a fragile woman in a fragile state of being. The main job right now on our part

01:54:14.400 --> 01:54:19.920
[Guest]: had to be to reassure her that she was not at fault because like every rape victim, she

01:54:19.920 --> 01:54:26.960
[Guest]: was saying, why didn't I fight back? Why did I freeze? Why did I freeze when this happened?

01:54:26.960 --> 01:54:32.240
[Guest]: Why didn't I hit him? Why didn't I struggle? He then walked me out to the auto. My God,

01:54:32.240 --> 01:54:37.280
[Guest]: what was I doing? Why didn't I scream? And, you know, people who were experienced had

01:54:37.280 --> 01:54:42.280
[Guest]: to tell her that this is most common. Nobody screams. When someone you know has suddenly

01:54:42.280 --> 01:54:49.360
[Guest]: violated you, you are frozen for a very, very long time. So don't blame yourself. And when

01:54:49.360 --> 01:54:55.200
[Guest]: she's in that state, you can't be pushing her to, you know, say, why aren't you protesting?

01:54:55.200 --> 01:54:58.480
[Guest]: Why aren't you protesting? Why aren't you complaining? Why aren't you going to the police?

01:54:58.480 --> 01:55:04.880
[Guest]: Because you can't. You have to be. And that person realized it. You know, the girl. The

01:55:04.880 --> 01:55:10.400
[Guest]: point is that experience makes you realize this. You can't realize it if you have an

01:55:10.400 --> 01:55:16.640
[Guest]: abstract idea that what feminist activism is, is only about posturing, you know, and

01:55:16.640 --> 01:55:23.840
[Guest]: only about what is done in the public eye. It's not. I took a long time to answer that one. Yeah.

01:55:25.360 --> 01:55:30.160
[Amit Varma]: No, no, that's, that's very illuminating. And, you know, just some messiness of the real world.

01:55:30.160 --> 01:55:34.080
[Amit Varma]: And it's good to get a sense of that sometimes. And this also speaks to, you know, something that

01:55:34.080 --> 01:55:37.520
[Amit Varma]: you've written about in your wonderful book, Peerless Freedom, where you've spoken about how

01:55:37.520 --> 01:55:42.960
[Amit Varma]: so many girls across India, if they're harassed in school or treated badly, they won't complain

01:55:42.960 --> 01:55:46.720
[Amit Varma]: to their parents, because their biggest fear is they won't be allowed to go to school again.

01:55:46.720 --> 01:55:51.360
[Amit Varma]: So that's just so poignant and fundamental. Now, my last two questions about politics,

01:55:51.360 --> 01:55:55.360
[Amit Varma]: and then we'll take a break. And then we can come back and talk about the state of women in India,

01:55:55.360 --> 01:56:00.560
[Amit Varma]: which is such a huge subject. So my penultimate question is this that, you know, when you were

01:56:00.560 --> 01:56:03.920
[Amit Varma]: talking about, you know, the imperative for winning elections with your party, and you said

01:56:03.920 --> 01:56:07.680
[Amit Varma]: that it's not about a brand name winning or a person winning, but it's about a certain class

01:56:07.680 --> 01:56:12.560
[Amit Varma]: of people finally coming through and winning. Now, my question there is, and this could apply to

01:56:12.560 --> 01:56:18.320
[Amit Varma]: the left parties, it could even apply to all kinds of parties, is that this class of people

01:56:18.320 --> 01:56:24.000
[Amit Varma]: whom you're trying to, you know, empower, doesn't vote for you, you know, hasn't voted for you.

01:56:24.000 --> 01:56:29.600
[Amit Varma]: So what does one make of that? Like, you know, people keep talking about with good reason,

01:56:29.600 --> 01:56:34.480
[Amit Varma]: the Brahmanism of the BJP and the RSS and all of that. But the fact of the matter is, in both 2014

01:56:34.480 --> 01:56:39.360
[Amit Varma]: and 2019, in the general elections, you know, more of the Dalit vote went to the BJP than to any

01:56:39.360 --> 01:56:45.040
[Amit Varma]: other party. So how does one then in politics, does there come a time when you begin to question

01:56:45.040 --> 01:56:49.520
[Amit Varma]: yourself when you say that, okay, I am doing this for X class of people, but they don't seem

01:56:49.520 --> 01:56:52.480
[Amit Varma]: interested, they're voting for someone else. So what's going on here?

01:56:54.160 --> 01:56:58.560
[Guest]: Yeah, I'm glad you asked that, because it's a very, very commonly asked question. And it also

01:56:58.560 --> 01:57:03.600
[Guest]: ties in with what you asked earlier, which was about, which I didn't answer that aspect of it,

01:57:03.600 --> 01:57:08.880
[Guest]: which is about the fact that politics in reality involves compromises, it involves, you know,

01:57:08.880 --> 01:57:15.760
[Guest]: tactical considerations, and not just an abstract, ideal thing, right? Because your ideas have to be

01:57:15.760 --> 01:57:20.400
[Guest]: have to become real, they have to be adopted by people. And they have to find space for themselves

01:57:20.400 --> 01:57:25.600
[Guest]: in a real political fight. And that is going to involve rubbing against, it's not going to be

01:57:25.600 --> 01:57:31.920
[Guest]: cast in stone what you do, right? So for me, somehow, my understanding is that this isn't

01:57:31.920 --> 01:57:37.840
[Guest]: really something that has troubled me ever. Because to me, I think, and I think of myself

01:57:37.840 --> 01:57:43.200
[Guest]: as a very classical sort of Marxist Leninist in that sense. Because I think, you know, that was

01:57:43.200 --> 01:57:50.320
[Guest]: the whole thing with Marx and Lenin, that it was about translating Marxist ideas into a political

01:57:50.320 --> 01:57:56.400
[Guest]: movement in a country very removed from where Marx was writing, in a very backward country like

01:57:56.400 --> 01:58:03.600
[Guest]: Russia. And it involved all kinds of compromises. And Lenin is writing about each of those and why

01:58:03.600 --> 01:58:08.560
[Guest]: those were taken. What he wrote also is not cast in stone, because you can see him changing his

01:58:08.560 --> 01:58:14.560
[Guest]: mind, okay? As time changed, not just he, you can see him having ferocious arguments with his

01:58:14.560 --> 01:58:19.920
[Guest]: comrades. And then realizing later that some of them were right, or them realizing later, no,

01:58:19.920 --> 01:58:23.440
[Guest]: no, actually he was right. And sometimes the timing for an idea was just plain wrong.

01:58:24.160 --> 01:58:28.640
[Guest]: Any number of examples. The same thing is what you do, you know, things are not, let me give you

01:58:28.640 --> 01:58:33.600
[Guest]: an example. Jaise humaari party mein election contest nahi karna hai, which is Maoists ka. So,

01:58:33.600 --> 01:58:38.080
[Guest]: even our party, originally at Naxal Party, didn't contest. Because at that time, it was a very

01:58:38.080 --> 01:58:41.840
[Guest]: different time where there were not, you know, there was only one major national party, the

01:58:41.840 --> 01:58:46.320
[Guest]: Congress. And there was a tremendous sentiment of people against it. And so it was, in a sense,

01:58:46.320 --> 01:58:51.600
[Guest]: a revolutionary time. But there was no revolutionary readiness of that kind. And

01:58:51.600 --> 01:58:57.760
[Guest]: so the movements happened, but they were crushed. And after that, you had this rise of so many

01:58:57.760 --> 01:59:03.200
[Guest]: regional parties and all of that. And at that time, to go on saying nahi, nahi, nahi hum shuddh

01:59:03.200 --> 01:59:07.920
[Guest]: hai aur vote nahi daalenge, we realized, and it took us a good long while to realize it, okay,

01:59:07.920 --> 01:59:12.960
[Guest]: my party, that in the early 1980s, when they realized that people in our party, and they were

01:59:12.960 --> 01:59:19.440
[Guest]: Dalit leaders, who had joined our party on their own, they had formed the party not because someone

01:59:19.440 --> 01:59:24.240
[Guest]: from above told them to, because they felt a need for this party. So they made the party.

01:59:24.240 --> 01:59:29.680
[Guest]: And for them, when they listened to people, they realized that the main issue for the Dalit

01:59:29.680 --> 01:59:34.640
[Guest]: laborers in Bihar was not ki election boycott karo, it was the opposite. They said humko vote

01:59:34.640 --> 01:59:40.480
[Guest]: nahi daalne dete. When we go to cast our vote, they kick us out. So they connected that with

01:59:40.480 --> 01:59:45.040
[Guest]: their sense of Dalit dignity and Dalit, you know, so their political rights and social rights were

01:59:45.040 --> 01:59:49.120
[Guest]: actually connected with each other. And their economic rights, because they said we are not

01:59:49.120 --> 01:59:56.400
[Guest]: paid, all of that. So the movement began to fight for their right to cast the vote. And that was a

01:59:56.400 --> 02:00:02.720
[Guest]: very violent confrontation, because even if you go non violently to cast your vote, they would be

02:00:02.720 --> 02:00:09.280
[Guest]: violently killed, shot, you know, for having cast their vote, without the landlord's permission and

02:00:09.280 --> 02:00:13.920
[Guest]: all of that. So then it meant that you had to have some kind of, you know, you have to make

02:00:13.920 --> 02:00:18.320
[Guest]: this a movement, then you had to ensure because the police is not protecting you. So you have to

02:00:18.320 --> 02:00:22.320
[Guest]: ensure that people are protected, and they go together to cast their vote. So you literally

02:00:22.320 --> 02:00:27.760
[Guest]: have to have a jaloose even to cast a vote, right? All of that. So the point is your tactics had to

02:00:27.760 --> 02:00:32.720
[Guest]: change, no? You couldn't stick to one thing saying elections are a pig, you know, Lenin famously said

02:00:32.720 --> 02:00:41.360
[Guest]: Parliament is a pigsty. The point is that he also, his party also entered that pigsty. And so do we,

02:00:41.360 --> 02:00:46.320
[Guest]: and we know it's a damn pigsty. But the point is that in the sense that pigsty in the sense that

02:00:46.320 --> 02:00:52.000
[Guest]: you're likely to get muck on you, okay? Even if you win a small panchayat seat, the number of

02:00:52.000 --> 02:00:58.400
[Guest]: opportunities for corruption is all around you. So how do we deal with it? We deal with it by saying,

02:00:58.400 --> 02:01:04.880
[Guest]: let the janta, public deal with it. So our only stipulation for our public representatives is that

02:01:04.880 --> 02:01:09.200
[Guest]: they and the party should be accountable to people. So they have to be democratic means where

02:01:09.200 --> 02:01:13.680
[Guest]: you have to be transparent and accountable to people. So people have every right to dharna

02:01:13.680 --> 02:01:20.560
[Guest]: pradarshan against you also. So you have to be accountable to them. And if you're not, then sorry,

02:01:20.560 --> 02:01:26.720
[Guest]: you know, you face the consequences. We are not about to, you know. So that is one thing. So it

02:01:26.720 --> 02:01:31.920
[Guest]: hasn't bothered me, therefore, that you have to make these compromises and all. I think I'm getting

02:01:31.920 --> 02:01:38.080
[Guest]: away from your main question, which you asked this time. What was that? I'm so sorry, I got

02:01:38.080 --> 02:01:42.480
[Amit Varma]: carried away by that. Which was that, you know, you're fighting this battle on behalf, you said,

02:01:42.480 --> 02:01:47.600
[Guest]: of a certain class of people. Yeah. So I love that question also, because, you know, for me,

02:01:47.600 --> 02:01:53.440
[Guest]: the point is that it's like, I'll use the Marxist term, which is actually a very useful thing. It's

02:01:53.440 --> 02:01:58.640
[Guest]: not a piece of jargon. So evocative, because it says that people are, you know, you're a worker

02:01:59.360 --> 02:02:04.560
[Guest]: in yourself. So you're a worker. Objectively, you're a masdur. Okay, your relationship with

02:02:04.560 --> 02:02:10.560
[Guest]: your employer is that of a worker and an employer or capitalist, whatever it is. But the point is,

02:02:10.560 --> 02:02:15.360
[Guest]: you're not a worker for yourself, because you're not thinking of yourself as a worker. You're

02:02:15.360 --> 02:02:19.920
[Guest]: thinking of yourself as a, you know, different things at different times, you think of yourself

02:02:19.920 --> 02:02:24.480
[Guest]: as a father, you think of yourself as a mother, you think of yourself as a member of a certain

02:02:24.480 --> 02:02:28.800
[Guest]: caste, you think of yourself as a member of a certain community, you may think of yourself as

02:02:28.800 --> 02:02:34.400
[Guest]: Hindu vis-a-vis Muslim, dozen hats you're wearing, right? You know, so you're different people are

02:02:34.400 --> 02:02:40.000
[Guest]: calling you out to identify yourself in different ways, right? So the Hindutva groups or the

02:02:40.000 --> 02:02:45.680
[Guest]: Shiv Sena would call out to the worker in Mumbai, to say you are identified as a Shiv Sena when it

02:02:45.680 --> 02:02:51.840
[Guest]: comes to vote, even if you're with a left trade union. So that is the whole challenge of trying

02:02:51.840 --> 02:02:57.680
[Guest]: to create a realization. And that happens only in the course of movements. You can't teach it in a

02:02:57.680 --> 02:03:05.280
[Guest]: class, you can't do it abstractly. It is in the course of the movement that a worker may realize

02:03:05.280 --> 02:03:10.480
[Guest]: that she and I'm when I say work, I don't mean an economic category alone. I'm saying somebody,

02:03:10.480 --> 02:03:14.800
[Guest]: for instance, who is oppressed because she is disabled, oppressed because she is Dalit,

02:03:14.800 --> 02:03:21.040
[Guest]: oppressed because she is a lesbian, oppressed, because she is a worker. She can be all those

02:03:21.040 --> 02:03:25.760
[Guest]: things. Okay, one of our trade union leaders. And when I when I say this to you, I'm actually

02:03:25.760 --> 02:03:31.200
[Guest]: thinking about a specific trade union leader we have who is a Safai Karmi, she is a lesbian woman,

02:03:31.200 --> 02:03:37.520
[Guest]: she is a, you know, someone who is, who has faced oppression as a Dalit. Okay, all of these things.

02:03:37.520 --> 02:03:41.920
[Guest]: And now she is all of those things when she's fighting, right? The point is that for her to

02:03:41.920 --> 02:03:47.280
[Guest]: realize that she is not, there are, you know, the BJP will call out to her saying, identify as a

02:03:47.280 --> 02:03:53.680
[Guest]: Hindu, hate the Muslims and vote for us. Or identify just as a subject of the government,

02:03:53.680 --> 02:03:57.840
[Guest]: who will get these, these things that the government will give you, if you are loyal,

02:03:57.840 --> 02:04:04.000
[Guest]: right? You just be loyal and you take these things. So, the idea that no, I actually need more,

02:04:04.000 --> 02:04:09.760
[Guest]: I expect more and I expect a certain dignity. I don't expect it for myself alone. I expect it for

02:04:09.760 --> 02:04:14.960
[Guest]: everybody, including those who are not part of my group, my organization, whatever. So,

02:04:14.960 --> 02:04:20.640
[Guest]: those people who are fighting, right? Who are fighting those movements. I'm talking about the

02:04:20.640 --> 02:04:27.600
[Guest]: victory for that movement. It will not always be on part of the majority. It's often a minority

02:04:27.600 --> 02:04:33.280
[Guest]: that is fighting it even within among the oppressed. The point is, it has a potential to

02:04:33.280 --> 02:04:38.960
[Guest]: change. So, what side do I want to be? Does my party want to be? What is the point of CPIML

02:04:38.960 --> 02:04:45.280
[Guest]: existing? Let me ask it that way. Okay. The point of a party like mine existing at all,

02:04:45.840 --> 02:04:51.360
[Guest]: is if it is going to be consistently every time, whatever tactical choices it makes, and it will

02:04:51.360 --> 02:04:57.680
[Guest]: be. We never used to align with any bourgeois party. We aligned, Congress to chodhi do. We

02:04:57.680 --> 02:05:03.120
[Guest]: did align eventually with some other parties and this time we aligned with the Congress, with RJD,

02:05:03.120 --> 02:05:08.800
[Guest]: the same RJD jiske saath 90s bhar we remained separate and we were at loggerheads. Okay.

02:05:09.600 --> 02:05:14.160
[Guest]: So, how did these changes happen? No matter what decision, because circumstances changed,

02:05:14.160 --> 02:05:20.400
[Guest]: okay? But you're making each decision thinking about is it going to help and advance

02:05:20.400 --> 02:05:26.160
[Guest]: this movement that's going on here? These movements, or these, you know, the potential

02:05:26.160 --> 02:05:30.960
[Guest]: for transformative change, you know, so every decision you make has to be on the side of that

02:05:30.960 --> 02:05:35.840
[Guest]: change. If it is not on the side of that change, if it is on the side of saying, achcha chalo,

02:05:35.840 --> 02:05:40.720
[Guest]: hum log bhi SEZ bana lete hain, hum log bhi kisanon ki jameen chheen lete hain, hum log bhi

02:05:40.720 --> 02:05:45.920
[Guest]: let's also do what all every other party does. And what's the point of a left party existing?

02:05:45.920 --> 02:05:51.520
[Guest]: That I think was what happened in Bengal and it should be a lesson to everyone on the left.

02:05:51.520 --> 02:05:57.760
[Guest]: I'm not saying this to score a sectarian point with the CPIM, but I really think that a party

02:05:57.760 --> 02:06:04.640
[Guest]: that was loved for its, by the peasantry, okay, with all my differences with it, I have to say

02:06:04.640 --> 02:06:12.400
[Guest]: that, I mean, CPM had the loyalty and the love of the peasants of Bengal for decades and that broke

02:06:12.400 --> 02:06:20.000
[Guest]: because they became a party that took land away. Now, other parties take land away and may get

02:06:20.000 --> 02:06:25.600
[Guest]: votes in spite of that, but not a left party, because they're not with you for that. They don't

02:06:25.600 --> 02:06:32.240
[Guest]: expect you to be doing that stuff, you know. So to my mind, it's that, that is the raison d'etre,

02:06:32.240 --> 02:06:38.720
[Guest]: that that's what you're going to keep doing. And your movements are primary, but your movement,

02:06:38.720 --> 02:06:44.880
[Guest]: I do not see movements as being contrary. I see the political interventions and the elections as

02:06:44.880 --> 02:06:52.080
[Guest]: being an extension of the movement. And therefore, and I'm not saying that caste considerations and

02:06:52.080 --> 02:06:56.640
[Guest]: all are not there. Of course, they will be because they must be there. Why not? You know,

02:06:56.640 --> 02:07:01.840
[Guest]: for instance, all our candidates in the Bihar election this time, it so happened that most of

02:07:01.840 --> 02:07:10.400
[Guest]: them were from the Dalit or OBC castes, okay. No women, okay. No women. I'm not happy with that.

02:07:10.400 --> 02:07:14.720
[Guest]: But a lot of people asked us, so did you plan that all these must be Dalit and OBC?

02:07:15.360 --> 02:07:21.920
[Guest]: And we told them that, look, it happened that way, because we only saw, okay, who is the person who

02:07:21.920 --> 02:07:27.360
[Guest]: is leading movements there. And the movements comprise of people from these groups. Naturally,

02:07:27.360 --> 02:07:32.320
[Guest]: the leadership is from those groups. And it's very natural. In some place, if there happens to be a

02:07:32.320 --> 02:07:38.400
[Guest]: leader who is, and there have been, okay, there have been leaders of struggles of the oppressed,

02:07:38.400 --> 02:07:44.160
[Guest]: who happened to not be from those communities. But they have been accepted as part of those

02:07:44.160 --> 02:07:51.520
[Guest]: communities because they have literally been willing to die with them. Somebody gave me this

02:07:51.520 --> 02:07:56.160
[Guest]: answer once when I was asking them, I was playing devil's advocate. So I'll tell you.

02:07:56.160 --> 02:08:04.240
[Guest]: So there was a, in the part of Bihar, there was a very terrible attack quite recently,

02:08:04.240 --> 02:08:11.040
[Guest]: some years back, and a sudden attack by some, you know, basically upper caste people,

02:08:11.040 --> 02:08:16.560
[Guest]: including a policeman. And among those who were killed were one person from a very, very,

02:08:16.560 --> 02:08:23.200
[Guest]: you know, extremely backward caste. So he was also from our party, he was a party leader.

02:08:23.200 --> 02:08:27.440
[Guest]: And the other person was also a party leader, but he happened to be from the same caste

02:08:28.000 --> 02:08:33.040
[Guest]: as the guys who were doing the attacking. Okay, and he was also hacked to death. In fact,

02:08:33.040 --> 02:08:39.440
[Guest]: they hacked him to death first. Okay, so it was, they were clearly, you know, they planned to kill

02:08:39.440 --> 02:08:48.800
[Guest]: him. So we were talking, and I was just playing devil's advocate about this. Some time after that,

02:08:48.800 --> 02:08:53.280
[Guest]: some meeting, we had met other people. And I was just asking those some other comrades,

02:09:02.160 --> 02:09:08.240
[Guest]: so would you accept them as a leader of a movement which you are leading? Because you are also

02:09:08.240 --> 02:09:13.760
[Guest]: leaders, but would they be also a leader of your movement? Why would you accept that as a member

02:09:13.760 --> 02:09:19.600
[Guest]: of your committee or whatever? So they looked at us and they said,

02:09:26.800 --> 02:09:31.840
[Guest]: so why would I consider the opportunist Dalit leader who is with the BJP or the

02:09:31.840 --> 02:09:39.600
[Guest]: LJP or whatever as my leader, who is betraying me, betraying my caste and my class to the oppressor,

02:09:39.600 --> 02:09:44.000
[Guest]: why would I consider them my leader? I'm considering the guy who's willing to be with me, live in my

02:09:44.000 --> 02:09:52.560
[Guest]: house, eat what food I eat, and shed blood with me as my leader. I trust him. So that I thought was

02:09:52.560 --> 02:09:59.280
[Guest]: a pretty powerful answer. And yeah, it does happen. But if there is someone like that,

02:09:59.280 --> 02:10:02.720
[Guest]: they may also contest an election. It's not like we, that doesn't happen.

02:10:03.440 --> 02:10:08.000
[Amit Varma]: So one quick follow up question before we go to the break, just part of this thread with a

02:10:08.000 --> 02:10:12.080
[Amit Varma]: wonderful answer. Like, you know, one of the cliches on my show, which has become a cliche,

02:10:12.080 --> 02:10:16.240
[Amit Varma]: because I say it so often is that, you know, we all contain multitudes, people contain multitudes,

02:10:16.240 --> 02:10:21.520
[Amit Varma]: which of course, comes from Walt Whitman's famous poem. And that's part of the answer you gave that

02:10:21.520 --> 02:10:25.440
[Amit Varma]: why don't these people vote for us, because there are many aspects to their personality. And in a

02:10:25.440 --> 02:10:30.720
[Amit Varma]: sense, that can give us hope that today, if a particular party is appealing to one particular

02:10:30.720 --> 02:10:35.280
[Amit Varma]: aspect of their character or personality or beliefs, that maybe there is a way to find

02:10:35.280 --> 02:10:39.680
[Amit Varma]: something else to appeal to maybe the better angels of the nature, so to say. But the question

02:10:39.680 --> 02:10:46.560
[Amit Varma]: then that also comes up is that, are you in any way that as a party, when you focus on this one

02:10:46.560 --> 02:10:52.080
[Amit Varma]: thing, say, maybe it's their identity as workers in the broad sense that you mean it in, or whatever

02:10:52.080 --> 02:10:59.600
[Amit Varma]: the locus of oppression is, does that then become reductionist in some way? Like, is there a danger

02:10:59.600 --> 02:11:05.360
[Amit Varma]: that there is one hammer you're taking to every nail? And that these people may not necessarily see

02:11:05.360 --> 02:11:12.320
[Amit Varma]: themselves as only that, that I am my identity is X, and therefore I am only oppressed? A lot else

02:11:12.320 --> 02:11:17.360
[Amit Varma]: is there. So do you think there is that danger? Does that kind of self doubt ever creep in?

02:11:18.240 --> 02:11:25.840
[Guest]: Yeah, I see what you're saying. But and totally, I don't think that that is a danger in the sense

02:11:25.840 --> 02:11:31.920
[Guest]: that I think you see that somebody who is part of such a movement wants to be able to live a fuller

02:11:31.920 --> 02:11:38.160
[Guest]: life, right? So they would like to go on a holiday, they would like to have fun, they would like to do

02:11:38.160 --> 02:11:45.760
[Guest]: things. But the point is that their location makes it such that they are either deprived of the means

02:11:45.760 --> 02:11:52.640
[Guest]: to enjoy this, or deprived of even the right to dream of enjoying it or to demand to enjoy it,

02:11:52.640 --> 02:12:01.600
[Guest]: right? So they are joining a struggle with the sky being the limit. Okay. So I often say this,

02:12:01.600 --> 02:12:09.440
[Guest]: that, you know, I've had that argument in my head once with, I think, an essay I read once by

02:12:09.440 --> 02:12:14.320
[Guest]: TM Krishna, where he had written something about the left being, I think, you know, why does the

02:12:14.320 --> 02:12:21.680
[Guest]: left think that the working class doesn't deserve to have consumer products? And I felt that he was

02:12:21.680 --> 02:12:27.120
[Guest]: wrong to say that, to think that the left thought that. I never got a chance to ask him, in fact,

02:12:27.120 --> 02:12:34.560
[Guest]: why he thought that way, why he felt that the left actually has such a constrained vision. Okay,

02:12:34.560 --> 02:12:39.520
[Guest]: I don't think so. I remember that, for instance, what struck me when I read about the Russian

02:12:39.520 --> 02:12:45.600
[Guest]: Revolution, is that one of the first things that happened there, quite apart from a whole lot of,

02:12:45.600 --> 02:12:52.720
[Guest]: you know, collectivization, by everybody got a right to go on a holiday to the beach. Okay,

02:12:52.720 --> 02:12:58.640
[Guest]: so entire working class families were getting to enjoy holidays at the beach and enjoy, you know,

02:12:58.640 --> 02:13:03.760
[Guest]: a vacation, which otherwise they could never have dreamt of doing. And to my mind, you know,

02:13:03.760 --> 02:13:09.680
[Guest]: something like that, which is an act of pleasure. It is not something which is, you know, so it is

02:13:09.680 --> 02:13:15.520
[Guest]: not a philosophy of deprivation, you know, your struggle is not something which is valorizing

02:13:15.520 --> 02:13:21.120
[Guest]: deprivation, which is valorizing, starving yourself of the good things in life. Rather,

02:13:21.120 --> 02:13:26.480
[Guest]: it is saying that, you know, let's be a struggling so that everyone gets the good things in life,

02:13:26.480 --> 02:13:32.320
[Guest]: which means that then your identity also, it's not so much about saying, okay, I'm this worker

02:13:32.320 --> 02:13:38.880
[Guest]: and must always be that, right? It's like, again, you know, that beautiful thing that Marx writes

02:13:38.880 --> 02:13:44.880
[Guest]: about what he says is that after, you know, in a truly revolutionary society, somebody could be a,

02:13:44.880 --> 02:13:49.760
[Guest]: you know, a fisherman in the morning and play the violin in the afternoon, and, you know,

02:13:49.760 --> 02:13:55.360
[Guest]: be this philosopher in the evening, and, you know, so on and so forth. So the point is that you can

02:13:55.360 --> 02:14:00.720
[Guest]: be all those multitudes that you contain, and you can be all of them, you don't have to forswear

02:14:00.720 --> 02:14:07.840
[Guest]: one of them to be the other, right. And I keep saying that even now, I say that to myself also,

02:14:07.840 --> 02:14:13.360
[Guest]: because sometimes the pressure of work is such that you forget the other people that you are,

02:14:13.360 --> 02:14:17.600
[Guest]: right. So I, of course, I'll be saying it on your podcast, and now everyone will realize I,

02:14:18.560 --> 02:14:24.000
[Guest]: the truth. I lurk on Insta, I don't post much political stuff there only in the last year,

02:14:24.000 --> 02:14:28.640
[Guest]: I've had to because during the lockdown, people started doing Insta lives and all.

02:14:28.640 --> 02:14:37.280
[Guest]: But otherwise, I used to lurk on Insta, only to post all the kutta billi nature pictures,

02:14:37.280 --> 02:14:43.200
[Guest]: because that is a big part of who I am. I'm an amateur, complete amateur, but I love sort of

02:14:43.200 --> 02:14:49.360
[Guest]: wandering around, looking at things growing and figuring out how animals and birds live and this

02:14:49.360 --> 02:14:54.000
[Guest]: and that, and enjoying all those things. So the point is, when I travel, I do a lot of this,

02:14:54.000 --> 02:14:58.240
[Guest]: you know, picture taking with my phone. What do I do with all of that? It's not part of the

02:14:58.240 --> 02:15:03.280
[Guest]: Andolan stuff that I'm going to post on my Facebook or Twitter. So then Insta is the

02:15:03.280 --> 02:15:08.160
[Guest]: place where I park that and I'm that person there. So I have a whole lot of Insta friends,

02:15:08.720 --> 02:15:16.720
[Guest]: who are basically just cat aunties or cat mothers or who are, you know, wonderful cooks or something

02:15:17.360 --> 02:15:23.520
[Guest]: all over the world. So they're not people who, you know, necessarily know much about what I'm

02:15:23.520 --> 02:15:29.120
[Guest]: doing in my other lives. Okay. But I'm that person also. And I think of Rosa Luxemburg,

02:15:29.120 --> 02:15:35.280
[Guest]: she, I've just gotten a copy of her book, you know, so they published her herbarium.

02:15:35.840 --> 02:15:42.880
[Guest]: So she, you know, she was a committed communist leader. She, all her life was like that. But she

02:15:42.880 --> 02:15:46.560
[Guest]: also, you know, wherever she went, she was very interested in nature. So she used to collect,

02:15:46.560 --> 02:15:51.680
[Guest]: you know, plants and flowers, and try and figure out what the name was, what the genus was,

02:15:51.680 --> 02:15:57.440
[Guest]: what the species was. And you realize when you read her writing about this thing, that she's also

02:15:57.440 --> 02:16:03.440
[Guest]: writing with such love about this, that this is some, you know, she's not writing, she's not

02:16:03.440 --> 02:16:11.680
[Guest]: reducing any of this to explaining it away in some, some sharp Marxist phrase, okay. She's

02:16:11.680 --> 02:16:18.400
[Guest]: realizing that in this natural world and in animals, there is so much to understand and

02:16:18.400 --> 02:16:23.200
[Guest]: their emotions and understanding, which human beings have not yet fathomed, they don't understand

02:16:23.200 --> 02:16:29.200
[Guest]: it. So she's writing about it with such feelings, knowing that, in a way, she's writing about the

02:16:29.200 --> 02:16:35.680
[Guest]: unknown. You know, she's writing, and there's almost a sense of a spiritual sort of enjoyment

02:16:35.680 --> 02:16:41.760
[Guest]: in that, a spiritual experience in that, let me put it that way. You know, and she maintained it

02:16:41.760 --> 02:16:47.040
[Guest]: till her death. I mean, you know, while being all the other revolutionary leaders that she was,

02:16:47.040 --> 02:16:58.000
[Guest]: so she wasn't, you know, I have good friends who remind me not to become a stick in the mud, who,

02:16:58.000 --> 02:17:04.080
[Guest]: you know, has no time for leisure and pleasure and for being these other people that I am.

