02:18:52.000 --> 02:18:55.920
[Amit Varma]: Welcome back to the scene and the unseen. I'm chatting with Kavita Krishnan about a formidable

02:18:55.920 --> 02:19:02.800
[Amit Varma]: career in life so far, but also about the state of women in India and her feminism and so on. And

02:19:02.800 --> 02:19:07.200
[Amit Varma]: let me begin with this question. You know, I've heard you say about your mother in an interview,

02:19:07.200 --> 02:19:11.600
[Amit Varma]: I found that, and you said it at the start of the show as well, that she was, quote,

02:19:11.600 --> 02:19:18.320
[Amit Varma]: a feminist by instinct rather than by training, stop quote. So and I presume that's the way for

02:19:18.320 --> 02:19:23.440
[Amit Varma]: every feminist that first, it is, of course, the instinct, you feel that this is the right thing

02:19:23.440 --> 02:19:28.080
[Amit Varma]: to do, it's the right way to behave, and so on and so forth. And then eventually, you read more,

02:19:28.080 --> 02:19:33.200
[Amit Varma]: you learn more. And that training sort of happens in different kinds of ways, whether through,

02:19:33.200 --> 02:19:37.520
[Amit Varma]: you know, osmosis, or just reading up on the subject, but once you get interested in it,

02:19:37.520 --> 02:19:43.120
[Amit Varma]: tell me a little bit about your journey into actually thinking about feminism in that kind

02:19:43.120 --> 02:19:49.680
[Amit Varma]: of formal way, and how it evolved, like, would you define it differently today in any way or

02:19:49.680 --> 02:19:57.680
[Guest]: nuance than you would have maybe 30 years ago? I think that for me, I mean, the way I came to

02:19:57.680 --> 02:20:04.320
[Guest]: feminist reading and feminist literature and so on was, I guess, in my BA in Bombay. So at that

02:20:04.320 --> 02:20:11.200
[Guest]: time, of course, I mean, I was, I had access to a lot of feminist writing, and some of it was part

02:20:11.200 --> 02:20:17.120
[Guest]: of curriculum. Some of it was just stuff that our teachers would read, and so they would encourage

02:20:17.120 --> 02:20:22.640
[Guest]: us to read. And then the same happened continued in JNU also. So you were, you know, you were

02:20:22.640 --> 02:20:28.320
[Guest]: exposed to a lot of feminist literary criticism, feminist writing, and all of that. So that,

02:20:28.320 --> 02:20:34.640
[Guest]: of course, I got only later in life during while studying. So the only thing is the way I would

02:20:34.640 --> 02:20:41.840
[Guest]: define myself would largely be the same as it always was, which is the idea of an instinct,

02:20:41.840 --> 02:20:50.240
[Guest]: I mean, a basic, basically the fact that you are striving for truly a society which is truly free

02:20:50.240 --> 02:20:56.400
[Guest]: of discrimination, of an oppression, okay, of oppression and of structural inequality.

02:20:57.120 --> 02:21:03.840
[Guest]: Okay, but I think that my ideas about how to achieve that, how you're going to get there,

02:21:03.840 --> 02:21:09.600
[Guest]: those have probably undergone some change. For instance, had you asked me when I was in school,

02:21:09.600 --> 02:21:17.200
[Guest]: okay, before I came to Bombay, I used to think that I was not in support of reservations.

02:21:17.200 --> 02:21:23.680
[Guest]: So the idea of caste or gender-based reservations, had you asked me, I would have probably said,

02:21:23.680 --> 02:21:28.480
[Guest]: no, you know. But the thing is that that was the time when the Mandal Commission

02:21:28.480 --> 02:21:33.840
[Guest]: had just been implemented. So I came to Bombay in 1990. So just in the wake of that,

02:21:33.840 --> 02:21:40.960
[Guest]: so there were the anti-Mandal agitations happening and all of that. And I am enormously relieved

02:21:40.960 --> 02:21:46.720
[Guest]: that as someone who is born in a privileged caste and had the privilege of not thinking

02:21:46.720 --> 02:21:51.680
[Guest]: about caste, right, so I had spent 18 years of my life with a great privilege of not having

02:21:51.680 --> 02:21:56.800
[Guest]: had to think about caste, because nobody was oppressing me on the basis of caste. So I could

02:21:56.800 --> 02:22:03.520
[Guest]: say, oh, I'm free of caste. But I'm hugely relieved that in Bombay, being in the social science centre,

02:22:03.520 --> 02:22:10.480
[Guest]: you know, I studied English literature, but since I happened to sort of fall in with

02:22:10.480 --> 02:22:16.240
[Guest]: the social science centre and there was someone called Father Rudy Heredia there, he's still here

02:22:16.240 --> 02:22:21.360
[Guest]: in Delhi. But Father Rudy was there, there were others, there were my friends there,

02:22:21.360 --> 02:22:27.360
[Guest]: there were other young students or former students who would come. So the talk there that I was

02:22:27.360 --> 02:22:33.680
[Guest]: exposed to, the arguments I was exposed to there, very quickly disabused me of these ideas of an

02:22:33.680 --> 02:22:39.840
[Guest]: abstract equality. So the point was that they would, you know, it would very quickly come to,

02:22:39.840 --> 02:22:43.840
[Guest]: I remember having this talk with Father Rudy, asking him with a great deal of diffidence,

02:22:44.640 --> 02:22:50.880
[Guest]: what do you say to people who say that the OBC reservations are wrong, Mandal Commission is wrong,

02:22:50.880 --> 02:22:57.440
[Guest]: what would you say? So he very patiently explained it to me and he said, you know, there is inequality,

02:22:57.440 --> 02:23:02.560
[Guest]: you know, all around. So there has to be something to correct that inequality. If you're going to,

02:23:02.560 --> 02:23:06.160
[Guest]: in the name of equality, if you're going to apply the same thing to everybody,

02:23:06.800 --> 02:23:16.160
[Guest]: then you're actually perpetuating inequality, because you're giving everyone the same means,

02:23:16.160 --> 02:23:21.440
[Guest]: who are, you know, you're not correcting for inequality. So if you don't correct for that,

02:23:21.440 --> 02:23:26.560
[Guest]: if you don't acknowledge that inequality exists, and from there I started thinking about, you know,

02:23:26.560 --> 02:23:33.600
[Guest]: the idea that yes, then even when it comes to feminism, surely then you have to realize that

02:23:33.600 --> 02:23:39.680
[Guest]: all women also are not constituted the same. Women and men are not the same, that's one thing.

02:23:39.680 --> 02:23:44.320
[Guest]: But all women also, you know, there are differences which are not constituted the same.

02:23:44.320 --> 02:23:50.720
[Guest]: You know, there are differences which are socially there. So somebody who is a domestic worker,

02:23:50.720 --> 02:23:56.400
[Guest]: somebody who is from an oppressed caste, someone who has the privilege of studying

02:23:56.400 --> 02:24:01.360
[Guest]: in an urban center in an English medium school, and someone who doesn't have that privilege,

02:24:01.360 --> 02:24:07.040
[Guest]: there are enormous, you know, chasms there. So instead of talking only about, you know,

02:24:07.040 --> 02:24:12.480
[Guest]: as being a feminism, talking about women as a category, right, as an abstract category,

02:24:12.480 --> 02:24:17.520
[Guest]: you would also have to talk about pretty specific other kinds of oppression that are happening,

02:24:17.520 --> 02:24:24.000
[Guest]: right? Then in terms of other changes that happened was, very early on, I can say that

02:24:24.640 --> 02:24:32.960
[Guest]: I was very much in support of LGBT rights, especially in terms of the L and G parts of

02:24:32.960 --> 02:24:40.480
[Guest]: those, which I was more, you know, which I had a reason to think about and directly sort of

02:24:40.480 --> 02:24:46.960
[Guest]: experience and interact with much earlier on in my BA days itself, okay. So close friends who had,

02:24:47.520 --> 02:24:53.760
[Guest]: you know, come out to me as lesbian, my own thinking about my own self and sexual self,

02:24:53.760 --> 02:24:59.840
[Guest]: and, you know, which is certainly such a part of yourself, right? But even thinking about that self

02:24:59.840 --> 02:25:07.920
[Guest]: and having, you know, very close relationships that were with women and not so much with men

02:25:07.920 --> 02:25:12.400
[Guest]: at that time. So the point is that you were, you know, you're going through a period of thinking

02:25:12.400 --> 02:25:17.520
[Guest]: also and of doubt and of recognising that obviously there is this spectrum inside you. At that time,

02:25:17.520 --> 02:25:23.840
[Guest]: the word spectrum was not used that much. But when I came across it, I could immediately connect it

02:25:23.840 --> 02:25:29.920
[Guest]: with my own sense of self and say that, yes, instead of ticking a box that says heterosexual,

02:25:29.920 --> 02:25:36.560
[Guest]: tuck, you know, it's not exactly like that, or you can't just tick heterosexual or bi so easily.

02:25:36.560 --> 02:25:43.280
[Guest]: The point is that you are someone who, you may be someone who occupies some places on a spectrum,

02:25:43.280 --> 02:25:50.080
[Guest]: and that place shifts depending on who you are and who you're meeting and where you are in your life,

02:25:50.080 --> 02:25:56.240
[Guest]: you know, all of that. But for me, the new thing was that I did not know, I knew very little about

02:25:56.880 --> 02:26:04.880
[Guest]: transgender experiences at all, okay. I knew very little. So I had experience of meeting

02:26:04.880 --> 02:26:12.640
[Guest]: trans persons in Bombay, but I didn't really have enough to understand or to get to know more.

02:26:12.640 --> 02:26:19.760
[Guest]: That happened over time. And I would now correct a lot of my articulations. So just to give you

02:26:19.760 --> 02:26:26.000
[Guest]: an example, one of the classic things which I, you know, when I'm explaining gender to somebody,

02:26:26.000 --> 02:26:30.480
[Guest]: the first thing I would say is that, look, there's biology. So there's, you know, what you're born

02:26:30.480 --> 02:26:38.880
[Guest]: with. And there is the socialization aspect of it. So biology is ladka hona, ladki hona. But the idea

02:26:38.880 --> 02:26:44.000
[Guest]: that there is a masculine and feminine, this is something that comes with socialization. Simple.

02:26:44.720 --> 02:26:50.320
[Guest]: But now all that is complicated, because who you are born, it is not, I can't say that anymore.

02:26:50.320 --> 02:26:56.400
[Guest]: I can't go and repeat this anymore, you know, unquestioningly, because clearly my understanding

02:26:56.400 --> 02:27:02.800
[Guest]: of that has been completely scrambled by not only the fact that political movements have developed

02:27:02.800 --> 02:27:08.480
[Guest]: around transgender identities, but also the fact that the science on this has changed.

02:27:08.480 --> 02:27:13.920
[Guest]: You know, the science on this tells you that, sorry, you know, your biological gender is not

02:27:13.920 --> 02:27:20.400
[Guest]: something just fixed, you know, by certain body parts. It is not, you know, so your chromosomes

02:27:20.400 --> 02:27:25.520
[Guest]: are there and there is a spectrum even there. And the point is that it's not and who you're

02:27:25.520 --> 02:27:32.160
[Guest]: expressing yourself, yourself, as in just like your sexual orientation, who you are inside

02:27:32.800 --> 02:27:39.440
[Guest]: is eventually something which you experience and only you can tell. And what if you feel that you

02:27:39.440 --> 02:27:45.680
[Guest]: are somebody who is a woman, you know, who's trapped in a man's body or the other way around?

02:27:47.040 --> 02:27:52.800
[Guest]: You know, who is someone else to tell you that, oh, this is just a statement you're making or

02:27:52.800 --> 02:27:57.360
[Guest]: something like that, right? So I still think that my learning on this is still underway.

02:27:57.360 --> 02:28:04.400
[Guest]: I still find it difficult to, I still feel very self-conscious if I use words other than women

02:28:04.400 --> 02:28:10.640
[Guest]: and men. So if I try to write W-O-M-X-N, I feel self-conscious because it's not something I'm

02:28:10.640 --> 02:28:16.000
[Guest]: used to doing. And so I feel a little, oh, but I really, and then I often don't use it. Okay.

02:28:16.000 --> 02:28:20.080
[Guest]: So I then go back to using what I'm comfortable with. I'm not saying that's correct. I'm not

02:28:20.080 --> 02:28:25.440
[Guest]: saying that's right, but I'm just saying that it's a, I think it's a process where one continuously

02:28:25.440 --> 02:28:32.560
[Guest]: thinks about things and, you know, makes oneself uncomfortable and welcomes discomfort. So for me,

02:28:32.560 --> 02:28:38.800
[Guest]: feminism in a way is about welcoming discomfort about one's understanding of the world around us

02:28:38.800 --> 02:28:44.080
[Guest]: and of recognizing that there's inequality and recognizing that therefore, for equity,

02:28:44.080 --> 02:28:50.080
[Guest]: it's not just, samanta nahi chalega. Agar aapko samta chahiye, really, in a real sense, then you have to

02:28:50.080 --> 02:28:55.680
[Guest]: recognize ki log saman hai and then you can't have a one size fits all for everybody. And then I

02:28:55.680 --> 02:29:00.960
[Guest]: realized that this idea is actually right there, up there in Marx also, because when he talks,

02:29:00.960 --> 02:29:08.480
[Guest]: I think in the Gotha program about socialism and what happens after socialism, he actually says

02:29:08.480 --> 02:29:13.760
[Guest]: that in socialism, you know, you can have each according to his work and from each according

02:29:13.760 --> 02:29:19.680
[Guest]: to his capacity. But ideally, you are working for a society where it's to each according to their need

02:29:20.240 --> 02:29:25.120
[Guest]: and from each according to their capacity. So it doesn't matter about how much work you're able to

02:29:25.120 --> 02:29:31.360
[Guest]: do. You may be elderly, you may be disabled. So the kind of work you do, it's not about how much

02:29:31.360 --> 02:29:38.000
[Guest]: you contribute. It's about what you need. So society owes you what you need and you do according

02:29:38.000 --> 02:29:44.320
[Guest]: to your capacity. So, you know, that also, he explains this, Marx explains this at great length

02:29:44.320 --> 02:29:50.800
[Guest]: about the fact that when you're going to apply equal things to unequal people, then you're not

02:29:50.800 --> 02:29:56.800
[Amit Varma]: going to get equity as a result, you know. Okay, I'm not quite a Marxist, as listeners

02:29:56.800 --> 02:30:02.000
[Amit Varma]: would know, but I am definitely a feminist. So I'll come at a long winded question and, you know,

02:30:02.000 --> 02:30:07.120
[Amit Varma]: begin with sort of where I got my understanding of feminism from and how that kind of evolved.

02:30:07.120 --> 02:30:12.320
[Amit Varma]: And my basic I mean, obviously, you begin with instinct that hey, everyone should be treated

02:30:12.320 --> 02:30:17.360
[Amit Varma]: equally and all of that. I think my first fundamental influence on me in learning about

02:30:17.360 --> 02:30:22.160
[Amit Varma]: feminism was one that perhaps a lot of people share, which is Mary Wollstonecraft's vindication

02:30:22.160 --> 02:30:26.640
[Amit Varma]: of the rights of women. Because before that, I really got into Locke and natural rights and

02:30:26.640 --> 02:30:30.560
[Amit Varma]: the right to self ownership, all other rights coming from there, blah, blah, blah, the whole

02:30:30.560 --> 02:30:37.120
[Amit Varma]: classical liberalism thing. And Wollstonecraft also read Locke and got her sort of principles

02:30:37.120 --> 02:30:41.280
[Amit Varma]: from there, except that she extended it, she said that these rights should be everybody's not just

02:30:41.280 --> 02:30:47.360
[Amit Varma]: men, but also women. And in those days, of course, you didn't use neutral pronouns. So, but

02:30:47.360 --> 02:30:51.520
[Amit Varma]: Wollstonecraft's a big thing was saying that, yeah, Lockean, but for everyone, women should

02:30:51.520 --> 02:30:57.440
[Amit Varma]: be treated equally. And that's, you know, pretty much for the next, say, 170, 180 years, that

02:30:57.440 --> 02:31:02.960
[Amit Varma]: that's basically what it was that men and women should be treated equally. Now, a couple of decades

02:31:02.960 --> 02:31:08.080
[Amit Varma]: ago, Christina Hoff Summers wrote this book called Who Stole Feminism, where she spoke about,

02:31:08.080 --> 02:31:12.880
[Amit Varma]: you know, the two sort of schools of thought within feminism, which were coming up and, you

02:31:12.880 --> 02:31:19.120
[Amit Varma]: know, equity feminism and gender feminism. And about equity feminism, she is basically this

02:31:19.120 --> 02:31:25.440
[Amit Varma]: whole Locke and Wollstonecraft view that, you know, it opposes sex discrimination, other forms

02:31:25.440 --> 02:31:30.640
[Amit Varma]: of unfairness to women, and so on and so forth. And it guided the first wave of feminism launched

02:31:30.640 --> 02:31:37.280
[Amit Varma]: the second wave, so on. And gender feminism looks at, you know, a more in Steven Pinker's words,

02:31:37.920 --> 02:31:42.720
[Amit Varma]: words, and I'm quoting from a blank slate, gender feminism holds that women continue to be enslaved

02:31:42.720 --> 02:31:48.000
[Amit Varma]: by a pervasive system of male dominance, the gender system in which bisexual infants are

02:31:48.000 --> 02:31:52.640
[Amit Varma]: transformed into male and female gender personalities, the one destined to command

02:31:52.640 --> 02:31:58.080
[Amit Varma]: the other to obey, stop quote. And then later, he sort of writes about what this means what

02:31:58.080 --> 02:32:03.040
[Amit Varma]: this difference means in practical terms, where he says, quote, equity feminism is a moral doctrine

02:32:03.040 --> 02:32:08.400
[Amit Varma]: about equal treatment that makes no commitments regarding open empirical issues in psychology or

02:32:08.400 --> 02:32:14.160
[Amit Varma]: biology. Gender feminism is an empirical doctrine committed to three claims about human nature.

02:32:14.160 --> 02:32:17.840
[Amit Varma]: The first is that the differences between men and women have nothing to do with biology, but

02:32:17.840 --> 02:32:23.280
[Amit Varma]: are socially constructed in in their entirety. The second is that humans possess a single social

02:32:23.280 --> 02:32:28.320
[Amit Varma]: motive, and that social life can be understood only in terms of how it is exercised. The third

02:32:28.320 --> 02:32:33.120
[Amit Varma]: is that human interactions arise not from the motives of people dealing with each other as

02:32:33.120 --> 02:32:38.240
[Amit Varma]: individuals, but from the motives dealing with other groups, in this case, a male gender

02:32:38.240 --> 02:32:43.120
[Amit Varma]: dominating the female gender, stop quote. And what we see in modern times with intersectionality and

02:32:43.120 --> 02:32:47.040
[Amit Varma]: all that is that it's not just male gender dominating female gender. But within this,

02:32:47.040 --> 02:32:52.560
[Amit Varma]: there are groups and subgroups, but the overall narrative is a narrative of oppression and

02:32:52.560 --> 02:32:59.200
[Amit Varma]: victimhood. And it could be argued that this, you know, it's important to acknowledge all aspects

02:32:59.200 --> 02:33:04.480
[Amit Varma]: of one's identity, it's important to acknowledge all aspects of oppression, but it becomes

02:33:04.480 --> 02:33:10.960
[Amit Varma]: reductionist. If you define yourself only by this, it's almost like the language of class warfare

02:33:10.960 --> 02:33:17.760
[Amit Varma]: in that happens in all of this. And according to Pinker, this is why a lot of people who would

02:33:17.760 --> 02:33:23.040
[Amit Varma]: otherwise agree with all feminist aims in terms of you know, treating people equally and all that

02:33:23.040 --> 02:33:28.720
[Amit Varma]: vehemently dispute that they're feminist, like he points to a 1997 study when 70% of women

02:33:28.720 --> 02:33:33.200
[Amit Varma]: surveyed in the US said they're not feminist. And even in India, you'll hear that kind of nonsense

02:33:33.200 --> 02:33:38.240
[Amit Varma]: from random film stars and all will say that, oh, I'm not a feminist, you know, as a feminist is a

02:33:38.240 --> 02:33:43.600
[Amit Varma]: bad word or a dirty word, where I would imagine from the way that I am looking at it as you know,

02:33:43.600 --> 02:33:48.640
[Amit Varma]: as an equity feminist as someone who's come from that whole wall stone craft and lock kind of

02:33:48.640 --> 02:33:53.360
[Amit Varma]: thinking that every decent human being is by default a feminist otherwise, you know, but

02:33:53.360 --> 02:33:58.000
[Amit Varma]: what's your kind of take on this, because we see some of these battles and some of these

02:33:58.000 --> 02:34:02.880
[Amit Varma]: fissures play out even here. And I'd argue that in an Indian context, it doesn't really matter,

02:34:02.880 --> 02:34:07.440
[Amit Varma]: because things are just so horrendously bad in terms of equal treatment that, you know,

02:34:07.440 --> 02:34:13.040
[Amit Varma]: that these are battles that you know, one can fight at a later point in time. But what's what's

02:34:13.040 --> 02:34:13.840
[Amit Varma]: your sense of this?

02:34:15.680 --> 02:34:21.680
[Guest]: So see, my sense on this has actually changed in past seven, eight years or so maybe decade or so,

02:34:22.320 --> 02:34:26.720
[Guest]: because I did used to, you know, earlier my answer to people who said that are feminist,

02:34:26.720 --> 02:34:30.960
[Guest]: you know, I'm not a feminist would be to say no, you know, recognize that you actually are

02:34:30.960 --> 02:34:35.840
[Guest]: because you stand for this value, that value. But I later realized that actually, I take it

02:34:35.840 --> 02:34:39.760
[Guest]: far more seriously now when someone says they're not feminist, because I genuinely think that

02:34:39.760 --> 02:34:44.960
[Guest]: they're not feminist, because I realized that they're not, you know, even on and this goes,

02:34:44.960 --> 02:34:49.840
[Guest]: I mean, across ideologies, okay, so even I find people on the left also may define themselves as

02:34:50.400 --> 02:34:54.720
[Guest]: not feminist. Okay, so I realized that they are not feminist. And that's not good.

02:34:54.720 --> 02:35:01.680
[Guest]: Because in my book, somebody, again, you know, because I am Marxist in method. And for me,

02:35:01.680 --> 02:35:07.840
[Guest]: I wouldn't be a I don't think anybody can be a Marxist in that sense, if they're not feminist,

02:35:07.840 --> 02:35:14.800
[Guest]: you know, sorry, they're not okay. So you're not because you are, your anti feminism is such that

02:35:14.800 --> 02:35:20.560
[Guest]: you are, you're able to say I'm not a feminist, because you are somehow operating under that same

02:35:20.560 --> 02:35:28.960
[Guest]: liberal idea that there is a category of human, and you're standing for all human rights,

02:35:28.960 --> 02:35:35.200
[Guest]: and women are part of that human. So you are not recognizing that the whole problem is what

02:35:35.200 --> 02:35:40.080
[Guest]: Wollstonecraft was talking about, which is that the category of human is excluding women,

02:35:40.080 --> 02:35:46.080
[Guest]: it's treating women differently right now. So you're just saying that, oh, I'm standing for

02:35:46.080 --> 02:35:52.880
[Guest]: all human beings is not good enough, because you are not recognizing the many ways. And the ways in

02:35:52.880 --> 02:35:56.960
[Guest]: which that discrimination operates is, you know, the both the kinds of categories you described,

02:35:56.960 --> 02:36:02.080
[Guest]: right. So the idea is, it's, I don't really see a dichotomy there, because I think that,

02:36:02.640 --> 02:36:07.840
[Guest]: you know, the social, the psychological, the, you know, even the definition of, you know,

02:36:07.840 --> 02:36:16.560
[Guest]: even your basic biological functions, every sphere of anybody who occupies positions that are not,

02:36:17.120 --> 02:36:22.560
[Guest]: you know, heterosexual, male, upper caste, whatever, is something which is, you know,

02:36:22.560 --> 02:36:28.640
[Guest]: they are having, they cannot take the selfhood for granted at any point. So the point is that you are

02:36:28.640 --> 02:36:34.320
[Guest]: then having to recognize that this world is not all right. And if you don't recognize that, and

02:36:34.320 --> 02:36:38.480
[Guest]: if you're not specifically fighting, you know, supporting the fights, and there's going to be

02:36:38.480 --> 02:36:42.080
[Guest]: fights, you know, call them class war, call them what war, they're going to be fights, they're

02:36:42.080 --> 02:36:51.680
[Guest]: going to be acrimonious battles, okay. You cannot do feminism without disturbing the idea of

02:36:51.680 --> 02:36:59.440
[Guest]: a happy family. You're never going to be able to do it, sorry. You know, even I, okay, who come

02:36:59.440 --> 02:37:06.160
[Guest]: from such a supportive family and all of that, I cannot say that there has been no friction at all.

02:37:06.160 --> 02:37:10.160
[Guest]: Of course there will be, because the whole structure that doesn't mean about, it's not

02:37:10.160 --> 02:37:14.800
[Guest]: just about those individuals. The problem is that the family situation is structured such

02:37:15.360 --> 02:37:19.680
[Guest]: that your labor is expected. I mean, Marx's daughter went through this,

02:37:19.680 --> 02:37:25.600
[Guest]: not because her father was a patriarch towards her, but because he was an old man who was ailing

02:37:25.600 --> 02:37:30.560
[Guest]: and she was the youngest daughter. She was extremely active. She was the one who was unmarried.

02:37:30.560 --> 02:37:36.560
[Guest]: And she realized that she had to, at some point, choose between being around to help her father

02:37:36.560 --> 02:37:42.560
[Guest]: and between, you know, pursuing her life as an activist, because there was no way to, because

02:37:42.560 --> 02:37:47.360
[Guest]: your social structures don't offer that kind of support structure to allow women to be free of

02:37:47.360 --> 02:37:54.480
[Guest]: this caring, caregiving role. So she went through a lot of distress and I identify with that distress

02:37:54.480 --> 02:37:59.360
[Guest]: so much because I don't think there's any woman who doesn't go through that. Okay. So my point is

02:37:59.360 --> 02:38:03.760
[Guest]: that I think that, so if you're not a feminist, I take it very seriously. I say, yes, you're not

02:38:03.760 --> 02:38:08.400
[Guest]: a feminist because you're not thinking in a feminist way about the social problem. You think

02:38:08.400 --> 02:38:14.080
[Guest]: you're for equality, but you're not. You're actually ending up working against everybody's

02:38:14.080 --> 02:38:20.640
[Guest]: rights because, so, and I'll give you an example, which is a more of a very bold example. I don't

02:38:20.640 --> 02:38:27.200
[Guest]: know if it's the best example, but say, you know, somebody like a liberal person who enjoys a lot

02:38:27.200 --> 02:38:32.720
[Guest]: of influence, someone like say, Dhruv Rathee. Okay. So if he says that Black Lives Matter should

02:38:32.720 --> 02:38:37.600
[Guest]: call itself All Lives Matter, or that feminism should call itself humanism, it has a branding

02:38:37.600 --> 02:38:43.200
[Guest]: problem. You know, the point is that that is wrong, right? He's putting it very boldly,

02:38:43.200 --> 02:38:49.280
[Guest]: but my assumption is now, my tendency is that when someone says they're not feminist,

02:38:49.280 --> 02:38:54.400
[Guest]: to assume that at best, that's what they mean. And at worst, what they mean is that they're

02:38:54.400 --> 02:39:00.080
[Guest]: really okay with the way things are. They really think that they want, what they're saying when

02:39:00.080 --> 02:39:06.480
[Guest]: they say, I'm not feminist is to say, I don't want to be this fighting person. I don't want

02:39:06.480 --> 02:39:15.040
[Guest]: to be perceived as someone who is negative, someone who is opposing a situation where women

02:39:15.040 --> 02:39:22.080
[Guest]: are expected to behave in a particular way. Then you're not feminist, because being feminist and

02:39:22.080 --> 02:39:28.320
[Guest]: being part of a feminist movement, you're going to be, you know, challenging expectations,

02:39:28.320 --> 02:39:33.920
[Guest]: you're going to be prodding on toes, no matter how decent and persuasive you are, somebody is

02:39:33.920 --> 02:39:38.960
[Guest]: going to say about you that you're a shrill fighter, okay, or you're bossy or dominating

02:39:38.960 --> 02:39:44.000
[Guest]: or whatever it is, okay, happens all the time. You know, I have learned with years and years

02:39:44.000 --> 02:39:48.240
[Guest]: and years to, you know, I've become more and more and more persuasive, more and more and more

02:39:48.240 --> 02:39:55.200
[Guest]: patient in my way of responding to questions, which may, you know, seem banal or whatever it

02:39:55.200 --> 02:40:01.200
[Guest]: is, I'm very, very patient, largely, okay, largely I am. The point is, I realized that no matter how

02:40:01.200 --> 02:40:06.800
[Guest]: patient I am, if you ask someone who is observing, what do you think of this person? What do you

02:40:06.800 --> 02:40:11.840
[Guest]: think of Kavita? They're going to say, oh, she's the scary feminist. They're going to say that

02:40:11.840 --> 02:40:19.440
[Guest]: because you are challenging something so central to their understanding of the world,

02:40:19.440 --> 02:40:28.000
[Guest]: that it is damn scary. So, you know, I don't see any way to sweeten that pill, you know.

02:40:28.000 --> 02:40:33.040
[Amit Varma]: No, I do think that many people who say they are feminist or not feminist,

02:40:33.040 --> 02:40:36.560
[Amit Varma]: but what you're saying that if they say they're not feminist, I take them at face value is

02:40:36.560 --> 02:40:41.120
[Amit Varma]: interesting, because my sort of response was that maybe you're not, but maybe you are, maybe you're

02:40:41.120 --> 02:40:45.360
[Amit Varma]: just defining it kind of differently. And I think there's a little bit of a dichotomy, I'll tell you

02:40:45.360 --> 02:40:50.560
[Amit Varma]: what the dichotomy is, in the sense that, you know, a lot of people like myself would consider

02:40:50.560 --> 02:40:55.040
[Amit Varma]: their feminism to be rooted in individual rights, every individual should be treated with the same

02:40:55.040 --> 02:40:59.680
[Amit Varma]: amount of dignity and be given, you know, have the same amount of agency and autonomy and all

02:40:59.680 --> 02:41:04.720
[Amit Varma]: of that. And it's important to recognize in all of this, of course, that certain groups of people

02:41:04.720 --> 02:41:09.280
[Amit Varma]: over time historically have oppressed other groups of people. But when you actually start

02:41:09.280 --> 02:41:13.760
[Amit Varma]: thinking at the individual level of how you approach it, I think there's a danger of heading

02:41:13.760 --> 02:41:18.240
[Amit Varma]: down a slippery slope if like if you say that I'm an individual and I demand equal treatment,

02:41:18.240 --> 02:41:22.560
[Amit Varma]: that's great. If you say that I'm a woman and I demand equal treatment, that's great. But if you

02:41:22.560 --> 02:41:28.320
[Amit Varma]: say I'm a woman, men have always oppressed women, therefore men are the enemy. And this can go down

02:41:28.320 --> 02:41:32.480
[Amit Varma]: a slippery slope, you know, back in the day, you'll remember that there used to be the saying

02:41:32.480 --> 02:41:36.720
[Amit Varma]: that some feminists and I'd call them the scary feminists would say things like all intercourse

02:41:36.720 --> 02:41:42.880
[Amit Varma]: is rape. Right. And this is the image that a lot of people have of feminism, this extreme thing

02:41:42.880 --> 02:41:48.720
[Amit Varma]: where everybody is your enemy. And and I think the danger with, you know, at the level of

02:41:48.720 --> 02:41:53.680
[Amit Varma]: description, at the level of analysis, it makes sense to talk about oppression and,

02:41:53.680 --> 02:41:58.320
[Amit Varma]: you know, to think in terms of groups and all that. But if we have to come out of it to perpetuate

02:41:58.320 --> 02:42:03.360
[Amit Varma]: this sort of group violence, in the way that we think, I think that, you know,

02:42:03.360 --> 02:42:07.280
[Amit Varma]: these are two different things. And I can see where, you know, the fault lines lie.

02:42:08.960 --> 02:42:14.800
[Guest]: Yeah, I mean, certainly, I would not endorse much of an idea about, you know, groups in that sense.

02:42:14.800 --> 02:42:20.400
[Guest]: OK, but I'm talking about, I think, you know, understanding not so much oppression as privilege.

02:42:20.400 --> 02:42:25.600
[Guest]: Right. So see, oppression has happened and men, too, are oppressed by patriarchy. OK,

02:42:25.600 --> 02:42:32.320
[Guest]: women more so, of course. But yeah, a lot of men. OK, so I think that I truly believe that for a

02:42:32.320 --> 02:42:38.480
[Guest]: true liberation of the of human society, you know, a feminist liberation is a central part of that

02:42:38.480 --> 02:42:43.680
[Guest]: for everybody. It's not just for women to be free of men. It's about men. It's about men and women

02:42:43.680 --> 02:42:49.040
[Guest]: to be free of patriarchy, of everybody, of every gender, every sexual orientation, to be free of

02:42:49.040 --> 02:42:54.720
[Guest]: this disgusting patriarchy that has actually stifled us, that has, you know, that binds us,

02:42:54.720 --> 02:43:01.840
[Guest]: that chokes off our potential and forces us to act in ways which are so horrible to other people

02:43:01.840 --> 02:43:08.800
[Guest]: also. Right. So there's that. But also, I'd say that, let me put it this way, instead of gender,

02:43:08.800 --> 02:43:13.040
[Guest]: if you talk about caste for one second, OK, because reservation is, again, something which,

02:43:13.040 --> 02:43:18.560
[Guest]: and I think caste and gender overlap there. So the idea that the minute you think as an individual,

02:43:19.200 --> 02:43:25.120
[Guest]: you can, you know, you may say, yes, every individual deserves equal opportunity and equal

02:43:25.120 --> 02:43:32.240
[Guest]: access. But the minute you talk about reservations, an upper caste person may feel, they do often

02:43:32.240 --> 02:43:39.200
[Guest]: feel, that I, as an individual, am being discriminated against by that individual who

02:43:39.200 --> 02:43:45.520
[Guest]: is enjoying reservation because he's got less number than me and he's getting in and I'm not.

02:43:45.520 --> 02:43:52.560
[Guest]: Right. So how do you change the way of looking at that situation? Because if you look at the

02:43:52.560 --> 02:43:57.280
[Guest]: situation only in those limits, yes, that's true. Right. You look at it just in this frame. If you

02:43:57.280 --> 02:44:02.720
[Guest]: don't look what is happening outside that narrow frame that you've drawn, then yes, here you are,

02:44:02.720 --> 02:44:10.400
[Guest]: both of you standing there, you with two marks more, this person with two marks less, that guy

02:44:10.400 --> 02:44:16.240
[Guest]: is getting in, you are not. And there's a limited number of seats and you deserve it and somebody

02:44:16.240 --> 02:44:22.640
[Guest]: else is getting it. Right. Now, my approach there is that where any inequality is concerned,

02:44:22.640 --> 02:44:28.320
[Guest]: if you just broaden the frame a little bit more and you first understand that there are several

02:44:28.320 --> 02:44:35.440
[Guest]: problems happening here. One of the problems is that historically and even today in society,

02:44:36.080 --> 02:44:43.600
[Guest]: that person is facing a kind of discrimination and reservation cannot address economic disparity.

02:44:43.600 --> 02:44:51.200
[Guest]: But it does address or eliminate, to some extent, at the point of admission, it eliminates social

02:44:51.200 --> 02:44:58.560
[Guest]: prejudice. So somebody who was going in for an interview, who realizes that they know that your,

02:44:59.440 --> 02:45:06.000
[Guest]: maybe your surname, maybe your way of speaking a language, so many things indicate in India,

02:45:06.000 --> 02:45:10.880
[Guest]: people can tell your caste from, you know, osmosis, okay, they know that immediately.

02:45:11.440 --> 02:45:15.840
[Guest]: You're sending those signals, they get those signals. And then they, you know, there's

02:45:15.840 --> 02:45:20.000
[Guest]: prejudice in the mind. And we know this from studies, right? We know this even in studies

02:45:20.000 --> 02:45:23.920
[Guest]: in the West, where people have done it for gender, where people have written the exact

02:45:23.920 --> 02:45:27.600
[Guest]: same word for word application, one in a man's name, one in a woman's name and sent it to an

02:45:27.600 --> 02:45:32.960
[Guest]: employer and the employers pick the man, right? So we know that this is maybe, it may be unconscious,

02:45:32.960 --> 02:45:38.640
[Guest]: but it's operating. How do you address that? Then you need something to say that in order to get

02:45:38.640 --> 02:45:44.320
[Guest]: rid of that bias there, that bias is not something the upper caste person is feeling. The bias is

02:45:44.320 --> 02:45:50.960
[Guest]: something that Dalit person or the OBC person is feeling. A. B, the other thing is that,

02:45:51.600 --> 02:45:57.600
[Guest]: oh, but don't I deserve to get a seat? Don't I deserve? Yes, you do. But the answer to that is

02:45:57.600 --> 02:46:02.480
[Guest]: not to say that that person is depriving you of your seat, but to say that why aren't there

02:46:02.480 --> 02:46:08.000
[Guest]: enough seats for everybody? You know, if so many people want to be doctors or engineers,

02:46:08.640 --> 02:46:13.760
[Guest]: why on earth would you have only so many seats? Why can't you, can't this country do with more

02:46:13.760 --> 02:46:19.280
[Guest]: doctors? Look at it now. It's not like you have enough doctors in this country. You need far more

02:46:19.280 --> 02:46:24.160
[Guest]: doctors. What's your problem? You know, you create, why can't you prioritize education so that people

02:46:24.160 --> 02:46:30.640
[Guest]: get, everybody gets admission. And the notion that reservation results in less quality is complete

02:46:30.640 --> 02:46:35.600
[Guest]: nonsense. Two quick answers to that, where gender caste, no matter what you see, the point is that

02:46:35.600 --> 02:46:40.160
[Guest]: you find, you know, medical system in Tamil Nadu, for instance, being one of the best in the country

02:46:40.160 --> 02:46:46.400
[Guest]: where they have the most reservation. The point is that, that, and the point is the looseness is

02:46:46.400 --> 02:46:51.120
[Guest]: at the point of entry. At the point of exit, everybody gives the same exam and passes the

02:46:51.120 --> 02:46:58.240
[Guest]: same exam, right? So that, in my sense, even when it comes to feminism, is my approach, which is

02:46:58.240 --> 02:47:04.240
[Guest]: that if you think only as an individual and only in a very narrow framework, then you're getting

02:47:04.240 --> 02:47:08.000
[Guest]: it wrong somewhere. You're getting, you're going to get your answers wrong because you're framing

02:47:08.000 --> 02:47:13.920
[Guest]: your questions too narrowly. And in the same regard, I'd say, and we can talk more about that,

02:47:13.920 --> 02:47:19.360
[Guest]: but I'll just put in that one sentence here, is that as a feminist, I think that those who think

02:47:19.360 --> 02:47:25.520
[Guest]: in terms of individuals alone tend to get, you know, you, you get with an idea of a liberal

02:47:25.520 --> 02:47:32.560
[Guest]: feminism, which sometimes gets it very wrong when it comes to understanding larger social

02:47:32.560 --> 02:47:38.560
[Guest]: structures and processes. So I have many examples of that, and we can talk about that. But yeah.

02:47:39.760 --> 02:47:44.240
[Amit Varma]: Yeah, no, I, as I said, at the level of analysis, I think we have to look at groups, we have to look

02:47:44.240 --> 02:47:50.320
[Amit Varma]: at all these patterns of oppression and all, you know, everything that is structurally wrong. But

02:47:50.320 --> 02:47:54.000
[Amit Varma]: you know, when you're moving ahead, I think if you think only in terms of groups, it's a bit of

02:47:54.000 --> 02:47:58.080
[Amit Varma]: an issue. You know, I asked you about feminism, you went into caste, it was almost like looking

02:47:58.080 --> 02:48:02.800
[Amit Varma]: London talking Tokyo. But I, but I love the fact that, you know, the question that the person

02:48:02.800 --> 02:48:07.440
[Amit Varma]: complaining about reservation should ask is why aren't there more seats, which I completely agree

02:48:07.440 --> 02:48:12.080
[Guest]: with. Reservations are, in fact, a feminist tool, not just where women are concerned, I actually

02:48:12.080 --> 02:48:17.440
[Guest]: think so, because I can see so many women having benefited from caste based reservations, they are

02:48:17.440 --> 02:48:20.960
[Guest]: in college and university today, because there's caste based reservation, and they would not be

02:48:20.960 --> 02:48:26.240
[Guest]: here otherwise, you know, and that's why, you know, for me, actually, I don't make that distinction

02:48:26.240 --> 02:48:31.440
[Guest]: for me in India, especially, caste and gender are absolutely, they're in bed with each other,

02:48:31.440 --> 02:48:38.160
[Amit Varma]: they're totally embedded. Yeah, totally. Yeah. Great. So let's move on from here. And I like I

02:48:38.160 --> 02:48:42.960
[Amit Varma]: have a bunch of general questions about, you know, broader questions about the state of women in

02:48:42.960 --> 02:48:48.880
[Amit Varma]: India. But before we get there, I was sort of struck by the beautiful way in which in your

02:48:48.880 --> 02:48:53.760
[Amit Varma]: opening few chapters of fearless freedom, you've kind of laid it all out and summed it all out.

02:48:53.760 --> 02:48:59.840
[Amit Varma]: And one of the first sort of fundamental things that you speak about is this mindset,

02:48:59.840 --> 02:49:05.120
[Amit Varma]: which creates a dichotomy between safety and freedom. So, you know, which seems really

02:49:05.120 --> 02:49:09.920
[Amit Varma]: fundamental, and which is kind of all around us. And tell me a little bit about that.

02:49:11.120 --> 02:49:16.400
[Guest]: Yeah, Amit, I just wanted to ask you before we go there, my brain is still stuck in your

02:49:16.400 --> 02:49:21.120
[Guest]: previous question a little bit, in the sense that one part of it I sort of, you know, when it comes

02:49:21.120 --> 02:49:26.800
[Guest]: to, you know, liberal, the idea of the liberal individual based feminism, vis-a-vis these,

02:49:26.800 --> 02:49:31.200
[Guest]: so if I just can have, you know, if I can just please, please go ahead. So I just wanted to say

02:49:31.200 --> 02:49:37.680
[Guest]: that, for instance, today in the world, there's this whole idea about the lean in feminism,

02:49:37.680 --> 02:49:45.120
[Guest]: and, you know, CEOs writing about breaking the glass ceiling and all of that. And the idea of

02:49:45.120 --> 02:49:50.320
[Guest]: feminism as being individual achievement, okay, so an individual woman who has broken the glass

02:49:50.320 --> 02:49:57.360
[Guest]: ceiling, right. And I'm extremely uneasy with that, because I feel that that's exactly where,

02:49:57.360 --> 02:50:03.840
[Guest]: that's where I think my Marxism comes in, okay, because, to me, that is the main, to me, the idea,

02:50:03.840 --> 02:50:08.960
[Guest]: you know, of Marxism is not, it's not a Marxism that is not feminist, it has to be feminist.

02:50:08.960 --> 02:50:14.240
[Guest]: The point is, it has to be a feminism that actually thinks about feminism for most women,

02:50:14.240 --> 02:50:20.480
[Guest]: for all women. And there, if it becomes something which is about individual achievement alone,

02:50:20.480 --> 02:50:27.040
[Guest]: what it ends up doing is that it often pits women against each other. And it often means that a

02:50:27.040 --> 02:50:33.600
[Guest]: privileged woman is actually gaining her breaking of the glass ceiling at the cost of other women

02:50:33.600 --> 02:50:40.480
[Guest]: who are actually, you know, in the very powerful image of a friend of mine who's written a book

02:50:40.480 --> 02:50:45.280
[Guest]: called Feminism for the 99%. She says, you know, somebody breaks the glass ceiling up there,

02:50:45.280 --> 02:50:51.440
[Guest]: who's cleaning the shards of the ground, okay. Suppose it's some cleaning worker, woman,

02:50:51.440 --> 02:50:56.080
[Guest]: presumably from some oppressed race, and so on, who's actually doing that. So where's the

02:50:56.080 --> 02:51:01.760
[Guest]: feminism for everybody, you know, so where is the idea that everyone's going to get to play

02:51:01.760 --> 02:51:08.240
[Guest]: on that field. And that can't come only by looking at the category as individuals. I agree with you

02:51:08.240 --> 02:51:13.520
[Guest]: entirely. That's not just about women versus men. Okay. In fact, I am uncomfortable now,

02:51:13.520 --> 02:51:18.320
[Guest]: even with the idea of saying just intersectionality, because intersectionality implies that

02:51:18.320 --> 02:51:26.000
[Guest]: there are these different roads, which are intersecting, right. But that's not how reality is,

02:51:26.000 --> 02:51:31.520
[Guest]: right. Suppose, you know, if I think of someone, somebody who's a lesbian and a Dalit and a worker

02:51:31.520 --> 02:51:40.080
[Guest]: and doing an extremely dangerous and menial job, okay. So, it's not just that caste, gender,

02:51:40.080 --> 02:51:47.600
[Guest]: class are all intersecting in her. She is this whole person, no, in which all these things are

02:51:47.600 --> 02:51:53.840
[Guest]: expressing themselves integrally as one, right. So you have to find a way to address all of this

02:51:53.840 --> 02:52:01.440
[Guest]: together. And so the system also is not patriarchy is not separate from the way in which our society

02:52:01.440 --> 02:52:08.000
[Guest]: is economically arranged. It is not separate from caste, it is not separate from, it's all,

02:52:08.000 --> 02:52:14.240
[Guest]: it's working together. And it's not, it's not just intersecting. It's all part of one system.

02:52:14.240 --> 02:52:19.280
[Guest]: It's not several systems that are intersecting. Let me put it that way. So when I look at it whole,

02:52:19.280 --> 02:52:24.080
[Guest]: and I want to find a way of fighting it whole while recognizing that there are all these

02:52:24.080 --> 02:52:31.760
[Guest]: different things happening, that's where I find that I find it more useful to think in terms of a,

02:52:31.760 --> 02:52:37.280
[Guest]: you know, I find Marxist methods useful there, because they allow me to address a variety of

02:52:37.280 --> 02:52:43.360
[Guest]: questions of oppression. While knowing that I want this whole system to change, I don't want

02:52:43.360 --> 02:52:49.120
[Guest]: to just tinker with this bit of it or that bit of it. So I don't, I'm not happy enough just saying,

02:52:49.120 --> 02:52:54.880
[Guest]: okay, I want this bit to change or that bit to change. So I'm recognizing that, you know, there

02:52:54.880 --> 02:53:02.160
[Guest]: may be disagreements about what you want in terms of the systemic change. But surely, you would

02:53:02.160 --> 02:53:10.960
[Guest]: agree or anybody who is, you know, invested in an egalitarian society would agree that just someone

02:53:10.960 --> 02:53:18.080
[Guest]: woman becoming a CEO or having more women CEOs is not going to ensure that you're going to have

02:53:18.080 --> 02:53:24.400
[Guest]: enough women, the large, vast majority of women actually living their lives with dignity. So for

02:53:24.400 --> 02:53:29.360
[Guest]: me, the thing to pursue would be, where is the collective childcare? Where is the, you know,

02:53:29.360 --> 02:53:35.680
[Guest]: where is better wages for everybody? Instead of privatizing everything? Why can't there be more

02:53:35.680 --> 02:53:41.600
[Guest]: access to socialized healthcare, you know, and, and you'll notice that even capitalist societies

02:53:41.600 --> 02:53:49.920
[Guest]: now are where the idea of socialism was taboo, are today beginning to talk about that now in America,

02:53:49.920 --> 02:53:54.800
[Guest]: it is no longer taboo. You know, you're having up and coming politicians speaking in these terms

02:53:54.800 --> 02:54:01.120
[Guest]: now, I think, because, you know, there's no way to really look away from that. So I'm not saying

02:54:01.120 --> 02:54:07.920
[Guest]: we repeat mistakes. I'm, as I told you earlier, I'm deeply, deeply suspicious of authoritarianism

02:54:07.920 --> 02:54:14.560
[Guest]: and cults. And I think that the left in its historical journey has a lot to answer for,

02:54:14.560 --> 02:54:19.680
[Guest]: because if they have become synonymous with authoritarianism and cults, it's not only because

02:54:19.680 --> 02:54:23.920
[Guest]: of bourgeois propaganda. It's also because of what has happened in the real Soviet Union,

02:54:23.920 --> 02:54:29.520
[Guest]: what's happening now in China. You know, it's very real. Even what has happened in Cuba, where

02:54:29.520 --> 02:54:36.160
[Guest]: a lot of very good things managed to survive. But one can't deny that there's, there was also this

02:54:36.160 --> 02:54:41.840
[Guest]: whole thing of the sense of a cult and the sense of authoritarianism. Galeano has a beautiful

02:54:41.840 --> 02:54:47.840
[Guest]: quotation about Fidel Castro that expresses this, this dichotomy there. But that's another thing.

02:54:47.840 --> 02:54:53.760
[Guest]: But I'm saying that acknowledging all of that, that explains why I'm still invested in the idea

02:54:53.760 --> 02:55:01.920
[Guest]: of a transformation. My feminism is, my feminist impulse and the work we do, work I do, comes from

02:55:01.920 --> 02:55:07.760
[Guest]: that sense of, you know, wanting to work for a collective transformation. Yeah, no matter what,

02:55:07.760 --> 02:55:10.880
[Guest]: you know, who knows when we'll see that happen. But yeah.

02:55:13.360 --> 02:55:17.360
[Amit Varma]: No, thank you for that nuance. That's a lot of nuance and a lot for me to think about when I,

02:55:17.360 --> 02:55:21.920
[Amit Varma]: you know, replay this episode a few times, hopefully and take notes. And I'm really glad

02:55:21.920 --> 02:55:26.640
[Amit Varma]: that this is the point of the show where you actually spoke about against the authoritarian

02:55:26.640 --> 02:55:30.880
[Amit Varma]: left because see, none of them is going to listen to this part. They would have reached your cat mom

02:55:30.880 --> 02:55:34.640
[Amit Varma]: part and they would have said Arni sunna. So you are kind of safe. They're not going to

02:55:35.200 --> 02:55:42.080
[Amit Varma]: lash out on Twitter at this anyway. So kind of moving on. And in fact, even before my freedom

02:55:42.080 --> 02:55:48.240
[Amit Varma]: versus safety question, I mean, part of why that begins, your book also seemed to me to be pertinent

02:55:48.240 --> 02:55:53.920
[Amit Varma]: to the germination of the book itself. Like it was, you know, in the anti-rape protests of 2012

02:55:53.920 --> 02:55:58.720
[Amit Varma]: and all of that, where it kind of germinated, you used that phrase and that very memorable speech

02:55:58.720 --> 02:56:03.280
[Amit Varma]: that you gave, which I'll of course link from the show notes and went viral for a reason. Why can't

02:56:03.280 --> 02:56:09.280
[Amit Varma]: things like that go viral viral instead of bloody viruses? So tell me, tell me a bit about the

02:56:09.280 --> 02:56:13.440
[Amit Varma]: germination of the book and then how you started conceptualizing it because this is all stuff,

02:56:13.440 --> 02:56:18.880
[Amit Varma]: you know, okay, India is a deep, deep mess in a million different ways. How do you give it structure

02:56:18.880 --> 02:56:26.000
[Guest]: in a book when you start thinking about it? So actually, it didn't start out as me thinking

02:56:26.000 --> 02:56:30.880
[Guest]: about a book at all. In fact, the book thing happened only because these couple of young

02:56:30.880 --> 02:56:37.360
[Guest]: women from Penguin reached out to me and said, we want you to write. And I said, you know, the only

02:56:37.360 --> 02:56:42.240
[Guest]: thing which I've been thinking about systematically for some years now has been exactly this issue.

02:56:42.800 --> 02:56:47.920
[Guest]: So well, if I write at all, then I can write about that, you know, that's all. But when it started

02:56:47.920 --> 02:56:52.800
[Guest]: was I remember exactly when I started thinking on these lines that I remember very clearly.

02:56:52.800 --> 02:56:58.240
[Guest]: The thing is that for some years, I had been a little uneasy with our own movements against

02:56:58.240 --> 02:57:04.800
[Guest]: sexual violence, because I felt that we were appealing to a sense of community outrage,

02:57:05.360 --> 02:57:12.320
[Guest]: assuming it was there, and finding it very easily, a little too easily. As I said, I'm always on the

02:57:12.320 --> 02:57:18.560
[Guest]: lookout for how can I invite discomfort into our zones. For me, feminism and all my activism is

02:57:18.560 --> 02:57:24.480
[Guest]: about, and I think the only useful activism is when you're continuously inviting discomfort into

02:57:24.480 --> 02:57:30.160
[Guest]: your own zone, you know, rather than just sitting in judgment on someone else far away. So what was

02:57:30.160 --> 02:57:33.920
[Guest]: happening was we would have these anti-rape protests and all of that, and they would happen,

02:57:33.920 --> 02:57:39.840
[Guest]: everybody is saying, and a lot of it would be saying, fasi do, you know, because that is very

02:57:39.840 --> 02:57:45.520
[Guest]: easily it comes to mind. And my own organization used to demand that and all of that. It's deeply

02:57:45.520 --> 02:57:50.320
[Guest]: uneasy with all of that. So I would keep arguing that, look, that is not okay, because you're

02:57:50.320 --> 02:57:55.360
[Guest]: giving the power to the state. And why the hell should the state have that power? And what are we

02:57:55.360 --> 02:58:02.160
[Guest]: talking about to kill someone? And how does it at all help us? Because it's so easy for the ruler

02:58:02.160 --> 02:58:08.080
[Guest]: also to say, ha ha ha, fasi do, fasi do, because what does it cost them? Doesn't cost them a damn

02:58:08.080 --> 02:58:13.920
[Guest]: thing. Whereas actually the things you need to prevent and prevent sexual violence or other

02:58:13.920 --> 02:58:19.760
[Guest]: forms of gender-based violence to give justice and to create spaces where women can be free of

02:58:19.760 --> 02:58:24.880
[Guest]: this violence, that stuff, these guys are not doing, governments are not doing. It's all too

02:58:24.880 --> 02:58:29.120
[Guest]: easy for them to periodically hang somebody. Doesn't make a difference. That one thing.

02:58:29.120 --> 02:58:34.240
[Guest]: The other thing was that, as I said, the slogans, other slogans also, they would all be,

02:58:34.960 --> 02:58:42.000
[Guest]: they're all raised in a way which were not creating discomfort to anybody raising them

02:58:42.000 --> 02:58:48.960
[Guest]: and to anybody listening to them. And I would keep wondering uneasily, is that community really

02:58:48.960 --> 02:58:55.920
[Guest]: with us on this? Are they really with our feminist cause? Because the minute you talk about what is

02:58:55.920 --> 02:59:03.360
[Guest]: rape, you would realize that even among the women protesting this particular rape and among people

02:59:03.360 --> 02:59:08.080
[Guest]: in the larger society, definitely part of the same village, part of the same juggi, part of the same

02:59:08.080 --> 02:59:15.280
[Guest]: community, part of the same colony, the minute you actually talk about rape as it mostly happens,

02:59:15.280 --> 02:59:21.920
[Guest]: which is rape not, which is not stranger rape, which involves someone known to you, someone known

02:59:21.920 --> 02:59:28.560
[Guest]: to and generally loved, trusted, whatever. Most rapes are like that all over the world.

02:59:28.560 --> 02:59:34.320
[Guest]: But the most protests don't happen about rapes like that. As I said, not everything happens

02:59:34.320 --> 02:59:38.960
[Guest]: on social media, media and on the streets. So much of those things are not things anybody

02:59:38.960 --> 02:59:43.680
[Guest]: really wants to, no one wants to, even the victim won't want to go and do a protest about that

02:59:43.680 --> 02:59:48.160
[Guest]: easily. Because it involves a family member, it involves a guru, it involves a teacher,

02:59:48.160 --> 02:59:55.760
[Guest]: it involves whatever, not easy. When that comes up, then immediately all the other sexist tropes

02:59:55.760 --> 03:00:02.240
[Guest]: come into play. And most of all, what occurred to me is that in Indian society, when you talk,

03:00:02.240 --> 03:00:08.400
[Guest]: then the distinction between rape and consensual sexual relationship is,

03:00:10.000 --> 03:00:16.240
[Guest]: there isn't a line there at all. Most people use the same word when they, or the same concept,

03:00:16.240 --> 03:00:22.640
[Guest]: when they are talking about their daughter who has run away to marry somebody and someone they

03:00:22.640 --> 03:00:31.040
[Guest]: don't approve of, and when they are talking about rape. So they think, so the idea of consent is

03:00:31.040 --> 03:00:40.320
[Guest]: missing. So the idea of rape as a violation of a woman's consent is missing. And instead you have

03:00:40.320 --> 03:00:47.280
[Guest]: the idea of the violation of a woman as sexual property. So she is a virgin, the parents are

03:00:47.280 --> 03:00:52.240
[Guest]: supposed to hand her over, hold to some guy of the correct caste. And if she has been raped,

03:00:55.360 --> 03:01:00.080
[Guest]: it is the violation of the property of a future husband. And this is embedded in the law,

03:01:00.080 --> 03:01:06.480
[Guest]: by the way. This used to be embedded in the law. Okay, so in many ways, I mean, I don't remember

03:01:06.480 --> 03:01:11.120
[Guest]: if I can actually recall the details right now. But... Can I read out those sections?

03:01:11.120 --> 03:01:14.480
[Amit Varma]: Yeah, yeah, of course. Yeah, I've written about it in the past. And

03:01:14.480 --> 03:01:20.160
[Amit Varma]: just for the sake of my listeners, because I don't think many people realize how our laws have

03:01:20.160 --> 03:01:24.960
[Amit Varma]: actually embedded women being the property of men as such. Now, section 497 of the IPC,

03:01:24.960 --> 03:01:29.680
[Amit Varma]: which deals with adultery, which was struck down in 2018, which is pretty late. We dealt with it

03:01:29.680 --> 03:01:35.440
[Amit Varma]: for 71 years, that said, quote, whoever has sexual intercourse with a person who is and whom he knows

03:01:35.440 --> 03:01:41.040
[Amit Varma]: or has reason to believe to be the wife of another man, without the consent or connivence of that man,

03:01:41.040 --> 03:01:45.280
[Amit Varma]: such sexual intercourse not amounting to the offense of rape is guilty of the offense of

03:01:45.280 --> 03:01:49.520
[Amit Varma]: adultery and shall be punished with blah, blah, blah, blah, blah. And the point here is, of course,

03:01:49.520 --> 03:01:53.520
[Amit Varma]: he doesn't need the consent of the woman, he needs the consent of that man as if she's property.

03:01:53.520 --> 03:01:58.800
[Amit Varma]: And section 498 of the IPC, which is titled enticing or taking away or detaining with

03:01:58.800 --> 03:02:03.760
[Amit Varma]: criminal intent, a married woman, you know, thereby implying the possession of some other

03:02:03.760 --> 03:02:08.960
[Amit Varma]: man, this one reads, whoever takes or entices away any woman who is or whom he knows or has reason

03:02:08.960 --> 03:02:14.000
[Amit Varma]: to believe to be the wife of any other man from that man, or from that person having the care

03:02:14.000 --> 03:02:18.560
[Amit Varma]: of her on behalf of that man with intent that she may have illicit intercourse with any person,

03:02:18.560 --> 03:02:23.280
[Amit Varma]: or conceals or detains with that intent, any such woman shall be punished with imprisonment

03:02:23.280 --> 03:02:27.920
[Amit Varma]: of either description or blah, blah, blah, blah, blah. And of course, it's it's written almost as

03:02:27.920 --> 03:02:31.840
[Amit Varma]: if it is too obscure, which is why you know, if it was written in simple language, I think it would

03:02:31.840 --> 03:02:36.400
[Amit Varma]: create a little more outrage, hopefully. So yeah, I'm sorry to interrupt you. But

03:02:37.280 --> 03:02:41.040
[Guest]: I'm glad I wanted to remember exactly that adultery law. I couldn't remember the section

03:02:41.040 --> 03:02:46.160
[Guest]: and all of that. Yeah, absolutely. Right. Yeah. So that's where I began writing. Now I began

03:02:46.160 --> 03:02:52.880
[Guest]: writing about that actually somebody in a website called Sanhati. So they had asked me to write

03:02:52.880 --> 03:02:58.400
[Guest]: about sexual violence. So when I wrote about it, I started raising these questions about what

03:02:58.400 --> 03:03:05.920
[Guest]: slogan should we raise? What form should the protest take? So that you are actually conveying,

03:03:05.920 --> 03:03:11.360
[Guest]: you know, you are promoting an understanding of consent, and promoting an understanding of rape

03:03:11.360 --> 03:03:18.480
[Guest]: as a violation of consent, and therefore supporting a woman's consensual relationships also. So you

03:03:18.480 --> 03:03:23.680
[Guest]: are not just saying a no is a no, you're also saying a yes is a yes, you know. So women's

03:03:23.680 --> 03:03:28.400
[Guest]: respect a woman's yes and respect a woman's no, you know, both. So how are you going to say that?

03:03:28.400 --> 03:03:32.960
[Guest]: So I began writing about that. And one essay did was published by them on their website.

03:03:33.520 --> 03:03:40.160
[Guest]: So that had happened, I think, around 2011 or 12 only sometime. And in the course of several

03:03:40.160 --> 03:03:47.280
[Guest]: struggles in 2012, I began thinking about that and trying to suggest slogans or ways of addressing

03:03:47.280 --> 03:03:50.880
[Guest]: things that would actually bring this in. So I was just playing around with it and didn't really

03:03:52.560 --> 03:03:57.600
[Guest]: have a clear picture of how to go ahead, but would practically try, you know, that how do

03:03:57.600 --> 03:04:04.720
[Guest]: you get people. First, I would try to tell people kindly don't raise the faasi do slogan. So if

03:04:04.720 --> 03:04:08.800
[Guest]: others are raising faasi do, it's not that you tell them achha stop it. But it's more about what

03:04:08.800 --> 03:04:13.840
[Guest]: other slogans do you offer, which are more useful in talking about consent, right? But I hadn't

03:04:13.840 --> 03:04:20.000
[Guest]: really hit upon the best way to do it. And somehow society also wasn't tuned in. What I think is that

03:04:20.000 --> 03:04:28.000
[Guest]: in 2012, December, what happened was that suddenly a lot of people tuned in. And suddenly there was

03:04:28.000 --> 03:04:34.320
[Guest]: people listening to you actually listening. Okay, so men, women, a lot of people. And so when I

03:04:34.320 --> 03:04:40.240
[Guest]: spoke about this then, and I suddenly was able to explain this, I've been struggling with explaining

03:04:40.240 --> 03:04:44.880
[Guest]: this for a long while, but in that speech, it came out with a certain clarity. Because just before

03:04:44.880 --> 03:04:48.880
[Guest]: the speech, some journalist, young woman journalist had come and asked me that, look, people are

03:04:48.880 --> 03:04:55.840
[Guest]: saying, achha theek hai, raat ko na nikle mailaaye. Lekin agar kisi ko job hai, wo nurse hai, raat ko

03:04:55.840 --> 03:05:01.360
[Guest]: kaam karte hai, how can she not go out at night if she has a job at night? So something in me got,

03:05:01.360 --> 03:05:06.240
[Guest]: you know, sort of possessed with rage at that. Not at that person, not at the young woman there,

03:05:06.240 --> 03:05:13.280
[Guest]: but at the idea that why should somebody have to explain to themselves a victim or a potential

03:05:13.280 --> 03:05:19.200
[Guest]: victim? Why should she have to explain why she's out in the night? Okay, so then I spoke from that

03:05:19.200 --> 03:05:23.840
[Guest]: place saying that, look, in the name of safety, there's some problem with saying suraksha.

03:05:23.840 --> 03:05:30.480
[Guest]: Because what people understand by safety is, there's a code there. And the secret code is that

03:05:30.480 --> 03:05:36.560
[Guest]: all those codes for safety are for the women. They're not for male behavior, they're for female

03:05:36.560 --> 03:05:40.640
[Guest]: behavior. And it will be women who are asked to enforce all of this also. It'll be a hostel

03:05:40.640 --> 03:05:43.920
[Guest]: warden, it'll be your mother-in-law, it'll be your mother. It'll be these people who'll have

03:05:43.920 --> 03:05:49.120
[Guest]: to do the enforcing much of the time. But the point is that you are, you know, you're not,

03:05:49.120 --> 03:05:55.520
[Guest]: do we really want this? We want to be able to have an unconditional access to public spaces

03:05:55.520 --> 03:06:01.440
[Guest]: and unconditional safety in living our lives in private spaces also, without having to explain

03:06:01.440 --> 03:06:08.400
[Guest]: ourselves for everything. So, you know, we should ask for freedom, not for safety. So that is what

03:06:08.400 --> 03:06:13.920
[Guest]: I was going for, that basically the idea of, you know, keep me safe. And so, you know, oh yes,

03:06:13.920 --> 03:06:18.800
[Guest]: we'll keep you safe. So let's lock you up to keep you safe. No, you know, don't lock me up to keep

03:06:18.800 --> 03:06:24.720
[Guest]: me safe. Please do something that can safeguard my freedom instead. And I realized that because

03:06:24.720 --> 03:06:29.760
[Guest]: so many people had tuned in then the first minute, I had no idea. Okay. I was not on Facebook or

03:06:29.760 --> 03:06:34.880
[Guest]: maybe I was, I think I was, I'd been dragged there, but I was only like I am on Insta now. Okay. So I

03:06:34.880 --> 03:06:43.280
[Guest]: used to learn, yeah, basically it's cats and stuff. So, and I was not on Twitter. I had no clue what

03:06:43.280 --> 03:06:48.480
[Guest]: going viral meant. I only thought songs like Kolavari went viral. Viral means, I thought

03:06:48.480 --> 03:06:54.800
[Guest]: a song would go viral. And I always used to suspect that someone would promote it and make it viral.

03:06:54.800 --> 03:07:01.920
[Guest]: I never imagined that things would go viral. So I got a call suddenly from, and tell me if you

03:07:01.920 --> 03:07:05.760
[Amit Varma]: think I'm digressing too much or something, to just bring me back. Please digress, this is very

03:07:05.760 --> 03:07:11.200
[Guest]: much tough show for digressions. So I had gone back, you know, this was around the 19th of December,

03:07:11.200 --> 03:07:17.520
[Guest]: I think. So I went back to my office where I was working on my Liberation magazine. And the 20th

03:07:17.520 --> 03:07:24.320
[Guest]: and 21st, the weekend that was coming up, there was this huge gathering at India Gate. So, you know,

03:07:24.320 --> 03:07:29.600
[Guest]: so it was in the 21st and 22nd, I think. So I had a couple of days just before that. So I'm working

03:07:29.600 --> 03:07:34.400
[Guest]: on my computer and trying to finish because I wanted to be at India Gate when, you know, people

03:07:34.400 --> 03:07:41.200
[Guest]: were gathering. So the phone rang in the office and they connected it to my floor, not my mobile

03:07:41.200 --> 03:07:46.880
[Guest]: phone, so phone. So I picked up the landline. It was somebody from America somewhere, some Indian

03:07:46.880 --> 03:07:53.360
[Guest]: guy, who said, yeah, actually, we wanted to speak to you. So I said, okay, who is this and all of

03:07:53.360 --> 03:07:58.320
[Guest]: that. And so they said, no, we are looking for you because we wanted to speak to you about your

03:07:58.320 --> 03:08:03.520
[Guest]: speech that has gone viral. And I said, no, I think you have the wrong person. I have no idea,

03:08:03.520 --> 03:08:08.720
[Guest]: you know, who are you looking for exactly? What speech, what viral, no clue. Okay. So he said,

03:08:08.720 --> 03:08:14.080
[Guest]: you're Kavita Krishnan, no? So there's a speech of yours and it's got viral. So I'm like, what

03:08:14.080 --> 03:08:18.720
[Guest]: speech? And I have no clue. And I was a little impatient also because I was eager to get back

03:08:18.720 --> 03:08:25.760
[Guest]: to work. So he said, no, there's a speech, no, which is online on the rape movement. So I said,

03:08:25.760 --> 03:08:29.520
[Guest]: oh, I have no idea. Anyway, he wanted to talk to me. I talked to him about the movement and all of

03:08:29.520 --> 03:08:35.920
[Guest]: that and put the phone down. Then I wondered what is, so I started asking people in the office,

03:08:35.920 --> 03:08:44.320
[Guest]: nobody knew. Okay. Then I realized that I went to Facebook, okay, which I generally didn't access

03:08:44.320 --> 03:08:52.800
[Guest]: at all much. And I realized that Facebook inbox, when I went to messages from people I don't know,

03:08:52.800 --> 03:08:59.680
[Guest]: I just checked. So I suddenly realized that my Facebook inbox is full of messages, many of them

03:08:59.680 --> 03:09:05.200
[Guest]: from young women, most of them from young women who are saying that you gave the speech and we

03:09:05.200 --> 03:09:09.920
[Guest]: are so thankful to you for saying this, because we need to be hearing this. It's very affirming

03:09:09.920 --> 03:09:15.840
[Guest]: to be listening to the idea of freedom versus safety. And one overriding concern for a lot of

03:09:15.840 --> 03:09:21.760
[Guest]: them was that they were worried that the media attention around the rape in Delhi, and Delhi

03:09:21.760 --> 03:09:27.120
[Guest]: is being talked about as the capital and whatnot, meant that their parents were reluctant to send

03:09:27.120 --> 03:09:32.640
[Guest]: them to study outside whichever small town they lived in or, you know, because they had been

03:09:32.640 --> 03:09:37.280
[Guest]: hoping to go study in Delhi, go study in a city and their parents, those who were studying in

03:09:37.280 --> 03:09:41.360
[Guest]: Delhi were saying, you know, our hostels are, you know, tightening up on curfews,

03:09:42.000 --> 03:09:47.040
[Guest]: our parents want us to go back. Some, you know, some were feeling threatened that their parents

03:09:47.040 --> 03:09:51.920
[Guest]: may just say, forget it, don't study there. So there was this whole panic also that was building

03:09:51.920 --> 03:09:57.840
[Guest]: up. And they felt that the speech had spoken to them. So I realized that by asking some of them

03:09:57.840 --> 03:10:03.840
[Guest]: what speech, that they sent me this YouTube link. So then I realized that it's my friend, Vijay,

03:10:03.840 --> 03:10:11.440
[Guest]: who was, who is a, you know, he's into, he's a filmmaker and a photographer. So he had been

03:10:11.440 --> 03:10:17.200
[Guest]: documenting, he's been documenting many movements, and generally used to come to whatever protest we

03:10:17.200 --> 03:10:21.360
[Guest]: were doing and take photographs, take video and upload here and there and none of us had paid any

03:10:21.360 --> 03:10:27.520
[Guest]: attention much. It is there, okay. And I never used to share those links on social media and

03:10:27.520 --> 03:10:33.280
[Guest]: all also, because I didn't use social media much anyway. So I called him then. And he said,

03:10:40.720 --> 03:10:45.040
[Guest]: but yours is somehow blown up a bit and it seems to be getting a lot of attention.

03:10:45.600 --> 03:10:51.200
[Guest]: So even he was not the kind actually to really, you know, worry too much about what was happening

03:10:51.200 --> 03:10:56.480
[Guest]: to the videos he was uploading. So he said, yeah, I was meaning to tell you, yeah, there seems to be

03:10:56.480 --> 03:11:00.400
[Guest]: a lot of attention that one is getting. So then I told him, yeah, if it is getting attention,

03:11:00.400 --> 03:11:05.280
[Guest]: then let's put in at least a bio there that explains to people who they can contact and

03:11:05.280 --> 03:11:09.680
[Guest]: who I am in the first place and what the organization's name is and all of that,

03:11:09.680 --> 03:11:15.200
[Guest]: so that at least they know it's not just this, you know, video. So then we immediately did that.

03:11:15.200 --> 03:11:19.040
[Guest]: And then he started asking, he said, a lot of people are asking for an English translation.

03:11:19.040 --> 03:11:26.960
[Guest]: So then a journalist from Tehelka, yeah, actually did that translation. And she did a great job of

03:11:26.960 --> 03:11:32.400
[Guest]: the translation. And it appeared in Tehelka the next day. And that translation then we linked to

03:11:32.400 --> 03:11:38.080
[Guest]: this video also saying, okay, whoever wants English can access it here. So that I think was my,

03:11:38.080 --> 03:11:43.920
[Guest]: you know, my moment of realizing that there is a huge resonance to this idea that people,

03:11:43.920 --> 03:11:48.400
[Guest]: that women are not concerned just about not being raped. Of course, they're concerned about

03:11:48.400 --> 03:11:56.880
[Guest]: not being raped. But they are concerned also about what the fear of rape or the pretext of

03:11:56.880 --> 03:12:04.400
[Guest]: protecting you from rape, how this fear or this conservative pretext basically, you know,

03:12:04.400 --> 03:12:11.600
[Guest]: regulates their lives and chokes off experience for them. So both things, one is a genuine fear

03:12:11.600 --> 03:12:17.360
[Guest]: that your parents may have for you, of course. But there's also the thing that that fear sort of,

03:12:17.360 --> 03:12:23.200
[Guest]: you know, meshes very easily with your parents' fear that you may fall in love and marry the

03:12:23.200 --> 03:12:30.320
[Guest]: wrong guy. So both those fears, you know, they're running into each other, which is why if you run

03:12:30.320 --> 03:12:35.440
[Guest]: away with someone and marry someone, your parents can go file a complaint of rape and say that he's

03:12:35.440 --> 03:12:41.520
[Guest]: abducted you and raped you. And so I began thinking about that more and, you know, talking about it,

03:12:41.520 --> 03:12:45.600
[Guest]: writing about it. So in the course of that movement, I think the conversations were amazing.

03:12:45.600 --> 03:12:50.800
[Guest]: And that is why I will argue very fervently with anyone who tries to tell me that essentially that

03:12:50.800 --> 03:12:56.960
[Guest]: movement was largely a conservative one that was obsessed with the death penalty. Because I think

03:12:56.960 --> 03:13:02.640
[Guest]: that there were both strands in it. There was that strand. Oh, yes, there was. But in my experience,

03:13:02.640 --> 03:13:07.760
[Guest]: a lot of the sadharan log who had come without any specific agenda, but just thinking that rape

03:13:07.760 --> 03:13:14.320
[Guest]: is a bad thing. I had personal experience of stepping into a huge crowd of people yelling

03:13:14.320 --> 03:13:20.800
[Guest]: for the death penalty. You couldn't hear yourself speak. OK. And stepping in and trying to raise an

03:13:20.800 --> 03:13:27.520
[Guest]: alternative slogan and not able to think of what and then starting the slogan, which, you know,

03:13:27.520 --> 03:13:32.880
[Guest]: which says, Mahi laaye maange aazadi. It's a very flexible slogan, right? Because you can fit a lot

03:13:32.880 --> 03:13:38.640
[Guest]: of things into it because you can explain what that aazadi is, what kind of aazadi. And of course,

03:13:38.640 --> 03:13:44.480
[Guest]: that slogan has two histories. One is, of course, with the Pakistan women's movement started the

03:13:44.480 --> 03:13:50.480
[Guest]: slogan of Mahi laaye maange aazadi. And of course, the cadence of the slogan also has to do with the

03:13:50.480 --> 03:13:57.200
[Guest]: Kashmiri movement. And a lot of Kashmiri feminists also reminded us of that. And we said that

03:13:57.200 --> 03:14:02.000
[Guest]: absolutely, we must talk about Kashmiri women's concerns as well in this movement. So I found

03:14:02.000 --> 03:14:07.760
[Guest]: myself with great trepidation, me and another comrade of mine called Sucheta. We would have

03:14:07.760 --> 03:14:13.280
[Guest]: this small hand mic. OK, so you couldn't hear yourself speak and you couldn't,

03:14:13.280 --> 03:14:18.560
[Guest]: that hand mic also was pretty useless in India Gate because it was so loud and you couldn't hear

03:14:18.560 --> 03:14:24.000
[Guest]: yourself think because hamara bhi muh khule toh what would come out of our mouths was faasi doh

03:14:24.000 --> 03:14:29.200
[Guest]: because you couldn't hear any other word. OK, so then we said, all right, we are going to try.

03:14:29.840 --> 03:14:35.600
[Guest]: So we got into one crowd, one such crowd and started shouting this Mahi laaye maange aazadi

03:14:35.600 --> 03:14:41.360
[Guest]: slogan. And it caught on because people were just starved of what to raise also. It hadn't occurred

03:14:41.360 --> 03:14:46.560
[Guest]: to them. So then we started saying achha school me bhi, college me bhi, sadak par bhi, ghar me bhi,

03:14:46.560 --> 03:14:52.400
[Guest]: is me bhi, us me bhi. And we realized. And then after people had raised the slogan for a while,

03:14:52.400 --> 03:14:58.240
[Guest]: then we'd stop. And then I'd start, I'd talk briefly also. So I'd tell them about Soni Sori,

03:14:58.880 --> 03:15:04.320
[Guest]: tell them about Kunal Pushpura. And to my absolute amazement, OK, I did this with a

03:15:04.320 --> 03:15:11.120
[Guest]: lot of trepidation because I thought if this is some conservative RWA crowd, then they can beat

03:15:11.120 --> 03:15:16.320
[Guest]: me up only here for starting to talk about how rapes are done by the army towards women in

03:15:16.320 --> 03:15:23.200
[Guest]: Kashmir or something. So I was a little scared if I talk about, you know, Manipur or Nagaland and

03:15:23.200 --> 03:15:32.320
[Guest]: Kashmir in this context. But never once did we face any pushback. Never. We did this dozens of

03:15:32.320 --> 03:15:37.600
[Guest]: times in that movement. And we never came across an instance where somebody came up saying,

03:15:37.600 --> 03:15:41.200
[Guest]: what the hell, you can't do this. In fact, people were listening wide eyed and saying,

03:15:41.840 --> 03:15:47.120
[Guest]: really, we haven't heard about this ever in our lives. We didn't know. And this is terrible.

03:15:48.080 --> 03:15:56.640
[Guest]: So and two highlights of that, if I may. One was when we were raising the slogan and then

03:15:56.640 --> 03:16:02.400
[Guest]: some girls from the crowd started raising a slogan saying, we were saying, khap se bhi aazadi,

03:16:02.400 --> 03:16:08.720
[Guest]: and they started saying, bap se bhi aazadi, bhai se bhi aazadi. So it was a real thrill for

03:16:08.720 --> 03:16:13.280
[Guest]: Sujata and I because we were literally we had goosebumps, OK, because we were like,

03:16:13.280 --> 03:16:17.040
[Guest]: that wasn't something that had occurred to us. But that was precisely what we were saying.

03:16:17.040 --> 03:16:22.160
[Guest]: And that was precisely what we wanted, that rape and gender based violence is not just something

03:16:22.160 --> 03:16:28.400
[Guest]: that strangers do to you in a bus. It is something that people you love may do to you

03:16:28.400 --> 03:16:34.240
[Guest]: because they believe in an idea that of how you are supposed to behave. If you don't conform to

03:16:34.240 --> 03:16:39.680
[Guest]: that, they may think that they are entitled to stop you from living your life as you choose to

03:16:39.680 --> 03:16:45.840
[Guest]: live it. Right. So this was something which exactly we wanted to do that. And that was happening.

03:16:46.640 --> 03:16:50.400
[Guest]: And I'll tell you something, that these efforts are something which even a lot of

03:16:50.400 --> 03:16:55.760
[Guest]: people I admire who are otherwise very progressive on many things, usually men

03:16:57.440 --> 03:17:02.800
[Guest]: chose not to see what's happening. They chose not to know that feminists were making these efforts.

03:17:02.800 --> 03:17:09.360
[Guest]: So I've had a person I admire very much, a human rights activist, and I felt very bad about this

03:17:09.360 --> 03:17:14.480
[Guest]: because we attended a program together somewhere and we were at an airport and a call came in from

03:17:14.480 --> 03:17:18.720
[Guest]: some journalist who clearly didn't know anything. So she is asking me, OK, I want to

03:17:18.720 --> 03:17:23.760
[Guest]: bite from you about how the death penalty is a good thing. So I said, have you even ever heard

03:17:23.760 --> 03:17:30.080
[Guest]: me or listened to what I say or what I write? I'm against the death penalty, dammit. So I told her

03:17:30.080 --> 03:17:34.720
[Guest]: that first do some homework and then call. I'm not. You can't take a bite from me in favor of

03:17:34.720 --> 03:17:39.360
[Guest]: the death penalty. And I knew some people who had done this because they won't even call me

03:17:39.360 --> 03:17:44.000
[Guest]: and they just use my name and put, OK, Kavita Krishnan demanded fancy for so-and-so. And then

03:17:44.000 --> 03:17:49.280
[Guest]: I have to call up their publication and say, you know, you didn't speak to me. How did you say

03:17:49.280 --> 03:17:54.080
[Guest]: that I demanded death penalty? Because I wouldn't, because I don't stand for it. So this person was

03:17:54.080 --> 03:18:00.640
[Guest]: standing next to me, this very well-respected human rights activist and all of that. So he asked me,

03:18:00.640 --> 03:18:04.080
[Guest]: what was that all about? So I told him and I said, oh, you know, people don't keep track

03:18:04.080 --> 03:18:09.840
[Guest]: and they think this movement is, you know, that 2012 movement was all about fancy, fancy.

03:18:09.840 --> 03:18:15.120
[Guest]: So he said, but it was, no. And you guys also were with that only, no. And I looked at him with

03:18:15.120 --> 03:18:19.200
[Guest]: such a sense of betrayal. And I remember that I wasn't angry enough. I think I was just very

03:18:19.200 --> 03:18:24.880
[Guest]: bemused at that point. And you only think of smart things to say later. So I later thought,

03:18:24.880 --> 03:18:29.360
[Guest]: you know, that I wanted to tell him and I don't remember whether I finally did or not. Maybe I did

03:18:29.360 --> 03:18:35.120
[Guest]: tell him that, you know, how could you? We were spending our time and energy intervening in this

03:18:35.120 --> 03:18:40.880
[Guest]: instead of assuming that these are a bunch of, you know, irretrievably right-wing, conservative,

03:18:40.880 --> 03:18:46.960
[Guest]: fundamentalist idiots. We went to people and we started finding a way to intervene and talk about

03:18:46.960 --> 03:18:53.680
[Guest]: feminist concerns. We did it. You guys didn't. Okay. We did it. And you have the luxury to think

03:18:53.680 --> 03:18:59.920
[Guest]: that, oh, you know, you people were all part of that now, that kind of, that movement that wanted

03:18:59.920 --> 03:19:05.360
[Guest]: all these, you know, draconian measures. No, we were not, you know. So that was one moment.

03:19:06.400 --> 03:19:09.760
[Guest]: The other highlight, which I'll always remember with a great deal of joy,

03:19:10.320 --> 03:19:15.760
[Guest]: is that at the Jantar Mantar, there was this one chap who was a permanent fixture at Jantar Mantar,

03:19:15.760 --> 03:19:21.200
[Guest]: always raising slogans for the death penalty and looking very large and aggressive. And he was

03:19:21.200 --> 03:19:27.680
[Guest]: obviously a sort of Delhi ka local. Toh wo panda, waha saara dim bhi hai. Toh wo panda

03:19:27.680 --> 03:19:36.480
[Guest]: waha saara dim rehta tha every day. And he looked pretty daunting. You know, and he wouldn't respond

03:19:36.480 --> 03:19:40.880
[Guest]: to anything we were saying. He would go on saying his own thing and raising his own slogans,

03:19:40.880 --> 03:19:47.360
[Guest]: almost alone. So one day in February, we had this larger program where we, for the first time,

03:19:47.360 --> 03:19:52.240
[Guest]: raised a small dais. Okay. So it was a slightly raised platform. So on that raised platform,

03:19:52.240 --> 03:19:57.520
[Guest]: many people spoke and spoke about explaining why the death penalty is wrong also. Even I spoke.

03:19:57.520 --> 03:20:03.920
[Guest]: And all of that. So after I spoke, and I'd spoken about many things, when I got down from there,

03:20:03.920 --> 03:20:09.120
[Guest]: this man was waiting for me. So I was a little wary because I was like, okay,

03:20:09.120 --> 03:20:14.960
[Guest]: maybe he is waiting to confront me with what, how dare you. And he came to me and he said,

03:20:14.960 --> 03:20:21.280
[Guest]: Madam, itne dino se aap roz aati rahi hai, maini na aapko pehli baar suna thek se.

03:20:21.280 --> 03:20:27.600
[Guest]: Toh isse pehle na, maini suna hi nahi tha aap kya boli thi. Toh aap toh bol rahi thi,

03:20:27.600 --> 03:20:32.160
[Guest]: woh toh bilkul achcha laga humko toh. Aap toh sahi bol rahi thi. Toh maini ka,

03:20:32.160 --> 03:20:37.440
[Guest]: achcha. Toh he said, bas mujhe do cheezon pe thoda sa doubt hua. Toh one of the things that he had

03:20:37.440 --> 03:20:42.240
[Guest]: doubt about was this death penalty thing. So he asked me, he said, lekin aapko nahi lagta ki

03:20:42.240 --> 03:20:47.600
[Guest]: jisne itna kharab kiya hai, unko nahi milni chahiye kya? Maini ka, milni toh, saza milni chahiye,

03:20:47.600 --> 03:20:52.800
[Guest]: ek toh sabko. Consent violate karne ke liye, hai na? Lekin faasi ki saza de karke,

03:20:53.600 --> 03:20:58.400
[Guest]: maini mahilaon ka faida kyun hoga? Rather you will allow the people who are wanting to change

03:20:58.400 --> 03:21:03.440
[Guest]: the conversation from women's rights to just feeling happy that somebody has been hanged

03:21:03.440 --> 03:21:07.120
[Guest]: and congratulating themselves and going back to treating women in their lives the same bad way.

03:21:07.680 --> 03:21:12.720
[Guest]: So he said, haan, yeh toh sahi baat hai. Then, and I also said, look, there are many instances

03:21:12.720 --> 03:21:18.800
[Guest]: in which innocent people in all kinds of cases are killed. So death penalty is irretrievable.

03:21:18.800 --> 03:21:22.240
[Guest]: You can't change it. You can't bring somebody alive once you've killed them. So what if you've

03:21:22.240 --> 03:21:27.840
[Guest]: killed the wrong guy, right? Is the police always reliable? Do they always catch the right guy?

03:21:27.840 --> 03:21:31.520
[Guest]: So he's like, haan, that's true. Then the second question he had was, he said,

03:21:31.520 --> 03:21:37.520
[Guest]: achha aapne army ke baare mein bola aur wo sab bola. So don't you think that militants also

03:21:37.520 --> 03:21:42.960
[Guest]: do violence against women in Kashmir and in Northeast and all or wherever? So I said,

03:21:42.960 --> 03:21:47.200
[Guest]: of course. But the point is that the law does not make an exception for them.

03:21:47.760 --> 03:21:53.120
[Guest]: If a militant does that, they are considered punishable by law. So our problem is that

03:21:53.120 --> 03:21:57.200
[Guest]: nobody should be given an exception for these things just because they are wearing an army

03:21:57.200 --> 03:22:04.640
[Guest]: uniform, right? Haan, bilkul theek bola aapne, he said. And I went off feeling a sense of triumph

03:22:04.640 --> 03:22:10.240
[Guest]: in a way. And when I told my partner this had happened, he said, woh kya hai na ki woh,

03:22:10.240 --> 03:22:15.280
[Guest]: he's been so busy talking that he hasn't, you were at the same level and he didn't hear you

03:22:15.280 --> 03:22:21.120
[Guest]: and you didn't have a good enough mic. This time it was on a platform. You had a mic. And in a way,

03:22:21.120 --> 03:22:26.560
[Guest]: it was loud enough that he actually stopped continuously talking himself and listened.

03:22:27.360 --> 03:22:33.520
[Guest]: And he was like, haan, makes sense. So yeah, I mean, even a very pakka death penalty guy

03:22:33.520 --> 03:22:40.160
[Amit Varma]: was actually persuaded the other way. Yeah. Remarkable story. Totally a web series should

03:22:40.160 --> 03:22:43.920
[Amit Varma]: be made on your life. Maybe, you know, the narrative in this episode can be the skeletal

03:22:43.920 --> 03:22:49.040
[Amit Varma]: structure. You sit down with me and then all the events unfold in vivid flashback.

03:22:49.840 --> 03:22:54.560
[Amit Varma]: So before I lead to my next big question, I just want to make one observation of my own,

03:22:54.560 --> 03:22:58.560
[Amit Varma]: which you can respond to if you have something to add. And I'll also quote a couple of times

03:22:58.560 --> 03:23:02.800
[Amit Varma]: from your book because I want to elaborate on things that you mentioned in your own words.

03:23:02.800 --> 03:23:07.280
[Amit Varma]: And then I'll get to my question. One as far as the death penalty is concerned,

03:23:07.280 --> 03:23:12.640
[Amit Varma]: the reason I am against it and in fact, against all death penalties in any crime, but for rape,

03:23:13.360 --> 03:23:17.600
[Amit Varma]: just the economist point of view is that you're creating an incentive to murder if the punishment

03:23:17.600 --> 03:23:23.040
[Amit Varma]: for murder and rape is exactly the same, then in the criminal's mind, it doesn't make a difference

03:23:23.040 --> 03:23:27.760
[Amit Varma]: in terms of the risk, but it makes it less likely for him to be caught if he murders a person he's

03:23:27.760 --> 03:23:33.040
[Amit Varma]: raping. So why do you want to create that incentive? And the other more deontological

03:23:33.040 --> 03:23:37.360
[Amit Varma]: standpoint there is that it is wrong to kill even if the state is doing it. And the point is the

03:23:37.360 --> 03:23:41.280
[Amit Varma]: state gets so much wrong. I mean, listeners of the show would realize I don't trust the state

03:23:41.280 --> 03:23:45.840
[Amit Varma]: with anything, you know, power always corrupt. So whoever is in control of the state at a

03:23:45.840 --> 03:23:50.080
[Amit Varma]: particular point in time, why do you want to give them the right over life and what you what you

03:23:50.080 --> 03:23:54.640
[Amit Varma]: said about the army is actually very striking. I had an episode with the philosopher Jason Brennan,

03:23:54.640 --> 03:24:00.000
[Amit Varma]: where we kind of discuss the right to self defense and to defend others. And one of the points that

03:24:00.000 --> 03:24:05.440
[Amit Varma]: he made, in fact, he wrote a book about it, is that even if somebody in uniform is doing something

03:24:05.440 --> 03:24:11.680
[Amit Varma]: right, there is absolutely zero extra protection that that person should have, just because they're

03:24:11.680 --> 03:24:16.720
[Amit Varma]: wearing a uniform or they're an officer of the state. So if you see someone beating up a young

03:24:16.720 --> 03:24:21.840
[Amit Varma]: girl on the street, it's your moral duty to intervene, even if the person doing the beating

03:24:21.840 --> 03:24:26.880
[Amit Varma]: up is a policeman, which is a convincing argument and an interesting episode. Now a couple of

03:24:27.440 --> 03:24:31.520
[Amit Varma]: important observations, and I'm only you've already mentioned them, but I just want to

03:24:31.520 --> 03:24:36.000
[Amit Varma]: emphasize on them because they made an impression on me. And I think they're, you know, powerful

03:24:36.000 --> 03:24:41.760
[Amit Varma]: insights. And I'd like my listeners to realize, and one of them is that you have a chapter on how

03:24:41.760 --> 03:24:46.240
[Amit Varma]: in India people treat the home as a haven for the women, women are not supposed to go out and so on

03:24:46.240 --> 03:24:52.080
[Amit Varma]: and so forth. But you point out that women are safer on the streets than in their homes. And,

03:24:52.080 --> 03:24:58.000
[Amit Varma]: and this is in fact, worldwide, like you talk about a United Nations study that shows that

03:24:58.000 --> 03:25:02.720
[Amit Varma]: women who are the victims of homicide globally, about half of them are killed by intimate partners

03:25:02.720 --> 03:25:09.120
[Amit Varma]: or family members and only 6% of men in Ireland. In fact, that's 87% of the women who were murdered

03:25:09.120 --> 03:25:14.640
[Amit Varma]: in Ireland were killed by a man they knew. And equally, you know, as you've pointed out,

03:25:14.640 --> 03:25:20.080
[Amit Varma]: the figures overwhelmingly showed that a lot of, you know, rapes and sexual assaults actually

03:25:20.080 --> 03:25:26.160
[Amit Varma]: happen in the home. The other important point to make is about how the way people define rape

03:25:26.160 --> 03:25:31.680
[Amit Varma]: in India doesn't often take consent into account, which is bizarre. And this goes in both ways,

03:25:31.680 --> 03:25:35.440
[Amit Varma]: as you pointed out that our notions of consent and non consent are screwed up,

03:25:35.440 --> 03:25:41.920
[Amit Varma]: where you've pointed out that how a tremendously large number of rape cases are actually filed by

03:25:41.920 --> 03:25:47.120
[Amit Varma]: parents against a man their daughter has eloped with. So they are calling it rape, because their

03:25:47.120 --> 03:25:52.240
[Amit Varma]: property has gone away with somebody else. And even and those two people might have consensual

03:25:52.240 --> 03:25:57.760
[Amit Varma]: sex or even a kid together, but they call it rape. And on the other hand, because their daughter is

03:25:57.760 --> 03:26:02.720
[Amit Varma]: property, they decide who to give it away to. And you have all these arranged marriages where poor

03:26:02.720 --> 03:26:08.320
[Amit Varma]: beveled women have to move away to wherever and just begin negotiating life again, and are raped

03:26:08.320 --> 03:26:12.160
[Amit Varma]: by their husbands. And that's not considered rape according to the law, which is, again, something

03:26:12.160 --> 03:26:18.240
[Amit Varma]: you've eloquently, you know, spoken about and written about in the past. Now, my question here

03:26:18.240 --> 03:26:24.960
[Amit Varma]: is this, that we spoke about, you know, how in the law, which is, of course, Victorian era relic,

03:26:24.960 --> 03:26:30.000
[Amit Varma]: the IPC, and we know the values they brought in, that women were treated as property of the men,

03:26:30.000 --> 03:26:33.840
[Amit Varma]: our culture is very much like that, like I realised that there are different strands in

03:26:33.840 --> 03:26:38.000
[Amit Varma]: our culture, we contain multitudes, and there is a liberal strand as well. And in fact,

03:26:38.000 --> 03:26:41.920
[Amit Varma]: I'm reminded of this book I discovered while recording an episode in the Gita Press with

03:26:41.920 --> 03:26:46.960
[Amit Varma]: Akshay Mukul. And you must have read the book many, many times, because just the title is so

03:26:46.960 --> 03:26:53.120
[Amit Varma]: awesome. The title is Marx Vada Ram Rajya by Karpatri Maharaj. Yeah, you're familiar with the

03:26:53.120 --> 03:26:59.360
[Amit Varma]: book. And one of the arguments he gives against communism is that because there is no private

03:26:59.360 --> 03:27:04.320
[Amit Varma]: property there, men can't own the women. So all women are like, you know, they are in a bucket,

03:27:04.320 --> 03:27:09.600
[Guest]: which any man can drink from the image that he used. The Communist Manifesto actually says that,

03:27:09.600 --> 03:27:15.280
[Guest]: no, the Communist Manifesto that Marx and Engels wrote has a line to that effect, because they say

03:27:15.280 --> 03:27:22.160
[Guest]: that the minute we say that property will be collectively owned, that minute the bourgeois

03:27:22.160 --> 03:27:27.280
[Guest]: ideologues start saying, Oh, my God, that means women will be owned in common. And he says,

03:27:27.280 --> 03:27:31.200
[Guest]: they don't understand poor things that we don't, we don't look at women as property,

03:27:31.200 --> 03:27:35.600
[Guest]: women will not be property, they will be, you know, in charge of their own lives.

03:27:35.600 --> 03:27:40.480
[Guest]: The Communist Manifesto has a line exactly to that effect in reply to this kind of nonsense.

03:27:40.480 --> 03:27:46.160
[Amit Varma]: Fantastic. I didn't know that you've kind of completed the story for me. But I found that

03:27:46.160 --> 03:27:51.600
[Amit Varma]: line by Karpatri Maharaj, a bucket that anyone can drink from just both hilarious and deeply

03:27:51.600 --> 03:27:57.040
[Amit Varma]: disturbing. And I say deeply disturbing, because I think it's reflective of a certain common way

03:27:57.040 --> 03:28:02.000
[Amit Varma]: of thinking that is in our culture, which kind of leads me to my question, which is that agreed

03:28:02.000 --> 03:28:07.360
[Amit Varma]: that there are multiple strands, but a dominant strand in our culture, certainly today, is this

03:28:07.360 --> 03:28:11.360
[Amit Varma]: kind of regressive strand, which says women are the property of men, they should be in the house,

03:28:11.360 --> 03:28:15.280
[Amit Varma]: they should take the permission of whoever their male guardian is before leaving the home and blah,

03:28:15.280 --> 03:28:19.920
[Amit Varma]: blah, blah, blah, blah, we know all of that, therefore reducing half of Indians to a subspecies.

03:28:19.920 --> 03:28:25.440
[Amit Varma]: Now, my question then is this, and this is, of course, a strand that's become dominant,

03:28:25.440 --> 03:28:30.000
[Amit Varma]: but which was always there. Now, one question that I've asked multiple guests who have come

03:28:30.000 --> 03:28:35.280
[Amit Varma]: on the show, especially when we are discussing the Constitution, is that if assuming that the

03:28:35.280 --> 03:28:40.000
[Amit Varma]: Constitution was a liberal document, and it's not liberal enough for me, but it's more liberal than

03:28:40.000 --> 03:28:46.960
[Amit Varma]: our society. Now, assuming that our Constitution is a liberal document imposed upon an illiberal

03:28:46.960 --> 03:28:53.760
[Amit Varma]: society, how can that imposition itself not be illiberal? And this is a dilemma I can't get

03:28:53.760 --> 03:28:58.320
[Amit Varma]: around, because you and I would share certain values, for example, the primacy of consent,

03:28:58.320 --> 03:29:04.320
[Amit Varma]: and the fact that coercion is bad, and we would share those. But we are elites in a bubble,

03:29:04.320 --> 03:29:09.360
[Amit Varma]: in a sense, most of the country doesn't share those. Now, Mahatma Gandhi's way would have been

03:29:09.360 --> 03:29:14.480
[Amit Varma]: to change the culture, right? Politics is downstream of culture, change the culture first,

03:29:14.480 --> 03:29:20.560
[Amit Varma]: and then things will change. And it and that looks like something that we and I'm very broad

03:29:20.560 --> 03:29:24.800
[Amit Varma]: tent, including, you know, the liberals and whoever feels this way that we failed in that,

03:29:25.360 --> 03:29:30.000
[Amit Varma]: that society hasn't changed, if anything, politics has now caught up with society.

03:29:30.000 --> 03:29:36.480
[Amit Varma]: And that makes me feel very bleak, because where is the failure? Was the failure inevitable,

03:29:36.480 --> 03:29:43.680
[Amit Varma]: if these beliefs are so deep rooted in society? And, you know, I don't know if I have a question,

03:29:43.680 --> 03:29:46.800
[Amit Varma]: but it's kind of a depressing observation. What do you think about this?

03:29:46.800 --> 03:29:54.720
[Guest]: You know, I actually attended a seminar once, which was organized by people who were basically

03:29:54.720 --> 03:30:01.440
[Guest]: very good scholars about India, Indian politics, Indian society, and specifically the Constitution.

03:30:01.440 --> 03:30:08.080
[Guest]: So this was actually it had been organized, I think it was in Norway. And what we said there

03:30:08.080 --> 03:30:15.440
[Guest]: has been published as a book, which I, as usual, in my post COVID brain cannot remember the exact

03:30:15.440 --> 03:30:22.640
[Guest]: title of it was India at 70 something or the other. But the thing is that there was actually

03:30:22.640 --> 03:30:29.040
[Guest]: a session where, you know, I had spoken, and I had spoken in response to, you know, just the

03:30:29.040 --> 03:30:33.440
[Guest]: session before that people had discussed exactly this, about whether because they had said that

03:30:33.440 --> 03:30:39.840
[Guest]: the Indian Constitution was more something that was sourced from, you know, good practices all

03:30:39.840 --> 03:30:43.840
[Guest]: over the world. And so it was, it was experts who were doing the sourcing. And it was very

03:30:43.840 --> 03:30:48.960
[Guest]: different from say, you know, the Paris Commune, right, you know, writing, or even the Soviet

03:30:48.960 --> 03:30:53.760
[Guest]: Revolution, you know, some some constitution being written there, because those were things

03:30:53.760 --> 03:30:58.400
[Guest]: in which people who are writing the Constitution, you know, the doors would keep opening and people

03:30:58.400 --> 03:31:02.080
[Guest]: would actually be coming, you can hear the you can read about these descriptions, both for the

03:31:02.080 --> 03:31:08.400
[Guest]: Paris Commune and for Soviet Constitution, Bolshevik Revolution, people coming in and saying,

03:31:08.400 --> 03:31:14.480
[Guest]: people coming in and saying, you haven't added this, what have you written about us here,

03:31:14.480 --> 03:31:18.880
[Guest]: what on earth, you have to change this, you have to change that. So it is a democratic process in

03:31:18.880 --> 03:31:25.280
[Guest]: and a much more chaotic process, but a democratic, much more democratic process. So are we imposing

03:31:25.280 --> 03:31:30.720
[Guest]: a constitution on, is it more of a pedagogic exercise that you are forcing it on people?

03:31:31.520 --> 03:31:37.520
[Guest]: So the way I look at it is, and what I said there also is that I don't think that's quite

03:31:37.520 --> 03:31:43.440
[Guest]: the thing. See, in any society, just put India aside for a minute and think about

03:31:44.160 --> 03:31:51.760
[Guest]: any society in the world, okay, they still have illiberal tendencies. And quite possibly,

03:31:51.760 --> 03:31:56.960
[Guest]: if you put things to a vote, I mean, I would say that even in a country like Ireland, I mean,

03:31:56.960 --> 03:32:03.040
[Guest]: getting, you know, the right to abortion, or, you know, other countries in which, you know,

03:32:03.040 --> 03:32:07.840
[Guest]: homosexuality being decriminalized and all, they've been able to do it through a referendum.

03:32:07.840 --> 03:32:13.600
[Guest]: I think, you know, the fact that they've been able to do this in the 21st century, and not before

03:32:13.600 --> 03:32:19.760
[Guest]: this tells you that, you know, that for all this while, the societies were not at that place. And

03:32:19.760 --> 03:32:25.840
[Guest]: I doubt if any of the societies were. Even today in the US, I would be suspicious that if you were

03:32:25.840 --> 03:32:31.120
[Guest]: to put the right to abortion to a vote, or if you were to put the, you know, the right of gay people

03:32:31.120 --> 03:32:37.680
[Guest]: to marry to a vote, I am not sure which position would win. It is not by any means certain, okay.

03:32:38.320 --> 03:32:44.880
[Guest]: So the whole point is that democracy is not just about what the majority believes in, right? It's

03:32:44.880 --> 03:32:53.280
[Guest]: also about protecting the rights of the individual and the rights of the minority to not be imposed

03:32:53.280 --> 03:32:58.880
[Guest]: on by the majority, right? So, and when I say majority minority here, I'm not talking about,

03:32:58.880 --> 03:33:04.160
[Guest]: okay, us as a, you know, some educated elites or whatever, right? I'm talking about people,

03:33:04.160 --> 03:33:07.280
[Guest]: after all, you know, for instance, if you look at inter-caste marriage, okay?

03:33:08.800 --> 03:33:14.400
[Guest]: The fact that there is such a, almost sort of moral panic about inter-caste marriage and

03:33:14.400 --> 03:33:19.440
[Guest]: interfaith marriage, and it's growing right now, is because more people are crossing those

03:33:19.440 --> 03:33:24.800
[Guest]: boundaries. You know, you're having people putting their lives on the line, marrying,

03:33:24.800 --> 03:33:32.080
[Guest]: you know, in the same gotra or across castes or across communities, okay? Which is why every time

03:33:32.080 --> 03:33:38.480
[Guest]: you see a louder voice in society railing on, even in history, okay? I was taught this as a

03:33:38.480 --> 03:33:43.600
[Guest]: literature student long ago, that if you're reading something in which you're, if somebody's

03:33:43.600 --> 03:33:48.400
[Guest]: writing the Manusmriti and trying to lay down the law on this and that, they're having to do that

03:33:48.400 --> 03:33:53.280
[Guest]: because clearly people are not doing that on the ground. The reality is, they're not reflecting

03:33:53.280 --> 03:34:02.560
[Guest]: reality, they're trying desperately to regulate reality, right? And regulate an unruly population.

03:34:02.560 --> 03:34:08.880
[Guest]: So, in India also, I feel that the Manusmriti may have been there and dominant castes and dominant

03:34:08.880 --> 03:34:15.360
[Guest]: culture may have lived by those values, even if they did not, you know, exactly read the Manusmriti

03:34:15.360 --> 03:34:21.120
[Guest]: every morning. The point is the Manusmriti has encodified a lot of things which were

03:34:21.120 --> 03:34:26.560
[Guest]: seen to be the right things and which may have been expressed in a variety of ways in

03:34:26.560 --> 03:34:32.160
[Guest]: more popular literature and scriptures and documents. But the point is that clearly,

03:34:32.160 --> 03:34:36.320
[Guest]: even in those societies, there were those who were not following those laws. There were those

03:34:36.320 --> 03:34:42.000
[Guest]: who were breaking those laws. I find it fascinating to read Wendy Doniger's latest, I think it's her

03:34:42.000 --> 03:34:48.560
[Guest]: latest book, which is called Beyond Dharma. She's written repeatedly about, she reads the Arthashastra

03:34:48.560 --> 03:34:55.680
[Guest]: and the Kamasutra as being documents that sort of dissenting against the Manusmriti. So, these are,

03:34:55.680 --> 03:35:00.720
[Guest]: you know, things that are in conversation with each other and are very subtly dissenting. So,

03:35:00.720 --> 03:35:06.800
[Guest]: they are paying lip service to all the rules, but then they are actually preaching something

03:35:06.800 --> 03:35:15.600
[Guest]: very different. So, they are saying, so the Kamasutra is saying, but in reality, they are

03:35:15.600 --> 03:35:21.280
[Guest]: dealing with a reality in which people are conducting secret affairs, people are having

03:35:21.280 --> 03:35:27.040
[Guest]: relationships with people, you know, which are forbidden, extramarital relationships,

03:35:27.040 --> 03:35:32.080
[Guest]: relationships across castes and all of that, right? So, my point is that therefore, you know,

03:35:32.640 --> 03:35:40.080
[Guest]: the constitution is not an entirely alien document and it wasn't perceived or received

03:35:40.080 --> 03:35:45.360
[Guest]: as only an alien document. So, if you look at this book called, again, I'm terrible with the names.

03:35:45.360 --> 03:35:48.880
[Amit Varma]: The People's Constitution by Rohit Desai. People's Constitution by Rohit Desai. Yeah. So,

03:35:48.880 --> 03:35:53.360
[Guest]: I remember the author's name, but not the. So, that is a fascinating book, isn't it? Because

03:35:53.360 --> 03:35:59.840
[Guest]: it is about people, basically ordinary Indian people picking up the constitution and deciding

03:35:59.840 --> 03:36:05.280
[Guest]: that they wanted to use it as a shield, use it as their instrument to, you know, claim

03:36:06.400 --> 03:36:12.160
[Guest]: inclusion and claim rights, right? So, I don't think of it, therefore, as only, I agree with

03:36:12.160 --> 03:36:18.080
[Guest]: you that I think that it's not, you know, liberal enough. It's not, there's a lot more, a lot more

03:36:18.080 --> 03:36:24.240
[Guest]: that the document could have been much more. Certainly, in reality, it has not been translated

03:36:24.240 --> 03:36:31.920
[Guest]: into reality at all, right? But on the whole, I don't see it as entirely an alien thing, okay?

03:36:31.920 --> 03:36:36.720
[Guest]: But to me, what I look at is what you're going to say. There are two ways of looking at this

03:36:36.720 --> 03:36:42.880
[Guest]: dichotomy between what the constitution represents as an idea and what is there in reality, right? So,

03:36:42.880 --> 03:36:48.800
[Guest]: if I am Ambedkar, if I follow Ambedkar, then Ambedkar said it right then, when it was being

03:36:48.800 --> 03:36:54.640
[Guest]: adopted. He said that, sorry, there is, you know, you have one man, one vote, but in society,

03:36:54.640 --> 03:37:00.720
[Guest]: it is not one man, one value. You still have a society which is not, which is deeply illiberal,

03:37:00.720 --> 03:37:05.440
[Guest]: where democracy is only in the top soil. So, at the end of it, what was he saying?

03:37:05.440 --> 03:37:11.520
[Guest]: He was saying, if it's at the top soil, please help it to get more rooted, no? He wasn't saying

03:37:11.520 --> 03:37:17.360
[Guest]: that, therefore, this is an alien document that you will have to keep through lack of consent

03:37:17.360 --> 03:37:23.040
[Guest]: or whatever, right? He was talking about changing society, therefore, as, you know, he and Gandhi,

03:37:23.040 --> 03:37:28.000
[Guest]: what you said about Gandhi, actually, that applies a lot more to Ambedkar, because Ambedkar was,

03:37:28.000 --> 03:37:32.800
[Guest]: is exactly saying this, that after all, then you need to be able to change society so that it is

03:37:32.800 --> 03:37:40.320
[Guest]: actually one human being, one value. But if I'm Ram Madhav, writing in 2017, when I feel that my

03:37:40.320 --> 03:37:48.000
[Guest]: ideology of the RSS, which was, you know, personal non grata in 1947, and certainly after 1948, when

03:37:48.000 --> 03:37:54.800
[Guest]: Gandhi was killed, the RSS was a hissing and a byword. But today, the RSS is in power. And he

03:37:54.800 --> 03:38:00.400
[Guest]: thinks he's triumphant, he thinks there's going to be a Hindu Rashtra by 2025. So writing in 2017,

03:38:00.400 --> 03:38:06.080
[Guest]: Ram Madhav writes about this exact situation, the same gap. He doesn't say constitution,

03:38:06.080 --> 03:38:11.920
[Guest]: but he means it. He says that, you know, our rulers, immediately after independence,

03:38:12.480 --> 03:38:19.040
[Guest]: all the governments since independence before this one, they were alien to the country,

03:38:19.760 --> 03:38:26.320
[Guest]: because they did not operate from the place of what he calls the genius of India. And he defines

03:38:26.320 --> 03:38:33.120
[Guest]: this as being caste, community, religion, festival, guru, something like that. Okay.

03:38:34.000 --> 03:38:41.600
[Guest]: So, you know, and he says that this is all Western liberal values that they

03:38:41.600 --> 03:38:48.240
[Guest]: embraced. And this is the first government that is in tune with the mob. And he deliberately uses

03:38:48.240 --> 03:38:56.320
[Guest]: the word mob, because he then taunts those whom he says are westernized liberal intellectuals,

03:38:56.320 --> 03:39:03.520
[Guest]: and says that, you know, you are so alienated from family, caste, community, guru and whatnot,

03:39:04.160 --> 03:39:09.360
[Guest]: that you are crying now because the mob is happy now. And he is referring to the protests against

03:39:09.360 --> 03:39:14.240
[Guest]: mob lynching. Because he's not he's not saying it, but he's using the word mob because he wants to

03:39:14.240 --> 03:39:18.960
[Guest]: say, the mob is happy because they're free to lynch and they can, you know, the government will

03:39:18.960 --> 03:39:24.160
[Guest]: say damn good job done, good job, rather than saying, oh, you violated the constitution, you

03:39:24.160 --> 03:39:29.840
[Guest]: know. So my point is, Ram Madhav is reaching the exact opposite conclusion that Ambedkar is. He's

03:39:29.840 --> 03:39:39.680
[Guest]: saying, you have a government that is in line with the mob now. And the ideals that your own society

03:39:39.680 --> 03:39:45.760
[Guest]: has values in it, it can be a better version of itself, okay, rather than, you know, looking at

03:39:45.760 --> 03:39:50.880
[Guest]: these values as being alien, liberal, westernized values, which is, you know, complete nonsense,

03:39:50.880 --> 03:39:55.360
[Guest]: if you look at it that way. Because my point is, you know, for instance, feminism,

03:39:55.360 --> 03:39:59.600
[Guest]: they love calling us feminists, you know, westernized, you know, cut off from the world

03:39:59.600 --> 03:40:04.560
[Guest]: and everything. But please tell me, I mean, you know, what do you say about and I've written

03:40:04.560 --> 03:40:10.400
[Guest]: about this in my book, that what do you say about, you know, some 13th century nun, who is writing

03:40:10.400 --> 03:40:17.120
[Guest]: about being free? What do you say about a 19th century housewife, who's writing about yearning

03:40:17.120 --> 03:40:27.040
[Guest]: to be free? And they face the same abuses of free sex that we are facing today. I mean, in different

03:40:27.040 --> 03:40:32.400
[Guest]: words and different, but the idea was that you are, you are not a good woman. Feminists being

03:40:32.400 --> 03:40:40.400
[Guest]: accused of being cut off and your idea of freedom and all has come up only because you are westernized

03:40:40.400 --> 03:40:45.760
[Guest]: and so on. And those women who are not educated, who were, you know, the real women of India,

03:40:45.760 --> 03:40:50.720
[Guest]: they are not bothered about all this. That's, that's just not true. Because if you look at

03:40:50.720 --> 03:40:57.360
[Guest]: centuries ago, long before any idea of, you know, formal feminism or a feminist movement came into

03:40:57.360 --> 03:41:04.000
[Guest]: being, the yearning to be free, the yearning to be free of an abusive husband or free of even

03:41:04.000 --> 03:41:10.240
[Guest]: domestic chores. As I said, you have the Buddhist nuns writing about this centuries ago, saying that

03:41:10.240 --> 03:41:16.560
[Guest]: I want to be free from the chakla belan and whatnot, you know, the home chores and kitchen

03:41:16.560 --> 03:41:21.840
[Guest]: and all of that. I want to be free of an abusive husband. You have, you know, a 19th century

03:41:21.840 --> 03:41:27.520
[Guest]: Bengali woman from a conservative household teaching herself to write secretly and saying

03:41:27.520 --> 03:41:33.680
[Guest]: that I know that people say that if women learn to read and write, then they will become immoral

03:41:33.680 --> 03:41:41.040
[Guest]: and so on. And she says Kalyug will come. She writes, I say, blessed, blessed be that Kalyug,

03:41:41.040 --> 03:41:46.720
[Guest]: if it means that girls will get to read and write, you know, and she talks about feeling like a caged

03:41:46.720 --> 03:41:52.480
[Guest]: bird and wanting to fly free. So what I'm saying is, why assume that a woman in a conservative

03:41:52.480 --> 03:41:58.480
[Guest]: household today, who lives a circumscribed life inside the four walls of the home, does not dream

03:41:58.480 --> 03:42:04.240
[Guest]: of living a larger life, does not want her daughter to have a different life? Of course they do.

03:42:04.880 --> 03:42:12.160
[Guest]: So I think we cannot concede that, and I refuse to concede that, you know, in general, all Indians,

03:42:12.160 --> 03:42:18.000
[Guest]: barring a small, educated, liberal elite, basically are, you know, conservative and

03:42:18.000 --> 03:42:22.000
[Guest]: share the RSS's values or whatever it is or casteist values or whatever. No,

03:42:22.640 --> 03:42:30.000
[Guest]: I think that they have a potential. In fact, I would hazard a guess that at least on some issues,

03:42:30.000 --> 03:42:34.400
[Guest]: it is actually a minority that imposes these things on the majority. For instance, meat eating.

03:42:34.400 --> 03:42:40.880
[Guest]: Okay. I am a vegetarian by choice because I, you know, I would hope to be vegan and so on and so

03:42:40.880 --> 03:42:46.320
[Guest]: forth. That's for a different conversation another day. But my point is that I realize that in India,

03:42:46.320 --> 03:42:52.640
[Guest]: diet and so on has so much to do with inequalities also. Okay. And I cannot go around imposing being

03:42:52.640 --> 03:42:57.760
[Guest]: vegetarian as a moral value over those who eat meat the other way around. I have to support those

03:42:57.760 --> 03:43:03.120
[Guest]: who are being attacked and killed for eating meat. Right. Now, my point is, if you did a poll in

03:43:03.120 --> 03:43:07.920
[Guest]: India, I really challenge it. This is one thing on which I am very confident that, you know,

03:43:07.920 --> 03:43:13.040
[Guest]: the far right would lose a referendum. If you were to do a poll on meat eating, because most,

03:43:13.040 --> 03:43:18.880
[Guest]: you know, the large, vast majority in India is not vegetarian. Okay. It simply is not, you know.

03:43:18.880 --> 03:43:24.480
[Guest]: So it's a wrong impression that they are. So on some things, I think it's actually a majority

03:43:24.480 --> 03:43:30.400
[Guest]: that is imposing values on the minority because they are much louder, much more powerful and

03:43:30.400 --> 03:43:34.960
[Guest]: dominant. But in some other things, suppose you say that, okay, inter-caste marriage,

03:43:34.960 --> 03:43:41.200
[Guest]: most people would not want it. Gay rights, most people may not want it. They may feel that this

03:43:41.200 --> 03:43:46.400
[Guest]: should be punishable. This should be, they want to. There are, in fact, people who are campaigning for

03:43:46.400 --> 03:43:52.160
[Guest]: getting rid of the right to marry, you know, inter-caste and so on. And I think about the

03:43:52.160 --> 03:43:57.360
[Guest]: change that has come about. You think about a film like Chameli Ki Shadi. Chameli Ki Shadi was

03:43:57.360 --> 03:44:02.000
[Guest]: made, I don't know, sometime in the 70s, probably. Or 80s, is it? I don't know. Sometime, you know.

03:44:02.000 --> 03:44:06.400
[Guest]: So it's that lovely film where you have, you know, Amjad Khan at the end being the lawyer.

03:44:06.400 --> 03:44:12.480
[Guest]: So there is this girl who has defied her parents and is marrying someone whom it is implied is a

03:44:12.480 --> 03:44:17.360
[Guest]: Dalit. Okay. So it is implied that he's from an oppressed caste or whatever. There's an

03:44:17.360 --> 03:44:22.880
[Guest]: inter-caste marriage happening, you know. And her parents come up and say, nahi yeh shadi nahi

03:44:22.880 --> 03:44:27.600
[Guest]: ho sakti kyunki humari beti hai, humne toh nahi haan diya. So Amjad Khan comes up and says, nahi,

03:44:27.600 --> 03:44:32.880
[Guest]: nahi, desh ka samvidhaan hai. Aur desh ka samvidhaan mein likha hua hai ki yeh toh balig

03:44:32.880 --> 03:44:38.160
[Guest]: ho gayi hai toh shadi hai. Kahan balig ho gayi hai? Woh toh abhi umar mein kam hai. This is exactly

03:44:38.160 --> 03:44:43.040
[Guest]: what happens all of today. And Amjad Khan says, aayiye toh madam. And he calls her school madam

03:44:43.040 --> 03:44:48.720
[Guest]: and he says, dekho school certificate mein jo umar likha hai, uske hesaap se yeh 18 saal se

03:44:48.720 --> 03:44:53.360
[Guest]: upar hai. So she's an adult. She can marry who the hell she likes. And they're like, what on earth?

03:44:53.360 --> 03:44:57.520
[Guest]: We didn't know this was the law. We didn't, you know, they're upset about it. And then he gets them

03:44:57.520 --> 03:45:03.520
[Guest]: around. The point is that a film like that could be made then. Could it be made now for a mass

03:45:03.520 --> 03:45:07.840
[Guest]: audience? I don't know. You could have it on Netflix, I'm sure. But the point is that today

03:45:07.840 --> 03:45:14.240
[Guest]: you're having a complete shift where, ironically, from the 90s onwards, the idea of people marrying

03:45:14.240 --> 03:45:19.520
[Guest]: for love, breaking, you know, defying parental, this thing and marrying for love, even if it's a

03:45:19.520 --> 03:45:26.480
[Guest]: tragic love, even if it's a Romeo and Juliet story, suddenly with the liberalization coming in,

03:45:26.480 --> 03:45:31.280
[Guest]: you simultaneously have a conservative streak where suddenly you have to ask parental permission

03:45:31.280 --> 03:45:38.080
[Guest]: for everything. Okay, with hum aapke hai kaun aur dil wale dulhani ale jaayenge. This whole thing

03:45:38.080 --> 03:45:45.200
[Guest]: about, you know, reimposing these ideas, you know, these are back in vogue. And now you have an

03:45:45.200 --> 03:45:50.880
[Guest]: entire, you know, political movement, which is in power today, which is determined to turn the

03:45:50.880 --> 03:45:57.520
[Guest]: clock on all this. And I insist on saying that, no, those youngsters who want to marry intercast

03:45:57.520 --> 03:46:03.200
[Guest]: are Indians. They are part of our society. They are not elite. You know, this is happening in

03:46:03.200 --> 03:46:08.560
[Guest]: Mofasils. This is happening in small towns. This is happening in villages. This is happening

03:46:08.560 --> 03:46:14.640
[Guest]: everywhere. And we are going to stand up for that India because that is an India that wants to come

03:46:14.640 --> 03:46:19.040
[Guest]: into being. And that's a far better version of the India that the RSS wants to bring into being or

03:46:19.040 --> 03:46:25.200
[Amit Varma]: that we had before the RSS also. That's both eloquent and passionate. And I agree with you

03:46:25.200 --> 03:46:30.800
[Amit Varma]: completely. And I have so many asides that I've been writing them down. I hope I don't kind of

03:46:30.800 --> 03:46:34.800
[Amit Varma]: forget something. First of all, I wouldn't blame it on liberalization. I'm not sure about that

03:46:34.800 --> 03:46:40.160
[Amit Varma]: causation. But we can leave that for another day. Secondly, you know, you had earlier mentioned not

03:46:40.160 --> 03:46:44.160
[Amit Varma]: standing for the anthem and you just mentioned being nonveg. So there's an anecdote I'll share

03:46:44.160 --> 03:46:49.680
[Amit Varma]: with you and my listeners that about 12 or 13 years ago, I was called as a panelist on Barkha

03:46:49.680 --> 03:46:56.080
[Amit Varma]: Dutt's TV show, We The People. And the subject was national symbols, because I had said that I

03:46:56.080 --> 03:47:00.640
[Amit Varma]: had blogged that I don't stand for the anthem and that we shouldn't take the flag so seriously and

03:47:00.640 --> 03:47:05.600
[Amit Varma]: all that. So they called me as a panelist and Smriti Irani was also there. So this would have

03:47:05.600 --> 03:47:11.520
[Amit Varma]: been around 2009. And at one point towards the end, Barkha went around asking all the panelists

03:47:11.520 --> 03:47:15.120
[Amit Varma]: that do you believe in sacred cows? And when she came to me and asked do you believe in sacred

03:47:15.120 --> 03:47:21.600
[Amit Varma]: cows? I said the only kind of sacred cow I like is a divine steak on my plate. And Smriti smiled

03:47:21.600 --> 03:47:27.200
[Amit Varma]: then but she was a little upset after the show about my insult there. The other thing I'd like

03:47:27.200 --> 03:47:32.480
[Amit Varma]: to point out is you mentioned free sex. And there is this very badass incident from a while ago,

03:47:32.480 --> 03:47:36.240
[Amit Varma]: where you were asked about free sex. Is it okay for women to have free sex and not just you but

03:47:36.240 --> 03:47:40.480
[Amit Varma]: also your mother said yes, we have free sex. It means consent. It's a good thing all sex should

03:47:40.480 --> 03:47:46.240
[Amit Varma]: be free. So, you know, much credit to you for saying that. That's, that's just wonderful.

03:47:46.240 --> 03:47:51.680
[Amit Varma]: What I also want to do is in the course of this, you know, four episodes I've done came to mind.

03:47:51.680 --> 03:47:56.000
[Amit Varma]: So I'll quickly plug them all for the listeners and have them in the show notes. One is with

03:47:56.000 --> 03:48:01.840
[Amit Varma]: Madhav but not Ram Madhav. It's with Madhav Khosla on the pedagogical aspect of the constitution,

03:48:01.840 --> 03:48:07.440
[Amit Varma]: exactly what you were talking about. And Madhav has written a fantastic book on and is very

03:48:07.440 --> 03:48:12.640
[Amit Varma]: eloquent, though I don't entirely agree with all of his arguments, because I think some of them go

03:48:12.640 --> 03:48:17.680
[Amit Varma]: too far in justifying some of the illiberalism of the constitution. But it is what it is fantastic

03:48:17.680 --> 03:48:23.600
[Amit Varma]: book. Madhav is a great scholar, again, Madhav Khosla, not Ram Madhav. Another episode I'd like

03:48:23.600 --> 03:48:27.920
[Amit Varma]: to recommend is by Tony Joseph, you know, early Indians, where he kind of points out that if you

03:48:27.920 --> 03:48:34.640
[Amit Varma]: look at the genetic evidence, you will find that till the year 0 BC or 0 AD or whatever it is that

03:48:34.640 --> 03:48:39.760
[Amit Varma]: turning point, India was there was a poverty happening here, as it were, you know, all the

03:48:39.760 --> 03:48:46.160
[Amit Varma]: different immigrants from all over were just having a party. And then one particular caste

03:48:46.160 --> 03:48:52.480
[Amit Varma]: based ideology from the Gangetic plain somehow gained dominance and endogamy became common,

03:48:52.480 --> 03:48:57.520
[Amit Varma]: which is why the Indian subcontinent when you look at it has often been described not as a large

03:48:57.520 --> 03:49:02.720
[Amit Varma]: population as the Han Chinese would be, but as a collection of many small populations. That's how

03:49:02.720 --> 03:49:08.800
[Amit Varma]: bad the caste endogamy kind of got, which you know, speaks to your point that India wasn't always

03:49:08.800 --> 03:49:13.600
[Amit Varma]: like this. We were a poverty culture once. And to underscore that I had an episode with Madhavi

03:49:13.600 --> 03:49:19.920
[Amit Varma]: Menon on the history of desire in India, where we speak in detail about the wild and libidinous

03:49:19.920 --> 03:49:25.760
[Amit Varma]: time our ancestors had. And just now you spoke about, you know, small towns, India that they

03:49:25.760 --> 03:49:30.320
[Amit Varma]: have aspirations, they want to be free. I'd done an episode with Sringda Poonam also on what young

03:49:30.320 --> 03:49:34.640
[Amit Varma]: people in small town India want. So all these things are there as far as Ambedkar is concerned.

03:49:34.640 --> 03:49:39.600
[Amit Varma]: Yeah, I agree. It's interesting that you know, this sense of go beyond the topsoil, you know,

03:49:39.600 --> 03:49:43.760
[Amit Varma]: change the culture was something that was one thing that Ambedkar and Gandhi could agree on.

03:49:44.960 --> 03:49:51.120
[Amit Varma]: Ambedkar in 1954, I think did also say that, given the state of what the Constitution had become,

03:49:51.120 --> 03:49:56.160
[Amit Varma]: he would like to burn it. And indeed, one of the problems with our Constitution is that as a

03:49:56.160 --> 03:50:00.720
[Amit Varma]: cartoonist once quipped, it's not a book, it's a periodical, they keep changing it regularly. And

03:50:00.720 --> 03:50:04.800
[Amit Varma]: another episode listeners can go and listen to is the one I did with Tripur Dhaman Singh on the

03:50:04.800 --> 03:50:10.000
[Amit Varma]: First Amendment, where it all started where, you know, one thing people don't realize is that yes,

03:50:10.000 --> 03:50:14.720
[Amit Varma]: the sedition law was there from British times, but it was ruled unconstitutional by an Indian

03:50:14.720 --> 03:50:19.040
[Amit Varma]: court in 1950. And then Nehru brought it back to deal with his political enemies, which just

03:50:19.040 --> 03:50:24.400
[Amit Varma]: shows that power does corrupt. And people do contain multitudes, that one can be both liberal

03:50:24.400 --> 03:50:30.000
[Amit Varma]: in one way and illiberal in another way. And finally, what you said is that all these laws

03:50:30.000 --> 03:50:34.480
[Amit Varma]: actually indicate that you know, these laws came into being when society was progressing. So people

03:50:34.480 --> 03:50:38.880
[Amit Varma]: felt the need to bring these laws to kind of control it. And I remember my friend Shruti

03:50:38.880 --> 03:50:43.200
[Amit Varma]: Rajagopalan wrote a controversial piece about this, where she said that, you know, if you look

03:50:43.200 --> 03:50:47.520
[Amit Varma]: at the love jihad laws, one way of looking at it is that there are more such marriages happening,

03:50:47.520 --> 03:50:51.280
[Amit Varma]: that's why the law was felt necessary. And unfortunately, on social media, that piece

03:50:51.280 --> 03:50:55.760
[Amit Varma]: whipped up a storm because everybody interpreted it as saying that she is for the love jihad laws,

03:50:55.760 --> 03:51:00.240
[Amit Varma]: which of course she is not, which she wrote in her piece. I did defend her in many places.

03:51:00.240 --> 03:51:05.200
[Amit Varma]: Yeah, I remember that. And it's an abominable law when she clarified that, take her at face value,

03:51:05.200 --> 03:51:09.200
[Guest]: it's in the article, but people just wanted to draw the conclusion. The caption, you know,

03:51:09.200 --> 03:51:12.800
[Amit Varma]: very often the captions misleading and people don't read anything about the caption. Yeah,

03:51:12.800 --> 03:51:16.240
[Amit Varma]: that's the problem. Yeah, people don't read anything. And I mean, I disagreed with the

03:51:16.240 --> 03:51:19.680
[Amit Varma]: argument in the sense that I think these people have been trying to do a love jihad law since

03:51:19.680 --> 03:51:24.000
[Guest]: the 1920s. Same here, I also disagreed with some of her arguments. But my point is, I said,

03:51:24.000 --> 03:51:28.800
[Amit Varma]: she's not saying that the love jihad law is a great thing. I mean, she's not finding an excuse

03:51:28.800 --> 03:51:33.760
[Amit Varma]: for it. She's not excusing it. Exactly. And social media mob kind of went after her. Now, finally,

03:51:33.760 --> 03:51:40.160
[Amit Varma]: leading on to sort of my next question. And this one came from, you know, you spoke in your first

03:51:40.160 --> 03:51:46.880
[Amit Varma]: chapter about this placard that you saw at that at the anti-rape protests of 2012. And this placard

03:51:46.880 --> 03:51:51.600
[Amit Varma]: said, quote, we live in a society that teaches women not to get raped instead of teaching men

03:51:51.600 --> 03:51:58.160
[Amit Varma]: not to rape, stop quote. And this reminded me of something Jackson Katz once said in a TED Talk,

03:51:58.160 --> 03:52:03.440
[Amit Varma]: which is a really important point about the use of language, which I'll quickly read out,

03:52:03.440 --> 03:52:08.240
[Amit Varma]: quote, we talked about how many women were raped last year, not about how many men raped women.

03:52:08.240 --> 03:52:11.840
[Amit Varma]: We talked about how many girls in a school district where Harris last year, not about how

03:52:11.840 --> 03:52:16.960
[Amit Varma]: many boys Harris girls. We talk about how many teenage girls got pregnant in the state of Vermont

03:52:16.960 --> 03:52:22.240
[Amit Varma]: last year, rather than how many men and teenage boys got girls pregnant. So you can see how this

03:52:22.240 --> 03:52:27.520
[Amit Varma]: use of the passive voice has a political effect. It shifts the focus of men and boys onto girls

03:52:27.520 --> 03:52:31.760
[Amit Varma]: and women. Even the term violence against women is problematic. It's a passive construction.

03:52:31.760 --> 03:52:36.560
[Amit Varma]: There's no active agent in the sentence. It's a bad thing that happens to women. It's a bad

03:52:36.560 --> 03:52:40.560
[Amit Varma]: thing that happens to women. But when you look at the term violence against women, no one is doing

03:52:40.560 --> 03:52:45.840
[Amit Varma]: it to them. It just happens. Men aren't even a part of it, stop quote. And my question here is

03:52:45.840 --> 03:52:55.040
[Amit Varma]: this that to what extent do you feel that more men are sort of looking inwards or looking at men as

03:52:55.680 --> 03:52:59.600
[Amit Varma]: you know, the crux of the problem, a lot of the solutions that people seem to come up with are

03:52:59.600 --> 03:53:04.560
[Amit Varma]: either these populist ones like Oh, hang the rapist and all that. Or it is that you know,

03:53:05.120 --> 03:53:10.320
[Amit Varma]: it is those, quote unquote, pragmatic arguments that women should not go out late and you know,

03:53:10.320 --> 03:53:15.040
[Amit Varma]: what was she wearing and all of that, you know, the onus going on the women and this kind of

03:53:15.040 --> 03:53:19.680
[Amit Varma]: brings me to the immediate peg. The reason I reached out to you is I saw your tweet about

03:53:19.680 --> 03:53:24.960
[Amit Varma]: the Tarun Tejpal judgment, which is a horrendous, horrendous judgment. And the whole judgment reads

03:53:24.960 --> 03:53:32.720
[Amit Varma]: like it was the survivor on trial, and not Tejpal. The onus was, again, suddenly on the woman. So

03:53:32.720 --> 03:53:39.360
[Guest]: what are your sort of thoughts on this? Yeah, so first, I mean, I was, there were several,

03:53:39.360 --> 03:53:44.560
[Guest]: several thoughts I was having. So I should have also put down my thoughts as you were speaking.

03:53:44.560 --> 03:53:49.600
[Guest]: So you may have to remind me a couple of things that you said. But one thing that occurred to me

03:53:49.600 --> 03:53:55.520
[Guest]: was before you spoke about the Tejpal judgment, about, you know, this whole thing about focusing

03:53:55.520 --> 03:54:03.440
[Guest]: on men, changing men's behavior, right? Changing the behavior of those who are committing violence.

03:54:03.440 --> 03:54:08.880
[Guest]: So my thoughts on that, on changing the conduct of not just men, but say, you know, anybody who

03:54:08.880 --> 03:54:13.360
[Guest]: behaves in a violent way. So lots of structural violence, you know, recognizing it's happening.

03:54:13.360 --> 03:54:18.800
[Guest]: So it's caste violence also, and all of that. How is this change going to happen? And because

03:54:18.800 --> 03:54:24.720
[Guest]: we were talking about the constitution and this whole pedagogic, whatever. One thing that really

03:54:24.720 --> 03:54:32.400
[Guest]: struck me last year was the Shaheen Baghs. Okay. What I felt was that I had for long been thinking

03:54:32.400 --> 03:54:38.960
[Guest]: that, you know, schools, ideally, if I had that kind of a power, then I would want schools to

03:54:38.960 --> 03:54:44.880
[Guest]: change the way, you know, for instance, we all have moral science or whatever. So instead of

03:54:44.880 --> 03:54:50.640
[Guest]: that, I would say teach constitutional morality. So constitutional morality in the Ambedkar sense,

03:54:50.640 --> 03:54:55.840
[Guest]: okay, in the, it's not just what is written in the constitution. It's precisely that concept,

03:54:55.840 --> 03:54:59.920
[Guest]: because I don't think anybody has a quarrel with that concept of constitutional morality,

03:54:59.920 --> 03:55:08.480
[Guest]: which is that the rights of the individual cannot be subservient to, you can't say that,

03:55:09.920 --> 03:55:15.440
[Guest]: all right, you're gay, but because the majority thinks that being gay is a crime,

03:55:16.240 --> 03:55:20.960
[Guest]: we'll keep it as a crime. No, you know, because that's the very essence of constitutional

03:55:20.960 --> 03:55:26.480
[Guest]: morality is that it cannot be a majoritarian morality, right? So there's a distinction

03:55:26.480 --> 03:55:32.800
[Guest]: between what society currently accepts as being moral, and what has to be a constitutional

03:55:32.800 --> 03:55:38.480
[Guest]: morality that we all agree to uphold, right? So I may not want to live my life in a certain way,

03:55:38.480 --> 03:55:46.000
[Guest]: okay? I may want to arrange marriage and so on and so forth. But I cannot have a right to endorse

03:55:46.000 --> 03:55:52.960
[Guest]: violence against somebody who wants to live their life as a single woman or, you know, live in with

03:55:52.960 --> 03:55:57.440
[Guest]: somebody or whatever it is, right? So this is what constitutional morality is about. So why can't

03:55:57.440 --> 03:56:01.760
[Guest]: schools teach constitutional morality? I used to keep thinking this, but I would often think about

03:56:01.760 --> 03:56:06.240
[Guest]: what would it look like in a classroom situation, you know, in the usual kind of school that we have,

03:56:06.240 --> 03:56:10.640
[Guest]: okay? And then when I saw the Shaheen bags, I felt like, all right, a class on constitutional

03:56:10.640 --> 03:56:17.680
[Guest]: morality should be held in a climate like this. So the idea should be to create a climate,

03:56:17.680 --> 03:56:25.440
[Guest]: you know, where there are diverse people who are feeling a sense of freedom to speak and freedom

03:56:25.440 --> 03:56:29.920
[Guest]: to argue with each other without being, you know, hit on the head with something telling them to

03:56:29.920 --> 03:56:35.360
[Guest]: shut up. And because I saw that happening, and I'm not talking just about what was happening on

03:56:35.360 --> 03:56:41.680
[Guest]: stage. So in the Shaheen bags off stage also, I was seeing, you know, parents bringing, Hindu

03:56:41.680 --> 03:56:48.160
[Guest]: parents bringing their kids to the Shaheen bags just to spend time there because they felt that

03:56:48.160 --> 03:56:55.760
[Guest]: there was hardly any other space where that child would be exposed to a variety of people,

03:56:55.760 --> 03:57:06.000
[Guest]: a variety of ideas, and, you know, to a sense of love for the constitution and the flag and the

03:57:06.000 --> 03:57:12.160
[Guest]: anthem that was not about standing at attention and, you know, it's not a military drill.

03:57:13.200 --> 03:57:17.520
[Guest]: You know, there's a sense of actual love in terms of what am I investing in it? I don't

03:57:17.520 --> 03:57:23.040
[Guest]: have to stand up for it or not. My point is, why do I love this? What do I love about it?

03:57:23.600 --> 03:57:29.520
[Guest]: And what do I disagree with in it? And how do I see my relationship with these things?

03:57:29.520 --> 03:57:35.840
[Guest]: Because I, you know, the country is me first, it's people. So how, what do we want to change

03:57:35.840 --> 03:57:41.360
[Guest]: about this country? And, you know, the culture that we love and all of that, because there's

03:57:41.360 --> 03:57:46.480
[Guest]: so much that we love here, even those of us who want to change a lot of things. There's so much

03:57:46.480 --> 03:57:51.520
[Guest]: that we will carry with us even, you know, wherever in the world we go, because these are

03:57:51.520 --> 03:57:55.760
[Guest]: things that are part of us and we love it because it is, you know, in a broad sense,

03:57:55.760 --> 03:58:00.720
[Guest]: you know, in a broad sense, Indian or whatever it is, right? So I think that is the kind of thing

03:58:00.720 --> 03:58:06.320
[Guest]: which I think of in terms of change. Okay. And the other thing, and even men, I mean,

03:58:06.320 --> 03:58:12.560
[Guest]: therefore, you know, exposing boys to, you know, ideas about consent. So in my opinion,

03:58:12.560 --> 03:58:17.520
[Guest]: even when people say we want to give safety lessons to women, okay, self-defense, I am all

03:58:17.520 --> 03:58:23.280
[Guest]: for self-defense. But I think I don't want to teach women that what Akshay Kumar does, which is

03:58:23.280 --> 03:58:28.480
[Guest]: to say, you can, you know, karate chop somebody and so, you know, you should be able to and I'll

03:58:28.480 --> 03:58:34.160
[Guest]: teach you how. No, you may be a wonderful karateka, but you may still get raped. You may still be

03:58:34.160 --> 03:58:39.920
[Guest]: raped. Somebody can rape you. You cannot prevent rape. You can't. You just can't because rape is

03:58:39.920 --> 03:58:44.800
[Guest]: not something which is only going to come as physical force. What if somebody you love and

03:58:44.800 --> 03:58:50.000
[Guest]: respect violates your boundaries and you are frozen at that point? That can happen to you,

03:58:50.000 --> 03:58:56.640
[Guest]: even if you're as strong as Mary Kom. Okay. So it isn't about, rape is not about that. It is about

03:58:56.640 --> 03:59:01.840
[Guest]: understanding consent. It is not about developing muscles or learning karate chops. But for all

03:59:01.840 --> 03:59:05.840
[Guest]: means, by all means, teach women, you know, physical, to be physically more confident.

03:59:05.840 --> 03:59:12.000
[Guest]: That's fine. But I think as a part of self-defense and a more important part of self-defense is

03:59:12.640 --> 03:59:18.480
[Guest]: accepting yourself, you know, which self are you going to defend? So teach women to defend,

03:59:18.480 --> 03:59:24.240
[Guest]: to love themselves, to accept themselves, to figure out what is their self as separate from

03:59:24.240 --> 03:59:29.280
[Guest]: what their parents want from them or what their boyfriend wants from them or whatever, right?

03:59:29.280 --> 03:59:33.280
[Guest]: Because I'm not saying, I mean, boyfriends can be just as oppressive as the parents. Okay. It's

03:59:33.280 --> 03:59:37.680
[Guest]: not always that you're, you know, running away with your boyfriend is necessarily going to make

03:59:37.680 --> 03:59:43.920
[Guest]: you freer. Okay. So Uma Chakraborty has this wonderful story about a girl whom they helped to,

03:59:43.920 --> 03:59:51.280
[Guest]: you know, defy her parents and marry this guy. And then once they were married,

03:59:51.280 --> 03:59:52.800
[Guest]: this guy would tell this girl,

04:00:02.160 --> 04:00:05.200
[Guest]: and, you know, you have to hear Uma Chakraborty say this actually, you know,

04:00:05.200 --> 04:00:09.680
[Guest]: because she says it with such outrage because she said, this is a girl who's gone,

04:00:09.680 --> 04:00:15.520
[Guest]: you know, she's had to, you know, leave behind so much and fight so much. You bloody haven't

04:00:15.520 --> 04:00:19.360
[Guest]: had to get rid of anything. And now she's with you and you're telling her you can't do this

04:00:19.360 --> 04:00:24.000
[Guest]: much only for me that you should now give up bits of your personality and your life.

04:00:24.000 --> 04:00:28.960
[Guest]: So of course, I mean, teaching women to respect themselves, teaching girls to respect themselves

04:00:28.960 --> 04:00:35.840
[Guest]: and to understand consent in terms of their right to draw boundaries, you know, even then you may

04:00:35.840 --> 04:00:40.720
[Guest]: not be protected from violence. But the point is, you at least will feel that if violence happens

04:00:40.720 --> 04:00:46.640
[Guest]: to you, you won't be the first to blame yourself. Because there'll be this voice in your head

04:00:46.640 --> 04:00:52.480
[Guest]: telling you, no, let me remember what I was taught, which is that I can draw this boundary.

04:00:53.360 --> 04:00:57.280
[Guest]: And I know that this is my boundary. But if somebody violates it, they're in the wrong.

04:00:58.000 --> 04:01:02.960
[Guest]: I can't be responsible for their violating that boundary. Just because I had a drink with them

04:01:02.960 --> 04:01:07.840
[Guest]: and happened to fall asleep, doesn't mean they had a right to assume I was available and to

04:01:08.480 --> 04:01:10.800
[Guest]: violate my boundary without my permission. No.

04:01:11.680 --> 04:01:16.560
[Amit Varma]: Fantastically inspiring words. I hope many young men and women sort of listen to this.

04:01:17.840 --> 04:01:22.160
[Guest]: Yeah. One more thing was which I wanted to say about men was that I wish that more men

04:01:22.160 --> 04:01:27.200
[Guest]: would speak to more boys. Because I feel that, well, I've spoken to a lot of young men and with

04:01:27.200 --> 04:01:34.880
[Guest]: very good results, I will assure you that I have been surprised on occasions by, if there were time

04:01:34.880 --> 04:01:40.480
[Guest]: I would narrate a fantastic story which happened to me on Rajya Sabha TV. But I've written about

04:01:40.480 --> 04:01:46.080
[Guest]: it on Facebook. So you can link it if you want. But it was fantastic in the sense in one sentence,

04:01:46.080 --> 04:01:51.760
[Guest]: what happened was that it was a debate on marital rape. And the two male panelists marched out in

04:01:51.760 --> 04:01:56.480
[Guest]: a rage because they were angry with what I was saying and another women panelist was saying.

04:01:56.480 --> 04:02:02.240
[Guest]: And the person running the show, there was an audience. So it had a lot of young men in it.

04:02:02.240 --> 04:02:06.080
[Guest]: And they were clapping for those guys. And we thought they were supporting those guys.

04:02:06.080 --> 04:02:10.400
[Guest]: When those guys left, the poor woman conducting the show thought, okay, the show is dead.

04:02:11.280 --> 04:02:18.240
[Guest]: But then I told her to just check. And so she asked the audience, what do you feel? And suddenly

04:02:18.240 --> 04:02:24.080
[Guest]: we realized that the majority of the men there are against the exemption for marital rape.

04:02:24.080 --> 04:02:28.880
[Guest]: So this lady asked them, but why were you clapping for those guys?

04:02:28.880 --> 04:02:33.440
[Guest]: They said, we didn't know how to show our opposition because we are sitting in the show.

04:02:33.440 --> 04:02:38.960
[Guest]: So how to make a noise? Toh hum toh unko mazaak mein kar rahe the unko to taunt them.

04:02:38.960 --> 04:02:42.480
[Guest]: So the problem is I've noticed this on other occasions also that people don't know,

04:02:42.480 --> 04:02:46.400
[Guest]: you know, the idea of clapping, it can happen when something very sad is said,

04:02:46.400 --> 04:02:50.880
[Guest]: when something outrageous is said, you know, clapping is your way of saying, okay, I noticed

04:02:50.880 --> 04:02:55.200
[Guest]: this and you know, how ridiculous also sometimes. So it turned out that most of those young men

04:02:55.200 --> 04:02:59.920
[Guest]: were saying, we're disgusted by the idea that the law says that if I marry my wife,

04:02:59.920 --> 04:03:03.040
[Guest]: then I have a right to her whether she likes it or not, you know.

04:03:03.040 --> 04:03:07.200
[Guest]: So I was very reassured by that, frankly, and I believe, but I wish a lot of more men

04:03:07.840 --> 04:03:13.280
[Guest]: would take it on themselves in a systematic way, you know, to talk to more young boys about

04:03:13.840 --> 04:03:14.880
[Guest]: respecting consent.

04:03:16.800 --> 04:03:20.800
[Amit Varma]: So that's a wonderful story. Maybe there's a preference cascade already happening in

04:03:20.800 --> 04:03:24.800
[Amit Varma]: this great advice from you. And as I was saying, I hope a lot of young women and men both,

04:03:24.800 --> 04:03:28.480
[Amit Varma]: you know, get inspired by your words and read your book, I actually wanted to discuss your book

04:03:28.480 --> 04:03:32.560
[Amit Varma]: chapter by chapter is so full of insights and all of that, but I won't do that. I think I've

04:03:32.560 --> 04:03:38.160
[Amit Varma]: taken enough time. So one final, longish question, which is, you know, I've been meaning to invite

04:03:38.160 --> 04:03:42.880
[Amit Varma]: you for the longest time to this show, I've admired your work and your writing. And it's

04:03:42.880 --> 04:03:48.720
[Amit Varma]: really sort of the Tarun Tejpal thread that kind of got me down to it, because I was just absolutely

04:03:48.720 --> 04:03:53.120
[Amit Varma]: disgusted for a number of reasons. I mean, he was acquitted of a crime that he had basically

04:03:53.120 --> 04:03:58.480
[Amit Varma]: confessed to, he had, you know, in his confession letter, in fact, he had sort of shown that

04:03:58.480 --> 04:04:02.640
[Amit Varma]: attitude of treating women as a property of men when he offered to apologize, apologize to the

04:04:02.640 --> 04:04:06.560
[Amit Varma]: boyfriend of the survivor, you know, if you remember, which is bizarre, and you've written

04:04:06.560 --> 04:04:11.360
[Amit Varma]: a wonderful sort of dissection of the judgment, which I just came across this morning, which I

04:04:11.360 --> 04:04:15.760
[Amit Varma]: linked from the show notes. And that says everything. And in the past, also, you've

04:04:15.760 --> 04:04:20.640
[Amit Varma]: written about, say, someone like Mahmood Farooqui, who was first convicted and then acquitted by a

04:04:20.640 --> 04:04:25.040
[Amit Varma]: higher court on the grounds of what is famously known as a feeble no, where the judge said that

04:04:25.040 --> 04:04:29.440
[Amit Varma]: the woman had said no, they accepted that, but they said, you know, it could be a feeble no,

04:04:29.440 --> 04:04:34.240
[Amit Varma]: who is to say why why is a poor man to blame? Shocking, but what shocks me more than just these

04:04:34.240 --> 04:04:40.240
[Amit Varma]: judgments, by now you have the new rape laws in effect that were done after 2012. And all of that,

04:04:40.240 --> 04:04:45.520
[Amit Varma]: so the laws are in place, the judgment is horrible, the Tejpal judgment, in fact, was by a lady judge.

04:04:45.520 --> 04:04:50.880
[Amit Varma]: So one, you have the law, letting these guys get away with with the shocking sort of reasoning.

04:04:50.880 --> 04:04:54.800
[Amit Varma]: And two, these guys are going to be rehabilitated. You and I know that, you know, Farooqui was at

04:04:54.800 --> 04:04:59.600
[Amit Varma]: JLF this year. Next year, I won't be surprised if Tejpal is also there. I mean, I honestly don't

04:04:59.600 --> 04:05:05.840
[Amit Varma]: know what the freaking organizers are thinking. It's just absurd. And you actually have these,

04:05:05.840 --> 04:05:10.960
[Amit Varma]: you know, cabals of Delhi liberals who are who are on their side. So my question here is this that

04:05:10.960 --> 04:05:15.520
[Amit Varma]: given all of this, you know, at one step, it would seem that it's two steps forward and

04:05:15.520 --> 04:05:20.800
[Amit Varma]: or four steps forward, three steps back is perhaps more like it. And I'd find reason for hope in the

04:05:20.800 --> 04:05:25.200
[Amit Varma]: fact that in exactly the anecdote that you described at that show where all these men are

04:05:25.200 --> 04:05:31.600
[Amit Varma]: kind of clapping that, you know, possibly there's a lot of silent people out there who may not speak

04:05:31.600 --> 04:05:36.400
[Amit Varma]: up now but who realize that there are others like them who are, you know, who feel the same way and

04:05:36.400 --> 04:05:40.080
[Amit Varma]: a lot of people who may, you know, listen to you or read you and they may change your mind. So that

04:05:40.080 --> 04:05:44.240
[Amit Varma]: makes me kind of hopeful. But at the same time, you look at these judgments, you look at what's

04:05:44.240 --> 04:05:49.920
[Amit Varma]: going on and the way the country is descending in all kinds of different ways. It also makes us

04:05:49.920 --> 04:05:54.560
[Amit Varma]: despair. So looking ahead, looking say 20 years ahead, what makes you hope and what makes you

04:05:54.560 --> 04:06:01.920
[Guest]: despair? So what makes me hope is I think that I feel that the backlash we are seeing now in these

04:06:01.920 --> 04:06:08.080
[Guest]: judgments also or in the love jihad laws or whatever it is, I feel that that is more of a

04:06:08.080 --> 04:06:14.400
[Guest]: backlash of the privileged who are, you know, banding together either in a very organized way

04:06:14.400 --> 04:06:21.840
[Guest]: with the RSS and the BJP, but even I would say across party lines, you know, in order to basically

04:06:22.560 --> 04:06:27.120
[Guest]: band together to push back against some kind of feminist assertion. Okay, so what you're seeing

04:06:27.120 --> 04:06:32.800
[Guest]: in the Tejpal Faruqi kind of context, and I can tell you something that the BJP kind of trolling,

04:06:32.800 --> 04:06:38.160
[Guest]: Sangeet trolling has never bothered me very much. Some of the worst trolling I have received and

04:06:38.160 --> 04:06:43.920
[Guest]: which has really, really troubled me and given me sleepless nights has been the trolling by friends,

04:06:43.920 --> 04:06:50.720
[Guest]: by those I would consider on our side on these two judgments, these two cases. Okay, so Tejpal

04:06:50.720 --> 04:06:56.320
[Guest]: Faruqi, both cases. Horrible. I mean, really very, very disturbing the kind of things that have been

04:06:56.320 --> 04:07:02.400
[Guest]: said and said not only about the survivors, but about us. My only thing which I just wanted to

04:07:02.400 --> 04:07:07.280
[Guest]: say before I get on to, you know, what makes me hopeful, I just want to say since you mentioned

04:07:07.280 --> 04:07:12.880
[Guest]: those judgments at length, I just wanted to clarify one thing. You see, I am at the end of

04:07:12.880 --> 04:07:19.360
[Guest]: the day, I'm not someone who is just out for, you know, punish, punish, punish, punish. That's not my

04:07:20.000 --> 04:07:24.800
[Guest]: concern. Okay, how much punishment also is my least concern. I do not, I'm not talking about

04:07:24.800 --> 04:07:30.640
[Guest]: severity of punishment. Frankly, I'm not, you know, I engage with the law only to try and make

04:07:30.640 --> 04:07:36.320
[Guest]: sure that it's, it's, it doesn't become the worst law possible. Even in 2012-13, my only fear was

04:07:36.320 --> 04:07:41.280
[Guest]: that they would bring in all kinds of horrible things and how to prevent them from so doing. Okay,

04:07:41.840 --> 04:07:49.760
[Guest]: so that was more of the effort. My point is that I am all for, I will not quarrel with an acquittal.

04:07:50.400 --> 04:07:55.920
[Guest]: If the acquittal is on the grounds that, look, whatever evidence is being brought here,

04:07:55.920 --> 04:08:01.280
[Guest]: we are not able to make it add up to say that beyond reasonable doubt, this must have happened.

04:08:01.840 --> 04:08:07.280
[Guest]: So while we acknowledge, I'm saying even in the Tejpal case, okay, he wrote these letters,

04:08:07.280 --> 04:08:12.080
[Guest]: all right. But suppose, you know, for a minute, you forget that this is Tejpal and forget that

04:08:12.080 --> 04:08:16.720
[Guest]: it is these particular letters and what the letters content is. Imagine some other case.

04:08:17.680 --> 04:08:24.560
[Guest]: I would say that, you know, suppose somebody writes letters and is asked to write letters

04:08:24.560 --> 04:08:31.360
[Guest]: by an institution, he writes them, and then there is a court case and so on. I would say that perhaps

04:08:31.360 --> 04:08:37.120
[Guest]: he is within his rights, his defense is within his rights to say, look, you know, you obtain these

04:08:37.120 --> 04:08:44.160
[Guest]: confessions as a form of punishment. And now you are using them, you know, for another punishment

04:08:44.160 --> 04:08:49.280
[Guest]: in another forum. So don't you think this is wrong or whatever? Okay, so in another case,

04:08:49.280 --> 04:08:53.440
[Guest]: I'm not talking about the Tejpal case right now, but I'm saying that I can imagine that being an

04:08:53.440 --> 04:08:59.600
[Guest]: argument. So on any grounds, if the judge were to conclude that, you know, evidence doesn't meet up,

04:08:59.600 --> 04:09:06.320
[Guest]: therefore I'm acquitting, I'll say fine. I'm not going to, you know, I would not feel particularly

04:09:06.320 --> 04:09:11.360
[Guest]: bothered by that. I think what botherss me about both the Tejpal acquittal and the Farooqi's High

04:09:11.360 --> 04:09:18.960
[Guest]: Court acquittal was what was said in order to do this, which is that you are basically saying that

04:09:18.960 --> 04:09:26.800
[Guest]: you are setting absurd standards which no woman can ever match up to. You know, it's hard enough

04:09:26.800 --> 04:09:32.560
[Guest]: for a woman to actually say no. You're conveying no with everything in your body and you're this

04:09:32.560 --> 04:09:38.000
[Guest]: thing. The law does not, the letter of the law does not say you have to say no. The letter of

04:09:38.000 --> 04:09:44.720
[Guest]: the law says that the man should not proceed unless, you know, by word or gestures as a yes.

04:09:44.720 --> 04:09:50.720
[Guest]: Okay, so the point is that, but most men who violate these rules and every woman I can tell

04:09:50.720 --> 04:09:55.600
[Guest]: you has an experience of this, everyone. I don't know anybody who doesn't, okay. They may not have

04:09:55.600 --> 04:10:01.760
[Guest]: complained, they may not have, everybody including me. We have experiences of people violating our

04:10:01.760 --> 04:10:07.760
[Guest]: boundaries and telling themselves that we are consenting. No matter how often, it's like you're

04:10:07.760 --> 04:10:13.440
[Guest]: talking to, okay, in one instance that I recall in my own experience. Here I am continuously,

04:10:13.440 --> 04:10:19.680
[Guest]: you know, twisting my body, making it stiff. No, the guy still thinks it's okay to, you know,

04:10:19.680 --> 04:10:25.120
[Guest]: pat and touch and whatnot. And then it goes further. Guy starts sending love letters and whatnot.

04:10:25.120 --> 04:10:32.080
[Guest]: I'm replying over and over saying politely that I respect you, but I'm not interested in any of

04:10:32.080 --> 04:10:37.520
[Guest]: this. I don't feel for you at all this way. I'm not interested. Guy takes my respect your statement

04:10:37.520 --> 04:10:42.160
[Guest]: to say, I realize that you're in love with me, but this will be a secret between us. And I'm like,

04:10:42.160 --> 04:10:46.800
[Guest]: where did I say this? I didn't say it. So the point is the guy who was doing the violating

04:10:46.800 --> 04:10:53.600
[Guest]: doesn't respect my agency. He is constructing a, you know, he may be telling himself that I'm

04:10:53.600 --> 04:10:58.400
[Guest]: consenting. Maybe he's lying to himself also. But that doesn't mean that the onus is on me to make

04:10:58.400 --> 04:11:03.120
[Guest]: him understand it. The point is, if I've said no, let him kindly accept. And if there's a doubt,

04:11:03.120 --> 04:11:07.840
[Guest]: then give me the benefit of doubt. Say that I'm going to back off until I'm sure that there's this

04:11:07.840 --> 04:11:13.040
[Guest]: heavy enthusiastic yes happening. So it's as simple as that. But the point is, these judgments

04:11:13.040 --> 04:11:17.840
[Guest]: don't do that. These judgments set absurd standards. What does feeble know? How is she

04:11:17.840 --> 04:11:23.680
[Guest]: supposed to scream no? How loud should that decibel be? What is this thing of saying how

04:11:23.680 --> 04:11:29.920
[Guest]: should a normative victim behave? And as my piece says, I'm not going to the details. I'll just say

04:11:29.920 --> 04:11:37.040
[Guest]: that my piece elaborates on, it takes down the idea which some of Tejpal's friends are saying,

04:11:37.040 --> 04:11:42.560
[Guest]: which is that no, no, ignore the misogyny bit. That bit may be wrong, but substantially there

04:11:42.560 --> 04:11:48.000
[Guest]: are facts which have been brought forward that prove the, you know, complainant to be lying.

04:11:48.640 --> 04:11:54.880
[Guest]: No, there aren't. And that's what my piece takes down because, in fact, what the judge is doing is

04:11:54.880 --> 04:12:01.280
[Guest]: she's accepting Tejpal's letters as fact, conveniently when she wants to. And she's

04:12:01.280 --> 04:12:08.800
[Guest]: using those facts. She's in a sense saying, guy says that you didn't complain and you didn't cry.

04:12:09.600 --> 04:12:13.120
[Guest]: So you're lying when you said you complained and you cried and there was an incident.

04:12:13.120 --> 04:12:17.040
[Guest]: Now, how can this kind of reasoning, you know, in the face of this reasoning, no fair trial is

04:12:17.040 --> 04:12:22.720
[Guest]: ever possible. No woman can ever hope to be believed, right? So this is what I want everyone

04:12:22.720 --> 04:12:29.200
[Guest]: to think about there. As for hope, even in these very, very bleak times, I feel that the hope comes

04:12:29.200 --> 04:12:35.120
[Guest]: from those who are fighting back against these things, the ones who are trying to say, what

04:12:35.120 --> 04:12:43.440
[Guest]: values do we stand for? Do we decide on a matter of rape? Do we decide where we stand based on who

04:12:43.440 --> 04:12:48.960
[Guest]: is accused and who is the survivor? What is their community? What is their politics? Or do we decide

04:12:48.960 --> 04:12:54.400
[Guest]: that even if it is one of our friends, one of our own who is violating, you know, consent, that's

04:12:54.400 --> 04:13:01.840
[Guest]: wrong. Do we decide that, okay, the consensus in, you know, those who are triumphant today, those

04:13:01.840 --> 04:13:07.760
[Guest]: who are, you know, claiming to be all powerful today are telling us that interreligious marriage

04:13:07.760 --> 04:13:13.600
[Guest]: is wrong or that, you know, the Muslims do not have a right to be, you know, their citizenship

04:13:13.600 --> 04:13:19.440
[Guest]: should be in doubt. We should have a right to, you know, the state should have a right to reject or

04:13:19.440 --> 04:13:25.120
[Guest]: accept them as citizens. They have to throw their citizenship in doubt, you know. Are there people

04:13:25.120 --> 04:13:30.240
[Guest]: who are willing to fight back, who are willing to say, no, no, no, no, no. Democracy is not about

04:13:30.240 --> 04:13:36.560
[Guest]: just accepting every law that is passed. Democracy is about every citizen questioning the government

04:13:36.560 --> 04:13:42.320
[Guest]: and speaking up even at risk to themselves. I think there's a lot of that happening and there's

04:13:42.320 --> 04:13:47.920
[Guest]: enough of it happening to give me hope. I am deeply pained by the thought of the young women

04:13:47.920 --> 04:13:54.400
[Guest]: who are in jail today. You know, what's the lawyer's name, Tushar Mehta, on the Tejpal case,

04:13:54.400 --> 04:14:00.560
[Guest]: when he's arguing in high court, he's saying, oh my God, I'm a feminist and why is it wrong to be

04:14:00.560 --> 04:14:05.440
[Guest]: a feminist and all of that. And I thought to myself when I read that report yesterday in the

04:14:05.440 --> 04:14:10.480
[Guest]: paper that he's defending, you know, he's questioning the Tejpal acquittal and in the

04:14:10.480 --> 04:14:15.200
[Guest]: appeal he's saying, why are feminists being attacked and even I'm a feminist. I feel like

04:14:15.200 --> 04:14:21.440
[Guest]: if I were to meet him, I would ask him, your government that you are defending is locking up

04:14:21.440 --> 04:14:26.640
[Guest]: feminists, locking up a young woman like Natasha, not even allowing her to meet her father,

04:14:27.200 --> 04:14:33.280
[Guest]: you know, who died without his daughter being able to meet him. How terrible is that? Natasha,

04:14:33.280 --> 04:14:38.080
[Guest]: Devangana, Sudha Bharadwaj, you know, these people, the thought of them being in prison today

04:14:38.080 --> 04:14:44.880
[Guest]: bothers me. But I also get hope from the fact that they are taking this risk for our country.

04:14:44.880 --> 04:14:52.000
[Guest]: They are taking this risk to try and defend the values that should be giving us hope. And so,

04:14:52.000 --> 04:14:57.840
[Guest]: I feel that in this pandemic times, I feel that although the suffering has been so terrible,

04:14:58.480 --> 04:15:06.160
[Guest]: the fact that people helped themselves, formed communities of help, irrespective of caste and

04:15:06.160 --> 04:15:11.760
[Guest]: community and all of that, helped each other, helped each other to try and live,

04:15:11.760 --> 04:15:17.200
[Guest]: helped each other to breathe, helped each other, you know, to have dignity in death.

04:15:18.560 --> 04:15:22.960
[Guest]: Somehow, I feel that if we draw upon even that very deep grief and sorrow,

04:15:23.760 --> 04:15:27.440
[Guest]: that would be truly a positive thing. I'm not talking about, you know, this negativity,

04:15:27.440 --> 04:15:32.640
[Guest]: positivity, all this government is trying to tell us, not saying that. I genuinely feel that the

04:15:32.640 --> 04:15:40.080
[Guest]: most positive thing that we can do as citizens is to draw hope from that deep collective grief

04:15:40.080 --> 04:15:46.960
[Guest]: and to say that if we find a way, find our way back as a society of caring for each other,

04:15:46.960 --> 04:15:53.680
[Guest]: mourning those who have died, not just those who died of COVID and of oxygen shortage,

04:15:53.680 --> 04:15:58.320
[Guest]: but those who died in last year's lockdown, migrant workers, those who died because of

04:15:58.320 --> 04:16:02.480
[Guest]: lynching, those who died because of medical care, those who died because of lack of food,

04:16:03.280 --> 04:16:08.160
[Guest]: all these things, if we find a way back trying to figure out how to care for each other,

04:16:08.160 --> 04:16:15.920
[Guest]: care for each other, I think from there you will, I hope for a new politics, a new political

04:16:15.920 --> 04:16:23.280
[Guest]: awakening and somehow a society that finds the courage and the moral value, the moral strength

04:16:23.280 --> 04:16:28.080
[Guest]: to actually take us to a better place than the terrible place we are in today.

04:16:29.360 --> 04:16:33.440
[Amit Varma]: Very wise words. And you mentioned Natasha Narwal and I was just heartbroken by that

04:16:33.440 --> 04:16:37.520
